{"title_page": "Shrewsbury School", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=December 2019}}\n{{About-distinguish2|the independent King Edward VI school|[[Shrewsbury High School, Shropshire|Shrewsbury High School]] or [[Shrewsbury Academy]]}}\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2010}}\n{{Infobox school\n | name                    = Shrewsbury School<br />{{small|King Edward VI School at Shrewsbury}}\n | logo                    = Shrewsbury School COA.svg\n | logo_size               = 120\n | image                   = Shrewsbury School 1.JPG\n | caption                 = The school's current main building from 1882\n | coordinates             = {{coord|52.7038|-2.7622|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dec|display=inline,title}}\n | motto                   = [[Latin]]: ''Intus Si Recte Ne Labora''<br />\n | established             = 1552<ref name=\"ofsted\">[http://www.ofstedgov.com/oxcare_reports/download/(id)/218681/(as)/SC020779_SC.pdf Ofsted Social Care report 2008.] Retrieved 19 March 2010</ref>\n | closed                  = \n | type                    = [[Public school (United Kingdom)|Public school]] <br />[[Independent school (United Kingdom)|Independent]] <br />[[day school|day]] and boarding school\n | religious_affiliation   = [[Church of England]]\n | president               = \n | head_label              = Headmaster\n | head                    = Leo Winkley\n | chair_label             = Chairman of Governing Body\n | chair                   = James Pitt<ref>{{cite web |title=Trustees |date=3 June 2015 |url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/trustees |publisher=Shrewsbury School |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref>\n | founder                 = [[Edward VI of England|King Edward VI]]\n | specialist              = \n | motto_translation       = If Right Within, Trouble Not\n | address                 = Kingsland\n | city                    = [[Shrewsbury]]\n | county                  = [[Shropshire]]\n | country                 = England\n | postcode                = SY3 7BA\n | local_authority         = [[Shropshire Council]]\n | urn                     = 123608\n | ofsted                  = \n | staff                   = ca. 120\n | enrolment               = ca. 800\n | gender                  = Co-educational (from 2015)\n | lower_age               = 13\n | upper_age               = 18\n | houses                  = 13\n | colours                 = Royal blue and white\n | publication             = ''The Salopian''\n | free_label_1            = Former pupils\n | free_1                  = [[List of Old Salopians|Old Salopians]]\n | free_label_2            = School Song\n | free_2                  = ''Carmen Salopiense''\n | website                 = {{URL|https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/|www.shrewsbury.org.uk}}\n | module                  = {{Infobox mapframe\n| stroke-color = #C60C30\n| stroke-width  = 3\n| marker        = school\n| marker-color = #1F2F57\n| zoom          = 13}}\n}}\n'''Shrewsbury School''' is an English [[Independent school (United Kingdom)|independent]] boarding school for pupils aged 13 to 18 in [[Shrewsbury]], Shropshire.  It was founded by [[Edward VI]] in 1552 by a [[Royal Charter]].<ref name=\"ofsted\" /> \n\nShrewsbury is one of the original seven [[Public school (United Kingdom)|public schools]] as defined by the [[Public Schools Act 1868]], and one of the 'great' nine identified by the [[Clarendon Commission]] of 1861. It was originally a boarding school for boys; girls have been admitted into the Sixth Form since 2008 and has been co-educational since 2015. There are approximately 130-day pupils.<ref name=\"isi report\">[http://www.isi.net/HistoricalReports/0992_07.htm Independent Schools Inspectorate report 2007] Retrieved 19 March 2010</ref> \n\nThe present site, to which the school moved in 1882, is on the banks of the [[River Severn]].<ref name=\"ofsted\" />\n\nThe school's alumni \u2013 or \"[[Old Salopians]]\" \u2013 include naturalists, poets, academics, politicians, authors, sportsmen, actors, and military figures.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Edward VI swagger.jpg|alt=King Edward VI, founder of Shrewsbury School|left|thumb|[[Edward VI of England|King Edward VI]], founder of Shrewsbury School ]]\n\n=== Foundation and Early Years ===\nShrewsbury School was founded by charter in 1552 under [[Edward VI of England|King Edward VI]], following a petition in 1542 to [[Henry VIII]] from the townspeople of Shrewsbury for a free grammar school.  \n\nThe school began operation in three rented wooden buildings, which included Riggs Hall, built in 1450, and now the only remaining part of the original foundation. \n\nThe early curriculum was based on Continental [[Calvinism]], under its first headmaster, [[Thomas Ashton (schoolmaster)|Thomas Ashton]] (appointed 1561) and boys were taught the catechism of [[John Calvin|Calvin]]. The school attracted large numbers of pupils from Protestant families in Shrewsbury, Shropshire and North Wales, with 266 boys on its roll at the end of 1562.<ref name=\"odnb\">{{cite book|title=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, Volume 2|year=2004|publisher=Oxford University Press|page=684|isbn=0-19-861352-0}}Article on Thomas Ashton by Martin R. Speight.</ref> Early pupils lodged with local families; [[Philip Sidney|Sir Philip Sidney]] did so with [[George Leigh (MP)|George Leigh]], Member of Parliament for [[Shrewsbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Shrewsbury]]. \n\nHaving achieved a reputation for excellence under Ashton, in 1571 the school was augmented by [[Elizabeth I of England|Queen Elizabeth I]].  \n\nAlthough Ashton had resigned from his headmastership in 1568, he returned to Shrewsbury in 1578 to help draw up the ordinances governing the school, which were in force until 1798; under them, the borough bailiffs (mayors after 1638) had power to appoint masters, with Ashton's old [[St John's College, Cambridge]] having an academic veto.<ref name=\"odnb2\">{{cite book|title=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, Volume 2|pages=684\u2013685}}</ref> Shrewsbury has retained links with the College, with the continued appointment of Johnian academics to the Governing Body, and the historic awarding of 'closed' Shrewsbury Exhibitions.<ref>{{cite web | title=Governing Body Members' Details |date= 20 December 2012 |url= http://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/governing-body-members-details | publisher=Shrewsbury School|accessdate=4 May 2018}}</ref>[[File:Shrewsbury Library 2017.jpg|alt=|left|thumb|The school's original building now serves as Shrewsbury's town library]]\n\nThe stone buildings on Castle Gates, including a chapel, dormitories, library and classrooms were completed by 1630, with the Ashton's successor,  John Meighen, founding a [[chained library]] in 1606,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/features/school-history|title=School History|date=2011-03-28|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>  though the library had begun making acquisitions by 1596, with a terrestrial globe by the first English globe maker [[Emery Molyneux|Emery Molineux]] being its first acquisition.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/ancient-taylor-library|title=The Ancient ('Taylor') Library|date=2011-03-28|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>  \n\n[[File:Shrewsbury Library 06.jpg|thumb|Early graffiti in the former school building|alt=|left]]A house was also built for the school in 1617 in the nearby village of [[Grinshill]] as a retreat in times of plague.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Nicolle, Dorothy.|title=Shrewsbury|date=2013|publisher=History|isbn=978-0-7524-8270-5|location=Stroud|oclc=841908132}}</ref><ref>{{NHLE|num=1055426|desc=STONE GRANGE, Grinshill |accessdate=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nThe school's original Castle Gates premises had little in way of provision for games. Under Dr Butler, there were two bat{{clarify|date=August 2018}} fives courts and playgrounds in front of and behind the buildings, but after the arrival of Dr Kennedy football was permitted, for which the school acquired a ground in Coton Hill (north of Castle Gates).<ref name=\"shrewslib\" /> \n\nThe school continued in these buildings, until it was relocated in 1882.  At this time, the original premises were converted to a public [[Shrewsbury Library|Free Library and Museum]] by the Shrewsbury Borough Council, opening in their new role in 1885; <ref>{{cite work|author=Beryl Copsey|title=Read All About It! Grand Opening of Shrewsbury's free library 100 years ago|work=The Shropshire Magazine|date=April 1985|page=18{{ndash}}19}}</ref> over the course of the 20th century the library purpose gradually took over the whole building, to which major restoration was done in 1983.<ref>A plaque erected by The [[Rotary Club]] of Shrewsbury, commemorating the club's 60th anniversary in 1985, reads: ''Castle Gates Library erected by Edward VI in 1552, Shrewsbury School occupied this site until 1882. The stone buildings were built 1594{{ndash}}1630. Judge Jefferys and Charles Darwin were educated here. Re-opened as a library in 1983 after complete renovation.''</ref><ref name=\"shrewslib\">{{cite book|title=Shrewsbury Library, Its History and Restoration|year=1983|publisher=Shropshire Libraries|isbn=0-903802-26-0}}(Unpaginated)</ref>\n\nIn 1798, a specific Act of Parliament, The Shrewsbury School Act, was passed for the better government of the school.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Raby, Peter.|title=Samuel Butler : a biography|date=1991|publisher=University of Iowa Press|isbn=0-87745-331-4|edition=1st|location=Iowa City|oclc=24031298}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Butier|first=Samuel II|url=https://books.google.com/?id=48taAAAAcAAJ&pg=RA1-PA15&lpg=RA1-PA15&dq=1798+shrewsbury+school+act+bill#v=onepage|title=A letter to Henry Brougham on certains clauses in the education bills now before Parliament|publisher=W. Eddowes|year=1820|isbn=|location=Shrewsbury|pages=15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=The House of Commons|first=Order of|date=1803|title=Journals of the House of Commons|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Y2FIAQAAMAAJ&dq=1798+shrewsbury+school+act+bill|journal=Journals of the House of Commons|volume=53|pages=702|via=}}</ref> The [[Court of Chancery|Court of Chanclery]] in 1853 later amended this scheme.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Shrosbree, Colin.|title=Public schools and private education : the Clarendon Commission, 1861-64, and the Public Schools acts|date=1988|publisher=Manchester University Press|isbn=0-7190-2580-X|location=Manchester, UK|oclc=17807648}}</ref>\n\n=== 1800s ===\n[[File:Benjamin Hall Kennedy, by Walter William Ouless.jpg|thumb|right|[[Benjamin Hall Kennedy]], headmaster of Shrewsbury for thirty years, from 1836 to 1866.]]The school had just three headmasters during the 19th century.  \n\n[[Samuel Butler (schoolmaster)|Samuel Butler]] was appointed headmaster in 1798, and the school's reputation, which had receded from the [[English Civil War|Civil War]], again grew.<ref name=\"ButlerDNB\">{{cite DNB|wstitle=Butler, Samuel (1774\u20131839)|last=Lee|first=Sidney|authorlink=Sidney Lee|volume=8}}</ref>\n\nButler was succeeded by his pupil [[Benjamin Hall Kennedy]] (of ''Latin Primer'' fame) in 1836,<ref name=\"ButlerDNB\" /> who in turn gave way to [[Henry Whitehead Moss]] in 1866. \n\nUnder Butler and Kennedy, Shrewsbury was one of three provincial schools among the nine studied by the [[Clarendon Commission]] of 1861\u201364 (the schools considered being [[Eton College|Eton]], [[Charterhouse School|Charterhouse]], [[Harrow School|Harrow]], [[Rugby School|Rugby]], [[Westminster School|Westminster]], and [[Winchester College|Winchester]], and two day schools: [[St Paul's School (London)|St Paul's]] and [[Merchant Taylors' School, Northwood|Merchant Taylors]]).<ref>Stray, Christopher (2005)'' Histories of the Nine Clarendon Schools: v. 1'' Thoemmes Continuum  {{ISBN|1-84371-108-7}}, {{ISBN|978-1-84371-108-7}}.</ref> Shrewsbury went on to be included in the Public School's Act 1868, which ultimately related only to the boarding schools.\n\nIn 1882, Moss moved the school from its original town centre location to a new site of {{convert|150|acre|ha}} in Kingsland (an area of land which at one time belonged to the Crown and granted to the Corporation at \u201ca rather remote period, the exact date of which appears not to be known\u201d, but apparently before 1180<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kingslandshrewsburyshorthistory.wordpress.com/landownership/|title=Landownership|date=2015-02-16|website=Kingsland, Shrewsbury|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>), on the south bank of the [[River Severn]] overlooking the town. A legacy of this move can be seen in the school premises being referred to as \"The Site\".   \n\nThe school was set up in the current Main School Building which dates from 1765 and had at different times housed a [[foundling hospital]] and the Shrewsbury [[workhouse]], before translating to this current use.  In order to meet this new purpose, it was remodelled by [[Arthur Blomfield|Sir Arthur Blomfield]] (whose other educational commissions include and [[Marlborough College]] and [[Lady Margaret Hall, Oxford]]).    \n\nBloomfiled also designed School House, to the east of the Main School building which was constructed during the 1880s.<ref>{{NHLE|num=1271348|desc=SHREWSBURY SCHOOL, SCHOOL HOUSE, Shrewsbury |accessdate=2020-04-14}}</ref>  The new Riggs Hall (which had existed from Tudor buildings at the old site<ref>{{NHLE|num=1246750|desc=RIGGS HALL RIGGS HALL, TO REAR OF LIBRARY, Shrewsbury |accessdate=2020-04-15}}</ref>) was also built at this time,<ref>{{NHLE|num=1271377|desc=SHREWSBURY SCHOOL, RIGG'S HALL, Shrewsbury |accessdate=2020-04-15}}</ref> as was Churchill's Hall<ref>{{NHLE|num=1271343|desc=SHREWSBURY SCHOOL, CHURCHILL'S HALL, Shrewsbury |accessdate=2020-04-15}}</ref> and Moser's Hall<ref>{{NHLE|num=1246401|desc=SHREWSBURY SCHOOL, MOSER'S HALL, Shrewsbury |accessdate=2020-04-15}}</ref>: these buildings are the work of [[William White (architect)|William White]].  [[File:Shrewsbury School 2.JPG|thumb|The school's current chapel, built in 1887|alt=]]A [[Gothic architecture|gothic]] chapel was built for the school (also by Blomfield) in 1887.  Its south and east windows are by [[Charles Eamer Kempe|Kempe]], employing medieval narrative style for lives of saints, scenes from the history of the school.<ref>{{NHLE|num=1271376|desc=SHREWSBURY SCHOOL CHAPEL, Shrewsbury |accessdate=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nOther buildings have since grown up around the edge of the site, with sports pitches in the centre, with diverse buildings being added to the new site over the last 130 years.\n\n=== 1900s ===\nMoss was succeeded in 1908 by [[Cyril Alington]], then Master in College at [[Eton College|Eton]]. Alington, though a Fellow of All Souls College, Oxford, was a sportsman, evidenced by the 1914 appointment as his secretary of [[Neville Cardus]], the future cricket journalist who had joined the school in 1912 as the school's assistant cricket professional. \n\nAt the time of his appointment as Headmaster, Alington was younger than any of the masters on the staff, so to bring in new blood into the teaching staff, he recruited several former Collegers from Eton, most notably [[Ronald Knox|The Rev. Ronald Knox]]. Alington wrote the school song and commissioned its flag (a [[banner of arms]] of its coat of arms)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/features/school-song|title=School song|date=2011-03-28|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>, and he was an energetic builder; the school Alington Hall (assembly hall) is named after him.  In December 1914 he wrote a poem, \"To The School at War\" {{NoteTag|\"To the School at War\n<br>\nWe don\u2019t forget \u2013 while in this dark December\n<br>\nWe sit in schoolrooms that you know so well,\n<br>\nAnd hear the sounds that you so well remember \u2013\n<br>\nThe clock, the hurrying feet, the Chapel bell:\n<br>\nOthers are sitting in the seats you sat in;\n<br>\nThere\u2019s nothing else seems altered here \u2013 and yet\n<br>\nThrough all of it, the same old Greek and Latin,\n<br>\n    You know we don\u2019t forget.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\nWe don\u2019t forget you \u2013 in the wintry weather\n<br>\nYou man the trench or tramp the frozen snow;\n<br>\nWe play the games we used to play together\n<br>\nIn days of peace that seem so long ago;\n<br>\nBut through it all, the shouting and the cheering,\n<br>\nThose other hosts in graver conflict met,\n<br>\nThose other sadder sounds your ears are hearing\n<br>\n    Be sure we don\u2019t forget.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\nAnd you, our brothers, who for all our praying,\n<br>\nTo this dear school of ours come back no more,\n<br>\nWho lie, our country\u2019s debt of honour paying \u2013\n<br>\nAnd not in vain \u2013 upon the Belgian shore;\n<br>\nTill that great day when at the Throne in Heaven\n<br>\nThe books are opened and the Judgment set,\n<br>\nYour lives for honour and for England given\n<br>\n    The School will not forget..\"<ref>{{cite book |first=Noakes |last=Vivien  |authorlink= |title=Voices of silence : the alternative book of First World War poetry  |year=2006 |publisher=Stroud, Gloucestershire: Sutton|oclc=71239052 }}</ref>}} , which was published in''[[The Times]]''.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Voices of silence : the alternative book of First World War poetry|date=2006|publisher=Sutton Pub|others=Noakes, Vivien, 1937-2011.|isbn=978-0-7509-4521-9|location=Stroud, Gloucestershire|oclc=71239052}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/school-will-not-forget|title=To the School at War|date=2014-09-04|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> After leaving Shrewsbury, Alington went on to serve as  [[Chaplain to the King]] to [[George V|King George V]] from 1921 until 1933, and then [[Dean of Durham]], from 1933 to 1951.  He appeared on the cover of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine on 29 June 1931. \"An accomplished classicist, a witty writer especially of light verse, and a priest of orthodox convictions ...\"<ref>{{Cite book|last=Pfaff|first=R.W.|title=Montague Rhodes James|publisher=Scolar Press|year=1980|isbn=|location=London|pages=260}}</ref> \n\nDuring the Edwardian period Oldham's Hall was built (1911).<ref>{{NHLE|num=1246451|desc=SHREWSBURY SCHOOL, OLDHAM'S HALL, Shrewsbury |accessdate=2020-04-14}}</ref> The current library building was added in 1916.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/library|title=Library|date=2011-03-28|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nMountaineer [[Andrew Irvine (mountaineer)|Andrew Irvine]], who, with [[George Mallory]] may have reached the summit of [[Mount Everest]] in the [[1924 British Mount Everest expedition|1924 British Everest Expedition]] attended Shrewsbury during the First World War.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/central/2013-05-29/midlanders-who-tackled-mount-everest/|title=Midlanders who tackled Mount Everest|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>  During the 1920s the Georgian villa houses at Severn Hill<ref>{{NHLE|num=1270651|desc=SEVERN HILL, Shrewsbury |accessdate=2020-04-15}}</ref> and Ridgemount<ref>{{NHLE|num=1254704|desc=RIDGEMOUNT, Shrewsbury |accessdate=2020-04-15}}</ref> were acquired by the school and adapted into boarding houses.  Severn Hill, the linear decedent of the house of which Irvine was captain, holds his ice axe from the expedition, discovered in 1933 by Wyn Harris.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/news/2015/04/11/shropshire-everest-victims-story-to-be-told-in-new-film/|title=Shropshire Everest victim's story to be told in new film|website=www.shropshirestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==== First World War and afterwards ====\nThe [[World War I|First World War]] saw 321 former members of the school die serving their country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/osww1|title=\"The School will not forget\" - Old Salopians in WW1|date=2014-08-26|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>  A war memorial was added to the school in 1923 for these fallen.<ref>{{NHLE|num=1246402|desc=WAR MEMORIAL AT SHREWSBURY SCHOOL, Shrewsbury |accessdate=2020-04-14}}</ref>  This memorail was added to after the [[World War II|Second World War]] to include the 135 members of the school who fell in that conflict.  The monument contains a statue of [[Philip Sidney|Sir Phillip Sidney]], the Elizabeth soldier, poet and courtier who himself was a former member of the school and died of wounds sustained at the [[Battle of Zutphen]] in 1597, and it faces the Main School building down an avenue of [[Tilia|linden]] trees, known as 'central'.   \n\n==== Post Second World War ====\nBetween 1944 and 1950 [[John Wolfenden, Baron Wolfenden|John Wolfenden]] (later Lord Wolfenden) was headmaster; he left Shrewsbury to become [[Vice-Chancellor]] of the [[University of Reading]].  He was appointed to various public body chairmanships by the [[Privy council|Privy Council]], and also went on to be director of the [[British Museum]].  His name is closely associated with the government-instituted  [[Wolfenden report|Wolfenden Report]], which he chaired.     \n\nIn 1952, the school was 400 years old.  It received a royal visit to mark the occasion, and presented the town with a new cross for the historic site of the town's High Cross (which had been removed in 1705) at the termination of the market street which was a starting point for civic and religious processions in the medieval town and a significant location (the place of execution of [[Earl of Worcester]] and others after the [[Battle of Shrewsbury]] in 1403, and of [[Dafydd ap Gruffydd|Dafydd III]], last native [[Prince of Wales]] in 1283) <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://search.shropshirehistory.org.uk/collections/getrecord/CCS_MSA1131/|title=Shropshire's History Advanced Search {{!}} Shropshire's History Advanced Search|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>. \n\nThe future [[Deputy Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Deputy Prime Minister]] of the UK [[Michael Heseltine]] attended the school immediately after the Second World War on  scholarship. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/pictures/2008/04/26/famous-salopians-part-two/|title=Famous Salopians - Part Two|website=www.shropshirestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> A number of the founders and writers of the satirical magazine [[Private Eye]] attended the school in the 1950s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/news/features/2019/07/06/private-eye-founder-dies-at-81/|title=Private Eye founder and former Shrewsbury School pupil Christopher Booker dies at 81|last=Neal|first=Toby|website=www.shropshirestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>  [[Willie Rushton|Willy Rushton]] was also at the school at this time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/pictures/2008/04/26/famous-salopians-part-two/|title=Famous Salopians - Part Two|website=www.shropshirestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>  The comedian, actor, writer and television presenter [[Michael Palin|Micheal Pailin]] of [[Monty Python's Flying Circus]] attended the school shortly afterwards and a scholarship is now available named for him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/news/education/2016/07/23/michael-palin-scholarship-launched-by-shrewsbury-school/|title=Michael Palin scholarship launched by Shrewsbury School|website=www.shropshirestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nBetween 1963 and [[Donald Wright (schoolmaster)|Donald Wright]] served as headmaster. ''[[The Times]]'' has called Wright a \"great reforming headmaster\". While there, working with the [[Anglican Diocese of Liverpool]], Wright took a leading role in the building of a new Shrewsbury House, the school's mission in [[Liverpool]], which was opened in 1974 by [[Anne, Princess Royal|Princess Anne]]. He secured many leading churchmen to come to preach in the school chapel, including [[Donald Coggan]], [[Archbishop of Canterbury]]. After retiring as a headmaster in 1975, Wright became the Archbishop of Canterbury's Patronage Secretary, chaired the William Temple Foundation, and served as Secretary to the [[Appointment of Church of England bishops|Crown Appointments Commission]].\n\nIn the 1960s, Kindgland House, another C19th gentleman's residence was acquired by the school and adapted for use for central catering for all pupils (previously food had been arranged in houses).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/101270614-kingsland-house-shrewsbury|title=Kingsland House, Shrewsbury, Shropshire|last=Stuff|first=Good|website=britishlistedbuildings.co.uk|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n[[Eric Anderson (teacher)|Sir Eric Anderson]] served as headmaster between 1975 and 1980.  He went on to be Rector of [[Lincoln College, Oxford]], chairman of the [[National Lottery Heritage Fund|Heritage Lottery Fund]] and [[Provost of Eton]], among other roles.  \n\nIn 1988, another Georgian villa house, the Grove, was bought and adapted for use as boarding house.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/event/30-years-grove|title=30 Years of the Grove|date=2018-06-22|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n=== 2000s ===\n[[File:Shrewsbury School 4.JPG|alt=|thumb|To mark the turn of the Millennium, Shrewsbury unveiled a monument of an old boy, [[Charles Darwin]].]]\nSince the turn of the millennium, the school's site has seen investment, beginning with the addition of a statue of alumnus Charles Darwin being added to the site to mark the millennial, which was unveiled by [[David Attenborough|Sir David Attenborough]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://statues.vanderkrogt.net/object.php?webpage=ST&record=gbwm018|title=Shrewsbury - Charles Darwin|website=statues.vanderkrogt.net|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>  \n\nA new music school, The Maidment Building, was opened by [[Prince Charles|HRH Prince Charles]] in 2001.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tes.co.uk/jobDetailsBronze_schoolInfo.aspx?ac=2961750&qry=parametrics%3DJOBCATEGORYCODE%7C10635%2CJOBCATEGORYCODE%7C10804%26PageNo%3D1&rslt=3&cur=3&UK=true|title=Shrewsbury School|work=TES|accessdate=21 April 2011}}</ref> \n\nA new boarding house has been completed (2006)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bhn.co.uk/boarding-house-shrewsbury-school|title=Shrewsbury School Boarding House - Mary Sidney Hall|website=www.bhn.co.uk|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>, as has a indoor cricket centre (2006)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/gmr-cricket-centre|title=GMR Cricket Centre|date=2017-07-28|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> and a new swimming pool (2007)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/swimming-pool|title=Swimming Pool|date=2017-07-28|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>.\n\nGirls were admitted to the school for the first time into the sixth-form in 2008, and the school became fully coeducational in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/news/education/2011/09/19/girls-given-go-ahead-to-join-shrewsbury-school/|title=Girls given go-ahead to join Shrewsbury School|website=www.shropshirestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012 the rowing facilities  was extend with a new Yale Boat house, which was opened by Olympian [[Matt Langridge]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishrowing.org/2012/10/langridge-launches-shrewsbury-boathouse/|title=Langridge launches Shrewsbury boathouse|date=2012-10-10|website=British Rowing|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>  A new Computing and Design faculty building, \"the Chatri Design Centre\" was established in 2017, re-purposing and redeveloping a former humanities building.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bhn.co.uk/chatri-design-centre-shrewsbury-school|title=Shrewsbury School - Chatri Design Centre|website=www.bhn.co.uk|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> In 2015 a new building, Hodgeson Hall, was built to house the 5 humanities departments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://adrianjames.com/project/shrewsbury-school/|title=Hodgson Hall: Shrewsbury School - Education Project - Adrian James Architects Oxford|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nThe addition of a new theater was announced in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/news/local-hubs/shrewsbury/2018/09/05/new-plans-for-school-theatre/|title=New plans for school theatre|last=Reynolds|first=Jordan|website=www.shropshirestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessleader.co.uk/shropshire-firm-lands-2-3m-refurbishment-for-shrewsbury-school/68682/|title=Shropshire firm lands \u00a32.3m refurbishment for Shrewsbury School {{!}} Business Leader News|date=2019-06-11|website=Business Leader|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\n==Sports==\nThe main sport in the Michaelmas (autumn) term is football, in the Lent term [[fives]] and rugby, and in summer cricket. Rowing takes place in all three terms. The kit of many of the sports teams shows a cross from the crown in the school's coat of arms, which is a practice that has been in place for sports teams for at least 150 years. For a period in the mid to late C20th, this [[cross patt\u00e9e]] (often mislabelled [[Maltese cross]]) was used solely by the school\u2019s boatclub. \n\nAdmission of girls in 2015 has seen the introduction of field hockey, netball and lacrosse, with cricket and tennis played during the summer term.\n\nThe present school buildings in Kingsland are arranged around the sports fields which have nine grass football pitches and one of [[Astroturf]]; almost all boys play football in the [[Michaelmas term]].<ref name=\"football\">{{cite web|url=http://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/football|title=Football|year=2011|publisher=Shrewsbury School}}</ref>\n=== Football ===\nSalopians were prominent in the early history of the organised game at [[Cambridge University]], according to Adrian Harvey \"Salopians formed a club of their own in the late 1830s/early 1840s but that was presumably absorbed by the [[Cambridge University A.F.C.|Cambridge University Football Club]] that they were so influential in creating in 1846\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Harvey|first=Adrian|title=Football: The first hundred years|publisher=Routledge|year=2005|page=251}}</ref> The school has an 1856 copy of the [[Cambridge rules]] of football, predating the 1863 rules of [[The Football Association|the FA]].  \n\nThis is in contrast to the resistance to football in the earliest years of the 1800s (paralleled at other public schools at the time), with the school authorities deeming football \"only fit for butchers boys\"<ref>{{Cite book|last=Shephard, Roy J.,|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/1005231187|title=A history of health & fitness : implications for policy today|isbn=978-3-319-65097-5|location=Cham, Switzerland|oclc=1005231187}}</ref>.  A embryonic version of football, which was called Douling (deriving its name from the Greek word for slave), was permitted and encouraged by Kennedy from 1830, and it became a valued part of the school's program<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://footballbh.net/2019/02/23/shrewsbury-school-douling-rules-old-boys/|title=Shrewsbury School part two: Douling, football's slavery|date=2019-02-23|website=Football Bloody Hell|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>, so much so that:  ''\u201cTo miss doulings was unwise, the recognised punishment being a \u2018kicking.\u2019 In 1870 J. Craig brought an action for assault against his house captain, Henry Wace, after he had received a kicking for going skating when he should have been Douling. The case was dismissed.\u201d'' [[File:School Boathouse Shrewsbury (20960693446).jpg|alt=|thumb|Shrewsbury School viewed from [[The Quarry (park)|The Quarry]], with the school's boathouse in the foreground.]]\n\n=== Rowing ===\nTh Royal Shrewsbury School Boat Club (RSSBC) is one of the oldest school rowing clubs, having been founded in 1866. \n\nSince the boat club began rowing at [[Henley Royal Regatta]] in 1912, they have won 14 times. Shrewsbury is only seconded in victories at [[Henley Royal Regatta|Henley]] to Eton, having won specifically:\n\n* Elsenham Cup:\u00a01919\u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0\n* Princess Elizabeth Challenge Cup: 1955, 1957, 1960, 1961, 2007\n* Ladies\u2019 Challenge Plate Winner: 1932\n* Special Race for Schools/Fawley Challenge Cup: 1975,1976, 1980, 1981, 1982, 1984, 1985<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/henley|title=Henley|date=2011-03-28|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Royal Shrewsbury School Boat Club Rowing Blade.svg|alt=Royal Shrewsbury School Boat Club Rowing Blade|thumb|Royal Shrewsbury School Boat Club Rowing Blade, this cross emblem is commonly used by sports teams, and has been for around 150 years, but for a period was reserved for the first VIII.  This arrangement is also used as the flag of the boat club, while other sports use the school's banner of arms]]\nShrewsbury is one of only two public schools to have [[bumps race]]s, the other being [[Eton College|Eton]], between the houses. They are rowed over four evenings at the end of term in July. There are usually three boats entered per house. On the fourth evening there are prizes for the leaders of the chart and the Leadbitter Cup for the boat which has made the most bumps over the four nights. The event is marshalled by senior rowers and rowing prefects, usually masters. The crew training is mainly pupil driven, though in preparation for [[Henley Royal Regatta|Henley]] the school's First VIII rowers often do not take part, and therefore the boats are composed of other rowers and some non-rowers. Previously, races were run every day until there were no more bumps (i.e. until they were nominally in speed order). This historical set-up could lead to weeks of racing and it was therefore abandoned in favour of a four-day version more than 100 years ago. Otherwise, it is only [[Oxford University|Oxford]] and [[Cambridge University|Cambridge]] that continue to have bumps. Shrewsbury and Eton both race bumps in fours whilst Oxford and Cambridge race in eights.\n\n=== Running ===\nThe Royal Shrewsbury School Hunt (RSSH or \"the Hunt\") is the oldest cross-country club in the world, with written records (the Hound Books) going back to 1831 and evidence that it was established by 1819.<ref name=\"Robinson\">{{cite journal|last=Robinson|first=Roger|date=December 1998|title=On the Scent of History|journal=Running Times|page=28}}</ref> The sport of \"the Hunt\" or \"the Hounds\", now known as a [[Paper Chase (game)|Paper Chase]], was formalised at the school around 1800. Two runners (the \"foxes\") made a trail with paper shreds and after a set time they would be pursued by the other runners (the \"hounds\"). The club officers are the Huntsman and Senior and Junior Whips. The hounds start most races paired into \"couples\" as in real [[fox hunting]]; the winner of a race is said to \"kill\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/history-tucks|title=History of The Tucks|year=2011|publisher=Shrewsbury School}}</ref> In his 1903 semi-autobiographical novel ''[[The Way of All Flesh]]'', Old Salopian [[Samuel Butler (novelist)|Samuel Butler]] describes a school based on Shrewsbury where the main protagonist's favourite recreation is running with \"the Hounds\" so \"a run of six or seven miles across country was no more than he was used to\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Butler|first=Samuel|title=The Way of All Flesh|title-link=The Way of All Flesh|publisher=Project Gutenberg|year=1903|chapter=39|authorlink=Samuel Butler (novelist)|chapter-url=http://www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/2084}}</ref> The first definite record of the Annual Steeplechase is in 1834, making it the oldest cross-country race of the modern era.<ref name=\"Robinson\" /> The main inter-house cross-country races are still called the Junior and Senior Paperchase, although no paper is dropped and urban development means the historical course can no longer be followed. Every October the whole school participates in a 3.5-mile run called \"The Tucks\", originally intended to prevent pupils attending a local horse race.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/tucks|title=The Tucks|year=2011|publisher=Shrewsbury School}}</ref> The school also lays claim to the oldest [[track and field]] meeting still in existence, which originated in the Second Spring Meeting first documented in 1840. This featured a series of mock horse races including the Derby Stakes, the Hurdle Race, the Trial Stakes and a programme of throwing and jumping events, with runners being entered by \"owners\" and named as though they were horses.<ref name=\"Robinson\" />\n\n=== Cricket ===\nCricket was being played at Shrewsbury at least as long ago as the 1860s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/news/nostalgia/2018/09/15/did-photographer-call-out-cricketer-with-dirty-pads/|title=Did photographer call out Shrewsbury School cricketer with dirty pads?|last=Neal|first=Toby|website=www.shropshirestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> A reference was made to an effort to set up a game with Westminster School in 1866 (declined by Westminster) in a House of Commons debate by [[Jim Prior]] in 1961.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/commons/1961/jun/16/public-schools-entry|title=PUBLIC SCHOOLS (ENTRY) (Hansard, 16 June 1961)|website=api.parliament.uk|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\n=== Eton Fives ===\n[[Eton Fives]] is major sport within the school and it has 14 Fives courts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/fives|title=Fives|date=2011-03-28|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> \n\n=== Minor Sports ===\nMinor sports include: shooting, fencing, basketball, golf, equestrian, badminton, swimming and squash.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/other-participation-sports|title=Other (Participation) Sports|date=2013-11-08|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==Houses==\nThe School, as of Michaelmas Term 2020, has 807 pupils: 544 boys and 263 girls. There are eight boys' boarding houses, four girls' boarding houses and two for day pupils, each with its own housemaster or housemistress, tutor team and matron. Each house also has its own colours. \n\nA single house will hold around 60 pupils, although School House and each of the dayboy houses hold slightly more. Having about 90 pupils, School House used to be divided into Doctors (black and white) and Headroom (magenta and white) for most sporting purposes, whilst being one house in other respects, but this distinction was abolished in around 2000.\n\nThere are many inter-house competitions: in football, for instance, each house competes in four different leagues (two senior, two junior) and three knock-out competitions (two senior, one junior). \n\nThe houses and their colours are:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!House!!Colours!!&nbsp;!!Notes\n|-\n|Churchill's Hall|| Dark Blue & Light Blue|| Richard Hudson||{{small|Opened in 1882, listed building}}\n|-\n|The Grove|| Cornflower Blue and White ||Clare Wilson||{{small|Converted to girls' house in summer 2014}}\n|-\n|Ingram's Hall ||Green & White||Sam Griffiths||\n|-\n|Moser's Hall|| Deep Red & Black|| Jane Pattenden ||{{small|Opened in 1884, listed building}}\n|-\n|Oldham's Hall|| Chocolate Brown & White ||Henry Exham||{{small|Opened in 1911, listed building}}\n|-\n|Port Hill || Gold & Red|| Andy Barnard|| rowspan=\"2\" |{{small|Formerly merged as Dayboys Hall}}\n|-\n|Radbrook ||Violet & White|| Richard Case\n|-\n|Ridgemount ||Royal Blue & Old Gold|| William Hughes ||{{small|Opened in 1926, listed building}}\n|-\n|Rigg's Hall|| Chocolate & Gold|| Matthew Barrett||{{small|Opened in 1882, listed building}}\n|-\n|School House|| Black, Magenta & White|| Morgan Bird||\n|-\n|Severn Hill || Maroon & French Grey ||Adam Duncan||{{small|Formerly known as Chances}}\n|-\n|Mary Sidney Hall|| Dark Blue & Pink ||Anita Wyatt ||{{small|Opened in September 2008}}\n|-\n|Emma Darwin Hall ||Wedgwood Blue & Green ||William Reynolds||{{small|Opened in September 2011}}\n|}\n\n==Royal Visits ==\nThe following royal visits have been made to Shrewsbury School:\n\n*[[Princess Louise, Duchess of Argyll|Princess Louise]], visited the school for coffee on 19 January 1898. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/3273211/3273215/79/lorne|title=PRINCESS- LOUISE AT SHREWSBURY. '-{{!}}1898-01-20{{!}}Evening Express - Welsh Newspapers|website=newspapers.library.wales|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n* The future [[Edward VIII]], then [[Prince of Wales]], visited in 1932 the  to celebrate the Jubilee of the school's move to the Kingsland site.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://volunteeringshropshiresheritage.wordpress.com/2013/11/15/20th-century-royal-visitors-to-shrewsbury/|title=20th Century Royal Visitors to Shrewsbury|date=2013-11-15|website=volunteeringshropshiresheritage|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n*[[George V]] visited the town of Shrewsbury, and he laid a foundation at the school for a new library by electrical switch from the town's square. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://player.bfi.org.uk/free/film/watch-the-kings-visit-to-the-royal-agricultural-show-shrewsbury-1914-online|title=Watch The King's Visit to the Royal Agricultural Show, Shrewsbury|website=BFI Player|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n*[[Elizabeth II|HM The Queen]] and [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|HRH The Duke of Edinburgh]] visited the school to celebrate its 400 year anniversary of foundation in 1952.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zV4JtRuek8U|title=Video of the Visit of HM The Queen in 1952|last=|first=|date=|website=British Movietone|url-status=live|archive-url=|archivedate=|accessdate=}}</ref>\n*[[Princess Royal|The Princess Royal]] opened the new Shrewsbury School Club, called the Shewsy, in Everton in1974.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/queens-visit-shrewsbury-1952|title=The Queen's visit to Shrewsbury in 1952|date=2012-05-09|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\u00a0\n*[[Princess Margaret, Countess of Snowdon|Princess Margaret]], in 1984, while officially visiting a new library in the town, lunched at the school and had a look at the new Art school.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n*[[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother|The Queen Mother]] came to Kingsland Hall during the headmastership of Donald Wright in the 1990s.<ref name=\":0\" />\u00a0\n*[[Charles, Prince of Wales|The Prince of Wales]] opened the new music school in 2001.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/news/2018/11/14/charles-at-70-we-remember-princes-visits-to-shropshire/|title=Charles at 70: We remember prince's visits to Shropshire and Mid Wales|last=Andrews|first=Mark|website=www.shropshirestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n==Coat of arms and flag==\nThe Arms of the school are those of [[King Edward VI]] being The Arms of England (three lions passant) quartered with those of France (fleur-de-lys).<ref>[http://www.victorianweb.org/victorian/history/education/shrewsburyseal.html \"Shrewsbury School coat of arms\"], The Victorian Web.</ref>\n\nAs a [[banner of arms]], this is also used as the school's flag. \n\n== Grants and prizes ==\nThe school awards a number of prizes, some of which have been running for many years, among these are:\n\n*'''The Sidney Gold Medal''', established 1838, The top award Shrewsbury offers, it originally came with a purse of 50 sovereigns as was awarded to the top classicist going on to [[Oxbridge]]. The Trustees commissioned Sir Edward Thomason to cut the original die and the image was based on a miniature painted by [[George Perfect Harding]] and owned by Dr Kennedy, now in the School collection.\u00a0 The medal was discontinued in 1855 when the stocks were exhausted, but was revived again in 1899.\u00a0 In 1980 the Salopian Club decided that the Medal should be open to all disciplines and not purely the Classics.\u00a0 Since that time the majority of recipients have excelled in the sciences.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/news/sidney-gold-medal-shrewsburys-top-academic-prize|title=The Sidney Gold Medal - Shrewsbury's top academic prize|date=2012-10-15|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n*'''The Arand Haggar Prize''', established 1890, original known as \u201cThe Mathematics Prize\u201d, an almost unbroken run of the annual competition paper stretches back in our archives to 1890. This makes it, possibly, one of the longest continually run mathematics competitions in the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/news/arnold-hagger-mathematics-prize-0|title=The Arnold Hagger Mathematics Prize|date=2019-03-29|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n*'''The Bentley Elocution Prize''', established 1867, candidates are required recite well a poem of at least [[sonnet]] length, introduced by Thomas Bentley, whose career at the School spanned more than 50 years. Past winners include Michael Palin<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/news/bentley-elocution-prizes|title=Bentley Elocution Prizes|date=2013-04-18|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n*'''[[Richard Hillary]] Essay Prize''', established 2013, modled on the single word essay formula used for admission for [[All Souls College, Oxford|All Souls, Oxford]]<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n*'''The Miles Clark Travel Award''', established 1994, recipients of this award have, for instance, cycled around the world for over four years; cycled back to the UK from Siberia, cycled by tandem from the north coast of [[Canada]] to [[Tierra del Fuego]] - anumber of accounts of these travels have been published=.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/miles-clark-travel-scholarship|title=The Miles Clark Travel Scholarship Fund|date=2012-04-24|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n== Societies and speakers  ==\nThere are dozens of organisations known as 'societies', in many of which pupils come together to discuss a particular topic or to [[File:Footpath through Shrewsbury School grounds - geograph.org.uk - 1470032.jpg|thumb|right|The school's site is intersected by shaded paths]]listen to a lecture, presided over by a senior pupil, and often including a guest speaker, they are largely run by the students.\n\nThose in existence at present include: \n\n* Archery\n* Art & Photography \n* Bastille Society (history)\n* Beekeeping\n* Canoe and Kayak Club\n* Chinese \n* Christian Forum\n* Coding \n* Comedy \n* Cooking\n* Craft and Textiles Club\n* Darwin Society (Science)\n* Debating Society\n* Drama\n* French\n* Junior History Society\n* Maths Club\n* Mindfulness \n* Model Railway Society\n* Paired Reading Society (students visit a local primary school, where they work with younger children on a one-to-one basis in order to help develop their reading skills).\n* Pilates\n* Quizzing \n* Reading\n* Royal Shrewsbury School Shooting Club\n* Sidney Society (literature)\n* Spanish Society\n* STEM \n* Technical Theatre\n\nThere is also a [[Combined Cadet Force]]. \n\nAmong past guest speakers include \n\n* [[William Hague|Lord Hague]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/news/lord-hague-reasons-be-optimistic|title=Lord Hague's 'Reasons to be Optimistic'|date=2020-02-14|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n* [[Michael Heseltine|Lord Heseltine]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/e-newsletter/180202|title=eNewsletter: Friday 2nd February 2018|date=2018-02-01|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n* [[Peter Hennessy|Lord Hennessy]], \n* [[Brian Hutton, Baron Hutton|Lord Hutton]], \n* [[Douglas Hurd|Lord Hurd]], \n* [[Oleg Gordievsky]],\n* [[Colin McColl|Sir Colin McColl]], \n* [[Aidan Hartley]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/news/bastille-society-lectures-0|title=Bastille Society Lectures|date=2020-03-11|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> \n\n== Music and Drama  ==\n\n=== Orchestras, ensembles and Choirs ===\nThe school has the following orchestras ensembles and choirs<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/ensembles-and-choirs|title=Ensembles and Choirs|date=2011-05-09|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>: \n\n* The Symphony Orchestra;\n* The Wind Orchestra;\n* Big Ban;\n* The Pepys Brass Quintet (one of two brass quintets run for the best senior brass players in the school);\n* The Senior Brass Ensemble\n* The Senior String Ensemble \n* The Chamber Choir\n* The Chapel Choir\n* The Community Choir (includes local members who are not part of the school)\n* Jazz Band\n* String quartets\n* Junior and Senior string ensembles\n* Clarinet and sax groups\n* Year-based brass groups\n* Flute Ensemble\n* Tuba and horn quartets\n\n=== Musicals ===\nEvery other year (and sometimes more often), Shrewsbury puts on its own homegrown School Musical which is taken to the[[Edinburgh Festival Fringe]], these have included<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/event/edinburgh-festival-2010-school-musical-what-you-will-15th-20th-august|title=Edinburgh Festival: The 2010 School Musical 'What You Will' 15th-20th August|date=2011-04-28|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>:\n\n* ''Rebecca The Drowned Bride''\n* ''What You Will''\n* ''Bubble''\n* ''Jekyll!''\n\nHigh profile musicians and performers also visit the school with such visitors including: \n\n* [[Jacques Loussier|Jacques Lussier]] , \n* [[The Swingle Singers|The Swingles]],\n* [[Cristina Ortiz]], \n* [[Tenebrae (choir)|Tenebrae Choir]],\n* [[Joe Stilgoe|Joe Stilgoe,]]  \n* [[Jenny Agutter]], \n* [[Voces8]], \n* [[Peter Donohoe (pianist)|Peter Donohoe]] .<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/music-arts-events|title=Music & Arts Events|date=2017-08-09|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n== Praepostors ==\nThe schools' [[Prefect|prefects]] are known as pr\u00e6postors. The word originally referred to a monastic [[prior]] and is late [[Latin]] of the [[Middle Ages]], derived from classical Latin ''praepositus'', \"placed before\".The use of ''praepostor'' in the context of a school is derived from the practice of using older boys to lead or control the younger boys. Privillages associated with the office are a particular tie showing the school's arms and the right to cycle a bike to lessons.\n\n== Awards ==\nHouse and school ties and scarfs are awarded achievements in co-curricular activities. \n\n== Scholarships, exhibitions and bursary support  ==\nVarious measures of financial assistance are available to students associated with need and with ability.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/scholarships-and-bursaries|title=Scholarships and Bursaries|date=2011-03-29|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n== School Song ==\nThe school has its own song, Carmen Salopiense, written inLatin in 1916 by the [[Cyril Alington]] who was Headmaster at the time:<blockquote>''Rex Edwarde, te canamus'' \n\n''Pium Fundatorem,'' \n\n''Nec, sodales, sileamus'' \n\n''Regiam Sororem.'' \n\n''Mente prosequamur grata'' \n\n''Regem et reginam,'' \n\n''Fautricemque amoena prata''\n\n''Resonent Sabrinam. Floreat Salopia.''\n\n''<br />Non tacendumst hic priorum''  \n\n''Nobilem Cohortem,''  \n\n''Plenam vitam huic honorum,''  \n\n''Pleniorem mortem;''  \n\n''Illius nec nomen turpis''  \n\n''Obruat robigo,''  \n\n''Qui humanae docet stirpis''  \n\n''Unde sit origo. Floreat Salopia.'' \n\n''<br />Ceteri dum magistrorum''  \n\n''Lugent breve fatum,''  \n\n''Fas iactare Informatorum''  \n\n''Hic triumviratum:''  \n\n''Nostra tum iubente nympha''  \n\n''(Rudis forte si sis)''  \n\n''Exardebat Cami lympha,''  \n\n''Exardebat Isis. Floreat Salopia.'' \n\n''<br />'' \n\n''Nimiis stipata turbis''  \n\n''Annis plus trecenis,''  \n\n''Sedem schola liquit urbis''  \n\n''Imparem Camenis:''  \n\n''Nescit studium mutari,''  \n\n''Quique alumnos pridem''  \n\n''Nominis amor praeclari''  \n\n''Nos exercet idem. Floreat Salopia.'' \n\n''<br />Editique caro colle''\n \n''Matri quam amamus''\n \n''Arte, libro, remo, folle''\n \n''Gloriam petamus:''\n \n''Sic futuros hic per annos''\n \n''Laus accumuletur''\n \n''Et per ultimos Britannos''\n \n''Nomen celebretur. Floreat Salopia.{{NoteTag|\"... Rex Edwarde, te canamus\n<br>\nPium Fundatorem,\n<br>\nNec, sodales, sileamus\n<br>\nRegiam Sororem.\n<br>\nMente prosequamur grata\n<br>\nRegem et reginam,\n<br>\nFautricemque amoena prata\n<br>\nResonent Sabrinam. Floreat Salopia.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\nNon tacendumst hic priorum\n<br>\nNobilem Cohortem,\n<br>\nPlenam vitam huic honorum,\n<br>\nPleniorem mortem;\n<br>\nIllius nec nomen turpis\n<br>\nObruat robigo,\n<br>\nQui humanae docet stirpis\n<br>\nUnde sit origo. Floreat Salopia.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\nCeteri dum magistrorum\n<br>\nLugent breve fatum,\n<br>\nFas iactare Informatorum\n<br>\nHic triumviratum:\n<br>\nNostra tum iubente nympha\n<br>\n(Rudis forte si sis)\n<br>\nExardebat Cami lympha,\n<br>\nExardebat Isis. Floreat Salopia.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\nNimiis stipata turbis\n<br>\nAnnis plus trecenis,\n<br>\nSedem schola liquit urbis\n<br>\nImparem Camenis:\n<br>\nNescit studium mutari,\n<br>\nQuique alumnos pridem\n<br>\nNominis amor praeclari\n<br>\nNos exercet idem. Floreat Salopia.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\nEditique caro colle\n<br>\nMatri quam amamus\n<br>\nArte, libro, remo, folle\n<br>\nGloriam petamus:\n<br>\nSic futuros hic per annos\n<br>\nLaus accumuletur\n<br>\nEt per ultimos Britannos\n<br>\nNomen celebretur. Floreat Salopia.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\n(Translated):\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\nTo King Edward from the loyal\n<br>\nsons of his foundation\n<br>\nhymns are due, and to his royal\n<br>\nsister salutation.\n<br>\nLet us, friends, acknowledge proudly\n<br>\nking and queen as founders,\n<br>\nand with Hail Sabrina! loudly\n<br>\nfill the fields around us.  Floreat Salopia!\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\nNext be praise to those accorded\n<br>\nwho were here before us,\n<br>\none who crowned a life much lauded\n<br>\nwith a death more glorious,\n<br>\nand another (ever splendid\n<br>\nhis renown) who teaches\n<br>\nhumankind from whence descended\n<br>\ntheirs and every species.  Floreat Salopia!\n<br>\nOthers mourn headmasters plundered\n<br>\nalmost ere they've seen them:\n<br>\nwe boast three who spanned a hundred\n<br>\nyears and more between them.\n<br>\nIn their day Salopian learning\n<br>\n(all must know the story)\n<br>\nset both Cam and Isis burning\n<br>\nwith Sabrina's glory.  Floreat Salopia!\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\nScholars long by cramps vexatious\n<br>\ncabin'd and frustrated\n<br>\nfrom their town to fields more spacious\n<br>\nfinally migrated.\n<br>\nSites may change, but not ambition:\n<br>\nours has never faltered;\n<br>\nand our forebears' high tradition\n<br>\nwe remain unaltered.  Floreat Salopia!\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\nOn our hill to serve our Mother\n<br>\nfame through art we'll give her,\n<br>\nfame in learning, as we love her,\n<br>\nfame on field and river.\n<br>\nPraise on praise be hers, and never\n<br>\nmay we fail to seek it,\n<br>\npraise that shall be heard wherever\n<br>\nBritish tongues can speak it.  Floreat Salopia!.\"<ref>{{cite book |first=Basil |last=Oldham |authorlink= |title=Boy |title-link=Boy (book) |year=1952 |publisher=B. Blackwell}}</ref>}} <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/features/school-song|title=School song|date=2011-03-28|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}} {{refn}}</ref>''</blockquote>\n\n== Ancient Library ==\nThe school has an ancient library, containing various significant antiquarian books and other items.  Particular highlights of the collection include:\n\n* Charles Darwin's school atlas, along with books, manuscripts and letters ;\n* [[Isaac Newton|Newton]]'s 'Principia', acquired on publication in 1687;\n* some forty medieval manuscripts, including a fine twelfth-century Gradual from [[Haughmond Abbey]] and the Lichfield Processional with its unique liturgical English plays of circa 1430 and [[Polyphonic Music|polyphonic music]]\n* the [[death mask]] of [[Oliver Cromwell]]<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n== Art Collection ==\nThe Moser Gallery, within the library buildings, contains part of the school's collection of paintings.  This includes work by [[J. M. W. Turner|J. M. W Turner]], important nineteenth century water colours, and work by [[Kyffin Williams]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.watercolourworld.org/collection/moser-gallery-shrewsbury-school|title=The Moser Gallery at Shrewsbury School|date=2019-04-04|website=Watercolour World|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> \n\n==Headmasters==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=22em|\n*2018\u2013 : Leo Winkley\n*2010\u201318: Mark Turner\n*2001\u201310: Jeremy W. R. Goulding\n*1988\u20132001: Ted Maidment\n*1981\u201388: Simon J. B. Langdale\n*1975\u201380: [[Sir Eric Anderson]]\n*1963\u201375: [[Donald Wright (schoolmaster)|A. R. D. Wright]]\n*1950\u201363: John \"Jock\" Magnus Peterson\n*1944\u201350: [[John Wolfenden, Baron Wolfenden]]\n*1932\u201344: Henry Harrison Hardy (father of the actor [[Robert Hardy]])\n*1917\u201332: Harold A. P. Sawyer\n*1908\u201317: [[Cyril Alington|Cyril Argentine Alington]]\n*1866\u20131908: [[Henry Whitehead Moss]]\n*1836\u201365: [[Benjamin Hall Kennedy]]\n*1798\u20131836: [[Samuel Butler (schoolmaster)|Dr Samuel Butler]] (afterwards [[Bishop of Lichfield]])\n*1771\u201398: Revd. J. Atcherley\n*1754\u201370: Charles Newling\n*1735\u201354: Leonard Hotchkiss\n*1727\u201335: Robert Phillips\n*1723\u201327: Revd. H. Owen\n*1687\u20131723: Revd. R. Lloyd\n*?1646\u201387: Revd. A. Taylor\n*1645{{ndash}}62: Thomas Pigott (deprived under [[Act of Uniformity 1662|Act of Uniformity]])\n*1637\u201345: Revd. Thomas Chaloner (expelled by Parliamentarians, died 1664)\n*1583\u20131635: John Meighen\n*1571\u201383: T. Lawrence\n*1561\u201371: [[Thomas Ashton (schoolmaster)|Thomas Ashton]]\n}}\n\n==Notable masters==\n*[[Nick Bevan]], housemaster, rowing coach, later headmaster of [[Shiplake College]]\n*[[Anthony Chenevix-Trench]], housemaster of School House, later headmaster of [[Bradfield College]], [[Eton College]] and [[Fettes College]]\n*[[Frank McEachran]]<ref>'Frank McEachran', obituary in ''Books and Bookmen'', vol. 20 (Hanson Books, 1975), pp. 58\u201359.</ref>\n*[[Ronald Knox|The Reverend Monsignor Ronald Knox]], English Catholic priest, theologian, author and broadcaster\n*[[David Profumo]], 6th Baron Profumo, teacher and novelist\n*[[Sir William Gladstone, 7th Baronet]], teacher and officer\n\n== Affiliate Schools ==\nShrewsbury has the following affiliate schools:\n\n* [[Shrewsbury International School, Bangkok]]. located on the banks of the [[Chao Phraya River]], opened 2003;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://whichschooladvisor.com/thailand/school-review/shrewsbury-international-school-bangkok-riverside|title=Shrewsbury International School Bangkok (Riverside) Review|website=whichschooladvisor.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n* Shrewsbury International School, [[Hong Kong]], opened 2018;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/shrewsbury-hong-kong|title=Shrewsbury Hong Kong|date=2017-08-01|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.edu.hk/|title=British Primary School {{!}} Shrewsbury International School Hong Kong|website=www.shrewsbury.edu.hk|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n* [[Packwood Haugh School]], is a Shropshire Preparatory School which united with Shrewsbury School in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/news/education/2019/05/15/merger-will-see-shropshire-school-family-grow/|title=Merger will see Shropshire school family grow|last=Robertson|first=Dominic|website=www.shropshirestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n==Fess and Admission ==\nPupils are admitted at the age of 13 by selective examination,<ref name=\"isi report\" /> and for approximately ten per cent of the pupils, English is a second or additional language.<ref name=\"ofsted\" /> The fees at Shrewsbury are up to \u00a312,980 a term for UK students and up to \u00a313,500 a term for international students, with three terms per academic year in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/fees|title=Fees|date=29 March 2011|website=Shrewsbury School}}</ref> \n\n==Old Salopians==\n{{See also|List of Old Salopians}}\nFormer pupils are referred to as [[:Category:People educated at Shrewsbury School|Old Salopians]] (from the old name for [[Shropshire]]).\n[[File:Charles darwin.gif|alt=Charles Darwin, Old Salopian, naturalist|thumb|Charles Darwin, naturalist]]\n[[File:AndrewIrvine.jpg|alt=Andrew Ivine, Old Salopian, part of the 1924 Everest Expedition|thumb|Andrew Ivine, part of the 1924 Everest Expedition. ]]\n[[File:Michael Palin (2).jpg|alt=Michael Palin, Old Salopian, member of Monty Plyton|thumb|Michael Palin, member of Monty Plyton]]\n[[File:Lord Heseltine (6969083278).jpg|alt=Michael Heseltine, former Deputy Prime Minister|thumb|Michael Heseltine, Old Salopian, former Deputy Prime Minister  ]]\n[[File:NSRW Phillip Sidney.jpg|alt=Sir Phillip Sidney, Old Slaopian, solidier, courtier and poet|thumb|Sir Phillip Sidney, solidier, courtier and poet ]]\n\n=== Contemporary Old Salopians  ===\n\n'''1930s'''\n\n* [[James Adams (diplomat)|Sir William Adams]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|KCMG}} (born 1932), ambassador to [[Tunisia]] 1984{{ndash}}87 and [[Egypt]] 1987{{ndash}}92\n* [[Peter Brown (historian)|Peter Brown]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FBA}} (born 1935), historian of [[Late Antiquity]] and Fellow of [[All Souls College, Oxford]]\n* [[Christopher Booker]] (born 1937), journalist, founder of ''[[Private Eye]]''\n* [[Michael Heseltine]], Baron Heseltine {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CH|PC}} (born 1933), politician and [[Deputy Prime Minister]]\n* [[Brian Hutton, Baron Hutton]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|PC|QC}} (born 1931), Law Lord, [[Lord Chief Justice of Northern Ireland]] and Chairman of Hutton Inquiry\n* [[Christopher Gill]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|RD}} (born 1936), politician\n* [[Richard Ingrams]] (born 1937), journalist, founder of ''[[Private Eye]]''\n* [[Colin McColl|Sir Colin Hugh Verel McColl]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|KCMG}} (born 1932), head of the [[Secret Intelligence Service]] (MI6)\n* [[Michael Simmons (RAF officer)|Air Marshall Sir Michael Simmons]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|KCB|AFC}} (born 1937), Royal Air Force Officer, Assistant Chief of the Air Staff\n\n'''1940s'''\n\n* [[Richard Barber]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRSL|FSA|FRHistS}} (born 1941), historian\n* [[Richard Best, Baron Best]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE|DL|FAcSS}} (born 1945), politician\n* [[Piers Brendon]] (born 1940), writer\n* [[Robert Corbett (British Army officer)|Major General Sir Robert John Swan Corbett]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|KCVO|CB}} (born 1940), [[List of Commandants of Berlin Sectors|Commandant of the British Sector in Berlin]] 1987-90\n* [[Peter Davis (businessman)|Sir Peter Davis]] (born 1941), businessman and chairman of [[Sainsbury's]]\n* [[Edward Foljambe, 5th Earl of Liverpool]] (born 1944), Conservative politician and peer\n* [[Martin Ferguson Smith]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE|FSA}} (born 1941), scholar, writer and Classics and Ancient History professor at [[Durham University|Durham]]\n* [[Robin Hodgson, Baron Hodgson of Astley Abbotts]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE}} (born 1942), politician and [[life peer]]\n* [[Stephen Jessel]] (born 1942), BBC correspondent\n* [[David Lovell Burbidge]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE|DL}} (born 1943), [[High sheriff]] of the West Midlands County 1990\u201391\n* [[Baron Rochester|David Lamb, 3rd Baron Rochester]] (born 1944), noble\n* [[Christopher MacLehose]] (born 1940), publisher\n* [[Terry Milewski]] (born 1949), journalist\n* [[Nick Owen]] (born 1947), TV presenter\n* [[Sir Mark Moody-Stuart]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|KCMG}} (born 1940), ex-chairman of [[Royal Dutch Shell]] and Chairman of the UN Global Compact committee\n* [[Michael Palin|Sir Michael Palin]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE|FRGS}} (born 1943), actor and TV presenter\n* [[Richard Passingham]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRS}} (born 1943), neurologist\n* [[Nicholas Penny|Sir Nicholas Penny]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FBA|FSA}} (born 1949), art historian, Director of the National Gallery\n* [[Martin Rees, Baron Rees of Ludlow]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OM|FRS|FREng|FMedSci|FRAS}} (born 1942), Astronomer Royal, erstwhile Master of [[Trinity College, Cambridge]], ex-President of [[Royal Society]]\n* [[Sykes Baronets|Sir Francis John Badcock Sykes, 10th Baronet]] (born 1942), businessman\n* [[Tom Macan|Thomas Townley Macan]] (born 1946), Governor and Commander-in-Chief of the [[British Virgin Islands]]\n* [[Roddy Llewellyn|Sir Roderic Victor Llewellyn, 5th Baronet]] (born 1947), author and partner of [[Princess Margaret, Countess of Snowdon]]\n* [[Selby Whittingham]] (born 1941), art expert\n* [[Vernon baronets|Sir James William Vernon, 5th Baronet]] (born 1949), landowner and accountant\n* [[Christopher Wallace (British Army officer)|Sir Christopher Wallace]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|KBE|DL}} (born 1943), Lieutenant General and Royal Green Jackets\n* [[Stephen Wright (diplomat)|Sir Stephen Wright]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|KCMG}} (born 1946), diplomat, [[Under-Secretary]] at the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]], Ambassador to Spain\n\n'''1950s'''\n\n* [[Bruce Clark (journalist)|Bruce Clark]] (born 1958), author and International Security Editor of [[The Times]]\n* [[Stephen Glover (columnist)|Stephen Glover]] (born 1952), journalist & columnist\n* [[Tim Lamb|Timothy Edward Lamb]] (born 1959), cricketer and sports administrator\n* [[Sir John Auld Mactaggart, 4th Baronet]] (born 1951), entrepreneur and philanthropist\n* [[Jonathan Marland, Baron Marland|Jonathan Peter Marland, Baron Marland]] (born 1956), Treasurer of the Conservative Party\n* [[Andrew McFarlane (judge)|Sir Andrew McFarlane]] (born 1954), [[Lord Justice of Appeal]] in England and [[Wales]]\n* [[Philip Campbell (scientist)|Sir Philip Montgomery Campbell]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRAS|FInstP}}  (born 1951), astrophysicist and editor-in-chief of [[Nature (journal)|Nature]]\n* [[Michael Proctor (academic)|Michael Proctor]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRS|FIMA|FRAS}} (born 1950), academic and [[Provost (education)|Provost]] of [[King's College, Cambridge]]\n* [[Nicholas Rankin]] (born 1950), writer and broadcaster\n* [[John Ryle (writer)|Johnathan Ryle]] (born 1952), writer, anthropologist and professor at [[Bard College]]\n* [[Desmond Shawe-Taylor]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|LVO}} (born 1955), art historian, Surveyor of the Queen's Pictures\n* [[John Shawe-Taylor|Jonathon Shawe-Taylor]] (born 1953), Director of the Centre for Computational Statistics and Machine Learning at [[University College, London|University College]], London\n* [[John Stuttard|Sir John Stuttard]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|JP|FCA}} (born 1945), Alderman and [[Lord Mayor of the City of London]] 2006\u201307\n\n'''1960s''' \n\n* [[Andrew Berry]] (born 1963), biologist and lecturer of Organismic and Evolutionary Biology at [[Harvard University|Harvard]]\n* [[Simon Baynes]] (born 1960), politician \n* [[Tim Booth]] (born 1960), musician\n* [[Nick Hancock]] (born 1962), actor and TV presenter\n* [[Clive Johnstone|Clive Carruthers Johnstone]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CB|CBE}} (born 1961), Royal Navy officer and Commander of the [[Allied Maritime Command]]\n* [[Baron Hampton|John Humphrey Arnott Pakington, 7th Baron Hampton]] (born 1964), landowner and photographer\n* [[Nicholas Jarrold]] (born 1959), Ambassador to [[Croatia]] 2000\u20132004 and to [[Latvia]] 1996\u20131999\n* [[Jonathan Legard]] (born 1961), journalist and broadcaster\n* [[Jonathan Lord]] (born 1962), politician\n* [[Twm Morys]] (born 1961), poet and musician.\n* [[Mark Oakley]] (born 1968), Canon Chancellor of [[St. Paul's Cathedral]] and Dean of [[St John\u2019s College, Cambridge]]\n* [[Angus Pollock]] (born 1962), cricketer for [[Cambridge University Cricket Club]]\n* [[Simon Shackleton]] (born 1968), DJ, musician\n* [[Martin Wainwright]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|MBE}} (born 1960), journalist and author\n\n'''1970s'''\n\n* [[Charles Robertson-Adams]] (born 1976), athlete\n* [[Jonty Heaversedge]] (born 1971), TV doctor\n* [[Christopher Hope]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRSL}} (born 1972), journalist, political editor of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''\n* [[Alastair Humphreys]] (born 1976), adventurer and author\n\n'''1980s'''\n\n* [[Line of succession to the Bruneian throne|Omar \u2018Ali Bolkiah]] (born 1986), [[Crown Prince]] of the [[Sultanate of Brunei]]\n* [[Anthony Mangnall|Anthony Magnall]] (born 1989), MP for [[Totnes (UK Parliament constituency)|Totnes]]\n* [[Richard Bridgeman, 7th Earl of Bradford|Alexander Orlando Bridgeman, Viscount Newport]] (born 1980), businessman and landowner\n* [[Big Brother (British series 10)|Freddie Fisher]] (born 1985), actor \n* [[Richard Goulding]] (born 1980) actor\n* [[Ian Massey]] (born 1985), cricketer, [[Cambridge University Cricket Club|Cambridge MCCU]] and [[Herefordshire County Cricket Club|Herefordshire]]\n* [[Joshua Sasse]] (born 1987), actor\n*[[Will Tudor]] (born 1987), actor\n\n'''1990s'''\n\n*[[James Taylor (cricketer, born 1990)|James Taylor]] (born 1990), Nottinghamshire and England cricketer\n*[[Claas Mertens]] (born 1992), German rower\n<!-- Please add deceased alumni to the separate List Of Old Salopians -->\n<!-- Proof of attendance is required -Please do not add Old Salopians who do not have a Wiki page, unless references are added.-->\n\n===Victoria Cross holders===\nTwo Old Salopians received the [[Victoria Cross]], both in the [[First World War]], 1914\u201318.\n*[[Thomas Tannatt Pryce]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|VC|MC}}\n*[[Harold Ackroyd]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|VC|MC}}\n\n=== Old Salopain Activities ===\nThe \"Old Salopian Club\", now known as the Salopian Club, was founded in 1886.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iwm.org.uk/collections/item/object/1500040698|title=Old Salopian Club, founded 1886 year-book, thirty-third issue; April 1921|website=Imperial War Museums|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>  A number of reunions, clubs and activities are arranged by the club.  The post nominals OS are used to denote Old Saloplians. .<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/salopian-club-has-been-furloughed-until-further-notice|title=The Salopian Club has been furloughed until further notice.|date=2011-03-14|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> \n\n==== Sports ====\nFormer members of the school have various sporting clubs:\n\n* Rowing is arranged by the \"Sabrina Club\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/os-rowing-sabrina|title=OS Rowing - Sabrina|date=2011-03-28|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>, which fields crews, including for Henley Royal Regatta<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hrr.co.uk/henley-royal-regatta-list-of-2019-entries|title=Henley Royal Regatta List of 2019 entries {{!}} Henley Royal Regatta|website=www.hrr.co.uk|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> as well as supporting the school crews at various events\n* Cricket is arranged by the \"Saracens\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/os-cricket-saracens|title=OS Cricket - Saracens|date=2011-05-20|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n* Old Salopian golf, yachting, fives cross country, tennis, football, squash and basket ball are also provided for.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/os-sport|title=OS Sport|date=2011-05-18|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\n==== Careers, arts and activities ====\nArrangements for cultural engagement of former members if the school, for instance concerts and plays and art exhibitions are also put on, and there is a programme around around careers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/os-arts-and-activities|title=OS Arts and Activities|date=2011-05-18|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/os-careers|title=OS Careers|date=2012-10-02|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\n== Social Action  ==\n\n=== Shrewsbury House - 'The Shewsy' ===\nShrewsbury House is a youth and community centre attached to St Peter's Church in [[Everton, Liverpool|Everton]], [[Liverpool]].  It was founded in 1903 by masters from Shrewsbury School, it employs two full-time trained youth workers and a team of part-time staff and offers young people in the local area an excellent range of facilities and sporting and recreational opportunities. 'The Shewsy' runs Junior Clubs for children aged 5 - 11 and Senior Clubs for those aged 12 - 20 throughout the week, as well as a variety of weekend activities, including residential trips and exchange visits.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/the-shewsy|title=Shrewsbury House - 'The Shewsy'|date=2011-03-28|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.shrewsburyhouse.org.uk/|title=Shrewsbury House {{!}} Youth Club|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\n=== Other Outreach ===\nDuring the [[coronavirus]] [[pandemic]] of 2020 the school donated over 1,600 items of [[personal protective equipment]] to the [[National Health Service|NHS]], including face shields it had 3D printed in its technology labs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/news/local-hubs/shrewsbury/2020/04/13/shrewsbury-school-donates-ppe-in-covid-19-fight/|title=Shrewsbury School donates PPE in Covid-19 fight|last=Humphreys|first=Nick|website=www.shropshirestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>  It also opened up rooms in its boarding houses for use for NHS staff.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boarding.org.uk/media/news/article/13563/2-500-boarding-beds-offered-in-the-fight-against-coronavirus|title=2,500+ boarding beds offered in the fight against coronavirus|website=www.boarding.org.uk|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n== Talargerwyn ==\nThe School owns Talargerwyn, a farm house situated in the Forest above Betws-y-Coed in central Snowdonia. It can accommodate up to twenty boys and staff and is used at week-ends in term-time throughout the year as a base for field work and expeditions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://files.api.beta.ofsted.gov.uk/v1/file/1585723|title=Inspection Report, Boarding School, Shrewsbury School|last=Commission of Socail Care Inspection|first=|date=2004|website=Ostead|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Steam Locomotive ==\nA [[SR V Schools class|Schools Class]] 4-4-0 [[locomotive]], 921 \"Shrewsbury\" (BR 30921),was named after Shrewsbury School. \n\nThis class of engines were designed by [[Richard Maunsell]] and were originally classified as Class V. Forty other independent schools had one of these  express passenger steam locomotives were produced at [[Eastleigh Works]] and numbered 900 - 939 for [[Southern Railway (UK)|Southern Railways]]. Combining designs used in the Lord Nelson Class and weighing in at 110 tons, the design of this Class represented the last usage of this type of 4-4-0 wheel arrangement in Great Britain.  The only surviving engines from the schools class are those named for [[Repton School|Repton]], [[Stowe School|Stowe]] and [[Cheltenham College|Cheltenham]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hornby.com/uk-en/sr-4-4-0-shrewsbury-schools-class.html|website=www.hornby.com|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nThe name plaque preserved in the Admissions Offices/Registry of the school.\n\n== Controversy ==\nIn September 2005, the school was one of fifty independent schools operating [[Independent school fee fixing scandal|independent school fee-fixing]], in breach of the [[Competition Act 1998|Competition Act, 1998]]. All of the schools involved were ordered to abandon this practice, pay a nominal penalty of \u00a310,000 each and to make ex-gratia payments totalling three million pounds into a trust designed to benefit pupils who attended the schools during the period in respect of which fee information had been shared.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Halpin|first=Halpin|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/independent-schools-face-huge-fines-over-cartel-to-fix-fees-rcwcznjnvnt|title=Independent schools face huge fines over cartel to fix fees|access-date=2020-02-29|issn=0140-0460}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20100402135855tf_/http://www.oft.gov.uk/news/press/2006/182-06|title=Office of Fair Trading Press Release|last=|first=|date=21 December 2006|website=National Ara chive|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=29 Feb 2020}}</ref> \n\n==See also==\n*[[Listed buildings in Shrewsbury (outer areas)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n* Alan Stewart, \"Philip Sidney: A Double Life\", Chatto and Windus, 2000. {{ISBN|0-7011-6859-5}}\n* \"Shrewsbury Library: Its History and Restoration\" \u2013 A.M Carr Shropshire Libraries 1983\n\n==Further reading==\n*[[Parliament of the United Kingdom|UK Parliament]] ''Clarendon Report'' (London: HM Stationery Office 1864) \n*[[iarchive:annalsshrewsbur01hillgoog|Annals of Shrewsbury School]], George William Fisher & John Spencer Hill (1899)\n* [https://archive.org/details/historyofshrewsb00blak History of Shrewsbury School, 1551\u20131888], [[John Brickdale Blakeway]] & Alfred Rimmer (1889)\n*Draisey, M., ''Thirty Years On! A Private View of Public Schools'' (Halsgrove,  2014 {{ISBN|978-0857042118}})\n*Gee, D., ''City on a Hill - A Portrait of Shrewsbury School'' (Somerset, Greenbank Press, 2015, {{ISBN|9780952369981}})\n*Bloomfield, R., ''History of Rowing at Shrewsbury School'' (2005)\n*Oldham, J.B., The History of Shrewsbury School (1952)\n*Fanning, P., ''The Divided Self'' (Somerset, Greenbank Press, 2015, {{ISBN|0952369990}})\n*McEachran, F., ''A Cauldron of Spells''  Jan. 1992 (Somerset, Greenbank Press, 1991, {{ISBN|0955398606}})\n*Charlesworth, M.L.,. ''Behind the Headlines'' (Somerset: Greenbank Press, 1994. {{ISBN|0952369915}})\n\n== Notes ==\n{{NoteFoot}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscatinline}}\n* {{Official|https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/}}\n\n{{Schools in Shropshire}}\n{{Shrewsbury architecture}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n\n[[Category:Boarding schools in Shropshire]]\n[[Category:Independent schools in Shropshire]]\n[[Category:Member schools of the Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in the 1550s]]\n[[Category:1552 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Schools in Shrewsbury]]\n[[Category:Schools with a Royal Charter]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=December 2019}}\n{{About-distinguish2|the independent King Edward VI school|[[Shrewsbury High School, Shropshire|Shrewsbury High School]] or [[Shrewsbury Academy]]}}\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2010}}\n{{Infobox school\n | name                    = Shrewsbury School<br />{{small|King Edward VI School at Shrewsbury}}\n | logo                    = Shrewsbury School COA.svg\n | logo_size               = 120\n | image                   = Shrewsbury School 1.JPG\n | caption                 = The school's current main building from 1882\n | coordinates             = {{coord|52.7038|-2.7622|type:edu_region:GB_dim:100|format=dec|display=inline,title}}\n | motto                   = [[Latin]]: ''Intus Si Recte Ne Labora''<br />\n | established             = 1552<ref name=\"ofsted\">[http://www.ofstedgov.com/oxcare_reports/download/(id)/218681/(as)/SC020779_SC.pdf Ofsted Social Care report 2008.] Retrieved 19 March 2010</ref>\n | closed                  = \n | type                    = [[Public school (United Kingdom)|Public school]] <br />[[Independent school (United Kingdom)|Independent]] <br />[[day school|day]] and boarding school\n | religious_affiliation   = [[Church of England]]\n | president               = \n | head_label              = Headmaster\n | head                    = Leo Winkley\n | chair_label             = Chairman of Governing Body\n | chair                   = James Pitt<ref>{{cite web |title=Trustees |date=3 June 2015 |url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/trustees |publisher=Shrewsbury School |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref>\n | founder                 = [[Edward VI of England|King Edward VI]]\n | specialist              = \n | motto_translation       = If Right Within, Trouble Not\n | address                 = Kingsland\n | city                    = [[Shrewsbury]]\n | county                  = [[Shropshire]]\n | country                 = England\n | postcode                = SY3 7BA\n | local_authority         = [[Shropshire Council]]\n | urn                     = 123608\n | ofsted                  = \n | staff                   = ca. 120\n | enrolment               = ca. 800\n | gender                  = Co-educational (from 2015)\n | lower_age               = 13\n | upper_age               = 18\n | houses                  = 13\n | colours                 = Royal blue and white\n | publication             = ''The Salopian''\n | free_label_1            = Former pupils\n | free_1                  = [[List of Old Salopians|Old Salopians]]\n | free_label_2            = School Song\n | free_2                  = ''Carmen Salopiense''\n | website                 = {{URL|https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/|www.shrewsbury.org.uk}}\n | module                  = {{Infobox mapframe\n| stroke-color = #C60C30\n| stroke-width  = 3\n| marker        = school\n| marker-color = #1F2F57\n| zoom          = 13}}\n}}\n'''Shrewsbury School''' is an English [[Independent school (United Kingdom)|independent]] boarding school for pupils aged 13 to 18 in [[Shrewsbury]], Shropshire.  It was founded by [[Edward VI]] in 1552 by a [[Royal Charter]].<ref name=\"ofsted\" /> \n\nShrewsbury is one of the original seven [[Public school (United Kingdom)|public schools]] as defined by the [[Public Schools Act 1868]], and one of the 'great' nine identified by the [[Clarendon Commission]] of 1861. It was originally a boarding school for boys; girls have been admitted into the Sixth Form since 2008 and has been co-educational since 2015. There are approximately 130-day pupils.<ref name=\"isi report\">[http://www.isi.net/HistoricalReports/0992_07.htm Independent Schools Inspectorate report 2007] Retrieved 19 March 2010</ref> \n\nThe present site, to which the school moved in 1882, is on the banks of the [[River Severn]].<ref name=\"ofsted\" />\n\nThe school's alumni \u2013 or \"[[Old Salopians]]\" \u2013 include naturalists, poets, academics, politicians, authors, sportsmen, actors, and military figures.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Edward VI swagger.jpg|alt=King Edward VI, founder of Shrewsbury School|left|thumb|[[Edward VI of England|King Edward VI]], founder of Shrewsbury School ]]\n\n=== Foundation and Early Years ===\nShrewsbury School was founded by charter in 1552 under [[Edward VI of England|King Edward VI]], following a petition in 1542 to [[Henry VIII]] from the townspeople of Shrewsbury for a free grammar school.  \n\nThe school began operation in three rented wooden buildings, which included Riggs Hall, built in 1450, and now the only remaining part of the original foundation. \n\nThe early curriculum was based on Continental [[Calvinism]], under its first headmaster, [[Thomas Ashton (schoolmaster)|Thomas Ashton]] (appointed 1561) and boys were taught the catechism of [[John Calvin|Calvin]]. The school attracted large numbers of pupils from Protestant families in Shrewsbury, Shropshire and North Wales, with 266 boys on its roll at the end of 1562.<ref name=\"odnb\">{{cite book|title=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, Volume 2|year=2004|publisher=Oxford University Press|page=684|isbn=0-19-861352-0}}Article on Thomas Ashton by Martin R. Speight.</ref> Early pupils lodged with local families; [[Philip Sidney|Sir Philip Sidney]] did so with [[George Leigh (MP)|George Leigh]], Member of Parliament for [[Shrewsbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Shrewsbury]]. \n\nHaving achieved a reputation for excellence under Ashton, in 1571 the school was augmented by [[Elizabeth I of England|Queen Elizabeth I]].  \n\nAlthough Ashton had resigned from his headmastership in 1568, he returned to Shrewsbury in 1578 to help draw up the ordinances governing the school, which were in force until 1798; under them, the borough bailiffs (mayors after 1638) had power to appoint masters, with Ashton's old [[St John's College, Cambridge]] having an academic veto.<ref name=\"odnb2\">{{cite book|title=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, Volume 2|pages=684\u2013685}}</ref> Shrewsbury has retained links with the College, with the continued appointment of Johnian academics to the Governing Body, and the historic awarding of 'closed' Shrewsbury Exhibitions.<ref>{{cite web | title=Governing Body Members' Details |date= 20 December 2012 |url= http://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/governing-body-members-details | publisher=Shrewsbury School|accessdate=4 May 2018}}</ref>[[File:Shrewsbury Library 2017.jpg|alt=|left|thumb|The school's original building now serves as Shrewsbury's town library]]\n\nThe stone buildings on Castle Gates, including a chapel, dormitories, library and classrooms were completed by 1630, with the Ashton's successor,  John Meighen, founding a [[chained library]] in 1606,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/features/school-history|title=School History|date=2011-03-28|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>  though the library had begun making acquisitions by 1596, with a terrestrial globe by the first English globe maker [[Emery Molyneux|Emery Molineux]] being its first acquisition.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/ancient-taylor-library|title=The Ancient ('Taylor') Library|date=2011-03-28|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>  \n\n[[File:Shrewsbury Library 06.jpg|thumb|Early graffiti in the former school building|alt=|left]]A house was also built for the school in 1617 in the nearby village of [[Grinshill]] as a retreat in times of plague.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Nicolle, Dorothy.|title=Shrewsbury|date=2013|publisher=History|isbn=978-0-7524-8270-5|location=Stroud|oclc=841908132}}</ref><ref>{{NHLE|num=1055426|desc=STONE GRANGE, Grinshill |accessdate=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nThe school's original Castle Gates premises had little in way of provision for games. Under Dr Butler, there were two bat{{clarify|date=August 2018}} fives courts and playgrounds in front of and behind the buildings, but after the arrival of Dr Kennedy football was permitted, for which the school acquired a ground in Coton Hill (north of Castle Gates).<ref name=\"shrewslib\" /> \n\nThe school continued in these buildings, until it was relocated in 1882.  At this time, the original premises were converted to a public [[Shrewsbury Library|Free Library and Museum]] by the Shrewsbury Borough Council, opening in their new role in 1885; <ref>{{cite work|author=Beryl Copsey|title=Read All About It! Grand Opening of Shrewsbury's free library 100 years ago|work=The Shropshire Magazine|date=April 1985|page=18{{ndash}}19}}</ref> over the course of the 20th century the library purpose gradually took over the whole building, to which major restoration was done in 1983.<ref>A plaque erected by The [[Rotary Club]] of Shrewsbury, commemorating the club's 60th anniversary in 1985, reads: ''Castle Gates Library erected by Edward VI in 1552, Shrewsbury School occupied this site until 1882. The stone buildings were built 1594{{ndash}}1630. Judge Jefferys and Charles Darwin were educated here. Re-opened as a library in 1983 after complete renovation.''</ref><ref name=\"shrewslib\">{{cite book|title=Shrewsbury Library, Its History and Restoration|year=1983|publisher=Shropshire Libraries|isbn=0-903802-26-0}}(Unpaginated)</ref>\n\nIn 1798, a specific Act of Parliament, The Shrewsbury School Act, was passed for the better government of the school.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Raby, Peter.|title=Samuel Butler : a biography|date=1991|publisher=University of Iowa Press|isbn=0-87745-331-4|edition=1st|location=Iowa City|oclc=24031298}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Butier|first=Samuel II|url=https://books.google.com/?id=48taAAAAcAAJ&pg=RA1-PA15&lpg=RA1-PA15&dq=1798+shrewsbury+school+act+bill#v=onepage|title=A letter to Henry Brougham on certains clauses in the education bills now before Parliament|publisher=W. Eddowes|year=1820|isbn=|location=Shrewsbury|pages=15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=The House of Commons|first=Order of|date=1803|title=Journals of the House of Commons|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Y2FIAQAAMAAJ&dq=1798+shrewsbury+school+act+bill|journal=Journals of the House of Commons|volume=53|pages=702|via=}}</ref> The [[Court of Chancery|Court of Chanclery]] in 1853 later amended this scheme.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Shrosbree, Colin.|title=Public schools and private education : the Clarendon Commission, 1861-64, and the Public Schools acts|date=1988|publisher=Manchester University Press|isbn=0-7190-2580-X|location=Manchester, UK|oclc=17807648}}</ref>\n\n=== 1800s ===\n[[File:Benjamin Hall Kennedy, by Walter William Ouless.jpg|thumb|right|[[Benjamin Hall Kennedy]], headmaster of Shrewsbury for thirty years, from 1836 to 1866.]]The school had just three headmasters during the 19th century.  \n\n[[Samuel Butler (schoolmaster)|Samuel Butler]] was appointed headmaster in 1798, and the school's reputation, which had receded from the [[English Civil War|Civil War]], again grew.<ref name=\"ButlerDNB\">{{cite DNB|wstitle=Butler, Samuel (1774\u20131839)|last=Lee|first=Sidney|authorlink=Sidney Lee|volume=8}}</ref>\n\nButler was succeeded by his pupil [[Benjamin Hall Kennedy]] (of ''Latin Primer'' fame) in 1836,<ref name=\"ButlerDNB\" /> who in turn gave way to [[Henry Whitehead Moss]] in 1866. \n\nUnder Butler and Kennedy, Shrewsbury was one of three provincial schools among the nine studied by the [[Clarendon Commission]] of 1861\u201364 (the schools considered being [[Eton College|Eton]], [[Charterhouse School|Charterhouse]], [[Harrow School|Harrow]], [[Rugby School|Rugby]], [[Westminster School|Westminster]], and [[Winchester College|Winchester]], and two day schools: [[St Paul's School (London)|St Paul's]] and [[Merchant Taylors' School, Northwood|Merchant Taylors]]).<ref>Stray, Christopher (2005)'' Histories of the Nine Clarendon Schools: v. 1'' Thoemmes Continuum  {{ISBN|1-84371-108-7}}, {{ISBN|978-1-84371-108-7}}.</ref> Shrewsbury went on to be included in the Public School's Act 1868, which ultimately related only to the boarding schools.\n\nIn 1882, Moss moved the school from its original town centre location to a new site of {{convert|150|acre|ha}} in Kingsland (an area of land which at one time belonged to the Crown and granted to the Corporation at \u201ca rather remote period, the exact date of which appears not to be known\u201d, but apparently before 1180<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kingslandshrewsburyshorthistory.wordpress.com/landownership/|title=Landownership|date=2015-02-16|website=Kingsland, Shrewsbury|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>), on the south bank of the [[River Severn]] overlooking the town. A legacy of this move can be seen in the school premises being referred to as \"The Site\".   \n\nThe school was set up in the current Main School Building which dates from 1765 and had at different times housed a [[foundling hospital]] and the Shrewsbury [[workhouse]], before translating to this current use.  In order to meet this new purpose, it was remodelled by [[Arthur Blomfield|Sir Arthur Blomfield]] (whose other educational commissions include and [[Marlborough College]] and [[Lady Margaret Hall, Oxford]]).    \n\nBloomfiled also designed School House, to the east of the Main School building which was constructed during the 1880s.<ref>{{NHLE|num=1271348|desc=SHREWSBURY SCHOOL, SCHOOL HOUSE, Shrewsbury |accessdate=2020-04-14}}</ref>  The new Riggs Hall (which had existed from Tudor buildings at the old site<ref>{{NHLE|num=1246750|desc=RIGGS HALL RIGGS HALL, TO REAR OF LIBRARY, Shrewsbury |accessdate=2020-04-15}}</ref>) was also built at this time,<ref>{{NHLE|num=1271377|desc=SHREWSBURY SCHOOL, RIGG'S HALL, Shrewsbury |accessdate=2020-04-15}}</ref> as was Churchill's Hall<ref>{{NHLE|num=1271343|desc=SHREWSBURY SCHOOL, CHURCHILL'S HALL, Shrewsbury |accessdate=2020-04-15}}</ref> and Moser's Hall<ref>{{NHLE|num=1246401|desc=SHREWSBURY SCHOOL, MOSER'S HALL, Shrewsbury |accessdate=2020-04-15}}</ref>: these buildings are the work of [[William White (architect)|William White]].  [[File:Shrewsbury School 2.JPG|thumb|The school's current chapel, built in 1887|alt=]]A [[Gothic architecture|gothic]] chapel was built for the school (also by Blomfield) in 1887.  Its south and east windows are by [[Charles Eamer Kempe|Kempe]], employing medieval narrative style for lives of saints, scenes from the history of the school.<ref>{{NHLE|num=1271376|desc=SHREWSBURY SCHOOL CHAPEL, Shrewsbury |accessdate=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nOther buildings have since grown up around the edge of the site, with sports pitches in the centre, with diverse buildings being added to the new site over the last 130 years.\n\n=== 1900s ===\nMoss was succeeded in 1908 by [[Cyril Alington]], then Master in College at [[Eton College|Eton]]. Alington, though a Fellow of All Souls College, Oxford, was a sportsman, evidenced by the 1914 appointment as his secretary of [[Neville Cardus]], the future cricket journalist who had joined the school in 1912 as the school's assistant cricket professional. \n\nAt the time of his appointment as Headmaster, Alington was younger than any of the masters on the staff, so to bring in new blood into the teaching staff, he recruited several former Collegers from Eton, most notably [[Ronald Knox|The Rev. Ronald Knox]]. Alington wrote the school song and commissioned its flag (a [[banner of arms]] of its coat of arms)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/features/school-song|title=School song|date=2011-03-28|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>, and he was an energetic builder; the school Alington Hall (assembly hall) is named after him.  In December 1914 he wrote a poem, \"To The School at War\" {{NoteTag|\"To the School at War\n<br>\nWe don\u2019t forget \u2013 while in this dark December\n<br>\nWe sit in schoolrooms that you know so well,\n<br>\nAnd hear the sounds that you so well remember \u2013\n<br>\nThe clock, the hurrying feet, the Chapel bell:\n<br>\nOthers are sitting in the seats you sat in;\n<br>\nThere\u2019s nothing else seems altered here \u2013 and yet\n<br>\nThrough all of it, the same old Greek and Latin,\n<br>\n    You know we don\u2019t forget.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\nWe don\u2019t forget you \u2013 in the wintry weather\n<br>\nYou man the trench or tramp the frozen snow;\n<br>\nWe play the games we used to play together\n<br>\nIn days of peace that seem so long ago;\n<br>\nBut through it all, the shouting and the cheering,\n<br>\nThose other hosts in graver conflict met,\n<br>\nThose other sadder sounds your ears are hearing\n<br>\n    Be sure we don\u2019t forget.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\nAnd you, our brothers, who for all our praying,\n<br>\nTo this dear school of ours come back no more,\n<br>\nWho lie, our country\u2019s debt of honour paying \u2013\n<br>\nAnd not in vain \u2013 upon the Belgian shore;\n<br>\nTill that great day when at the Throne in Heaven\n<br>\nThe books are opened and the Judgment set,\n<br>\nYour lives for honour and for England given\n<br>\n    The School will not forget..\"<ref>{{cite book |first=Noakes |last=Vivien  |authorlink= |title=Voices of silence : the alternative book of First World War poetry  |year=2006 |publisher=Stroud, Gloucestershire: Sutton|oclc=71239052 }}</ref>}} , which was published in''[[The Times]]''.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Voices of silence : the alternative book of First World War poetry|date=2006|publisher=Sutton Pub|others=Noakes, Vivien, 1937-2011.|isbn=978-0-7509-4521-9|location=Stroud, Gloucestershire|oclc=71239052}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/school-will-not-forget|title=To the School at War|date=2014-09-04|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> After leaving Shrewsbury, Alington went on to serve as  [[Chaplain to the King]] to [[George V|King George V]] from 1921 until 1933, and then [[Dean of Durham]], from 1933 to 1951.  He appeared on the cover of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine on 29 June 1931. \"An accomplished classicist, a witty writer especially of light verse, and a priest of orthodox convictions ...\"<ref>{{Cite book|last=Pfaff|first=R.W.|title=Montague Rhodes James|publisher=Scolar Press|year=1980|isbn=|location=London|pages=260}}</ref> \n\nDuring the Edwardian period Oldham's Hall was built (1911).<ref>{{NHLE|num=1246451|desc=SHREWSBURY SCHOOL, OLDHAM'S HALL, Shrewsbury |accessdate=2020-04-14}}</ref> The current library building was added in 1916.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/library|title=Library|date=2011-03-28|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nMountaineer [[Andrew Irvine (mountaineer)|Andrew Irvine]], who, with [[George Mallory]] may have reached the summit of [[Mount Everest]] in the [[1924 British Mount Everest expedition|1924 British Everest Expedition]] attended Shrewsbury during the First World War.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/central/2013-05-29/midlanders-who-tackled-mount-everest/|title=Midlanders who tackled Mount Everest|website=ITV News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>  During the 1920s the Georgian villa houses at Severn Hill<ref>{{NHLE|num=1270651|desc=SEVERN HILL, Shrewsbury |accessdate=2020-04-15}}</ref> and Ridgemount<ref>{{NHLE|num=1254704|desc=RIDGEMOUNT, Shrewsbury |accessdate=2020-04-15}}</ref> were acquired by the school and adapted into boarding houses.  Severn Hill, the linear decedent of the house of which Irvine was captain, holds his ice axe from the expedition, discovered in 1933 by Wyn Harris.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/news/2015/04/11/shropshire-everest-victims-story-to-be-told-in-new-film/|title=Shropshire Everest victim's story to be told in new film|website=www.shropshirestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==== First World War and afterwards ====\nThe [[World War I|First World War]] saw 321 former members of the school die serving their country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/osww1|title=\"The School will not forget\" - Old Salopians in WW1|date=2014-08-26|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>  A war memorial was added to the school in 1923 for these fallen.<ref>{{NHLE|num=1246402|desc=WAR MEMORIAL AT SHREWSBURY SCHOOL, Shrewsbury |accessdate=2020-04-14}}</ref>  This memorail was added to after the [[World War II|Second World War]] to include the 135 members of the school who fell in that conflict.  The monument contains a statue of [[Philip Sidney|Sir Phillip Sidney]], the Elizabeth soldier, poet and courtier who himself was a former member of the school and died of wounds sustained at the [[Battle of Zutphen]] in 1597, and it faces the Main School building down an avenue of [[Tilia|linden]] trees, known as 'central'.   \n\n==== Post Second World War ====\nBetween 1944 and 1950 [[John Wolfenden, Baron Wolfenden|John Wolfenden]] (later Lord Wolfenden) was headmaster; he left Shrewsbury to become [[Vice-Chancellor]] of the [[University of Reading]].  He was appointed to various public body chairmanships by the [[Privy council|Privy Council]], and also went on to be director of the [[British Museum]].  His name is closely associated with the government-instituted  [[Wolfenden report|Wolfenden Report]], which he chaired.     \n\nIn 1952, the school was 400 years old.  It received a royal visit to mark the occasion, and presented the town with a new cross for the historic site of the town's High Cross (which had been removed in 1705) at the termination of the market street which was a starting point for civic and religious processions in the medieval town and a significant location (the place of execution of [[Earl of Worcester]] and others after the [[Battle of Shrewsbury]] in 1403, and of [[Dafydd ap Gruffydd|Dafydd III]], last native [[Prince of Wales]] in 1283) <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://search.shropshirehistory.org.uk/collections/getrecord/CCS_MSA1131/|title=Shropshire's History Advanced Search {{!}} Shropshire's History Advanced Search|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>. \n\nThe future [[Deputy Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Deputy Prime Minister]] of the UK [[Michael Heseltine]] attended the school immediately after the Second World War on  scholarship. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/pictures/2008/04/26/famous-salopians-part-two/|title=Famous Salopians - Part Two|website=www.shropshirestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> A number of the founders and writers of the satirical magazine [[Private Eye]] attended the school in the 1950s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/news/features/2019/07/06/private-eye-founder-dies-at-81/|title=Private Eye founder and former Shrewsbury School pupil Christopher Booker dies at 81|last=Neal|first=Toby|website=www.shropshirestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>  [[Willie Rushton|Willy Rushton]] was also at the school at this time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/pictures/2008/04/26/famous-salopians-part-two/|title=Famous Salopians - Part Two|website=www.shropshirestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>  The comedian, actor, writer and television presenter [[Michael Palin|Micheal Pailin]] of [[Monty Python's Flying Circus]] attended the school shortly afterwards and a scholarship is now available named for him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/news/education/2016/07/23/michael-palin-scholarship-launched-by-shrewsbury-school/|title=Michael Palin scholarship launched by Shrewsbury School|website=www.shropshirestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nBetween 1963 and [[Donald Wright (schoolmaster)|Donald Wright]] served as headmaster. ''[[The Times]]'' has called Wright a \"great reforming headmaster\". While there, working with the [[Anglican Diocese of Liverpool]], Wright took a leading role in the building of a new Shrewsbury House, the school's mission in [[Liverpool]], which was opened in 1974 by [[Anne, Princess Royal|Princess Anne]]. He secured many leading churchmen to come to preach in the school chapel, including [[Donald Coggan]], [[Archbishop of Canterbury]]. After retiring as a headmaster in 1975, Wright became the Archbishop of Canterbury's Patronage Secretary, chaired the William Temple Foundation, and served as Secretary to the [[Appointment of Church of England bishops|Crown Appointments Commission]].\n\nIn the 1960s, Kindgland House, another C19th gentleman's residence was acquired by the school and adapted for use for central catering for all pupils (previously food had been arranged in houses).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/101270614-kingsland-house-shrewsbury|title=Kingsland House, Shrewsbury, Shropshire|last=Stuff|first=Good|website=britishlistedbuildings.co.uk|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n[[Eric Anderson (teacher)|Sir Eric Anderson]] served as headmaster between 1975 and 1980.  He went on to be Rector of [[Lincoln College, Oxford]], chairman of the [[National Lottery Heritage Fund|Heritage Lottery Fund]] and [[Provost of Eton]], among other roles.  \n\nIn 1988, another Georgian villa house, the Grove, was bought and adapted for use as boarding house.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/event/30-years-grove|title=30 Years of the Grove|date=2018-06-22|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n=== 2000s ===\n[[File:Shrewsbury School 4.JPG|alt=|thumb|To mark the turn of the Millennium, Shrewsbury unveiled a monument of an old boy, [[Charles Darwin]].]]\nSince the turn of the millennium, the school's site has seen investment, beginning with the addition of a statue of alumnus Charles Darwin being added to the site to mark the millennial, which was unveiled by [[David Attenborough|Sir David Attenborough]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://statues.vanderkrogt.net/object.php?webpage=ST&record=gbwm018|title=Shrewsbury - Charles Darwin|website=statues.vanderkrogt.net|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>  \n\nA new music school, The Maidment Building, was opened by [[Prince Charles|HRH Prince Charles]] in 2001.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tes.co.uk/jobDetailsBronze_schoolInfo.aspx?ac=2961750&qry=parametrics%3DJOBCATEGORYCODE%7C10635%2CJOBCATEGORYCODE%7C10804%26PageNo%3D1&rslt=3&cur=3&UK=true|title=Shrewsbury School|work=TES|accessdate=21 April 2011}}</ref> \n\nA new boarding house has been completed (2006)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bhn.co.uk/boarding-house-shrewsbury-school|title=Shrewsbury School Boarding House - Mary Sidney Hall|website=www.bhn.co.uk|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>, as has a indoor cricket centre (2006)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/gmr-cricket-centre|title=GMR Cricket Centre|date=2017-07-28|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> and a new swimming pool (2007)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/swimming-pool|title=Swimming Pool|date=2017-07-28|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>.\n\nGirls were admitted to the school for the first time into the sixth-form in 2008, and the school became fully coeducational in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/news/education/2011/09/19/girls-given-go-ahead-to-join-shrewsbury-school/|title=Girls given go-ahead to join Shrewsbury School|website=www.shropshirestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012 the rowing facilities  was extend with a new Yale Boat house, which was opened by Olympian [[Matt Langridge]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishrowing.org/2012/10/langridge-launches-shrewsbury-boathouse/|title=Langridge launches Shrewsbury boathouse|date=2012-10-10|website=British Rowing|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>  A new Computing and Design faculty building, \"the Chatri Design Centre\" was established in 2017, re-purposing and redeveloping a former humanities building.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bhn.co.uk/chatri-design-centre-shrewsbury-school|title=Shrewsbury School - Chatri Design Centre|website=www.bhn.co.uk|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> In 2015 a new building, Hodgeson Hall, was built to house the 5 humanities departments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://adrianjames.com/project/shrewsbury-school/|title=Hodgson Hall: Shrewsbury School - Education Project - Adrian James Architects Oxford|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nThe addition of a new theater was announced in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/news/local-hubs/shrewsbury/2018/09/05/new-plans-for-school-theatre/|title=New plans for school theatre|last=Reynolds|first=Jordan|website=www.shropshirestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessleader.co.uk/shropshire-firm-lands-2-3m-refurbishment-for-shrewsbury-school/68682/|title=Shropshire firm lands \u00a32.3m refurbishment for Shrewsbury School {{!}} Business Leader News|date=2019-06-11|website=Business Leader|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\n==Sports==\nThe main sport in the Michaelmas (autumn) term is football, in the Lent term [[fives]] and rugby, and in summer cricket. Rowing takes place in all three terms. The kit of many of the sports teams shows a cross from the crown in the school's coat of arms, which is a practice that has been in place for at least 150 years. Up until recently, the Maltese cross was used solely by the school\u2019s boatclub. \n\nAdmission of girls in 2015 has seen the introduction of field hockey, netball and lacrosse, with cricket and tennis played during the summer term.\n\nThe present school buildings in Kingsland are arranged around the sports fields which have nine grass football pitches and one of [[Astroturf]]; almost all boys play football in the [[Michaelmas term]].<ref name=\"football\">{{cite web|url=http://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/football|title=Football|year=2011|publisher=Shrewsbury School}}</ref>\n=== Football ===\nSalopians were prominent in the early history of the organised game at [[Cambridge University]], according to Adrian Harvey \"Salopians formed a club of their own in the late 1830s/early 1840s but that was presumably absorbed by the [[Cambridge University A.F.C.|Cambridge University Football Club]] that they were so influential in creating in 1846\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Harvey|first=Adrian|title=Football: The first hundred years|publisher=Routledge|year=2005|page=251}}</ref> The school has an 1856 copy of the [[Cambridge rules]] of football, predating the 1863 rules of [[The Football Association|the FA]].  \n\nThis is in contrast to the resistance to football in the earliest years of the 1800s (paralleled at other public schools at the time), with the school authorities deeming football \"only fit for butchers boys\"<ref>{{Cite book|last=Shephard, Roy J.,|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/1005231187|title=A history of health & fitness : implications for policy today|isbn=978-3-319-65097-5|location=Cham, Switzerland|oclc=1005231187}}</ref>. [[File:School Boathouse Shrewsbury (20960693446).jpg|alt=|thumb|Shrewsbury School viewed from [[The Quarry (park)|The Quarry]], with the school's boathouse in the foreground.]]\n\n=== Rowing ===\nTh Royal Shrewsbury School Boat Club (RSSBC) is one of the oldest school rowing clubs, having been founded in 1866. \n\nSince the boat club began rowing at [[Henley Royal Regatta]] in 1912, they have won 14 times. Shrewsbury is only seconded in victories at [[Henley Royal Regatta|Henley]] to Eton, having won specifically:\n\n* Elsenham Cup:\u00a01919\u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0\n* Princess Elizabeth Challenge Cup: 1955, 1957, 1960, 1961, 2007\n* Ladies\u2019 Challenge Plate Winner: 1932\n* Special Race for Schools/Fawley Challenge Cup: 1975,1976, 1980, 1981, 1982, 1984, 1985<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/henley|title=Henley|date=2011-03-28|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Royal Shrewsbury School Boat Club Rowing Blade.svg|alt=Royal Shrewsbury School Boat Club Rowing Blade|thumb|Royal Shrewsbury School Boat Club Rowing Blade, this cross emblem is commonly used by sports teams, and has been for around 150 years, but for a period was reserved for the first VIII.  This arrangement is also used as the flag of the boat club, while other sports use the school's banner of arms]]\nShrewsbury is one of only two public schools to have [[bumps race]]s, the other being [[Eton College|Eton]], between the houses. They are rowed over four evenings at the end of term in July. There are usually three boats entered per house. On the fourth evening there are prizes for the leaders of the chart and the Leadbitter Cup for the boat which has made the most bumps over the four nights. The event is marshalled by senior rowers and rowing prefects, usually masters. The crew training is mainly pupil driven, though in preparation for [[Henley Royal Regatta|Henley]] the school's First VIII rowers often do not take part, and therefore the boats are composed of other rowers and some non-rowers. Previously, races were run every day until there were no more bumps (i.e. until they were nominally in speed order). This historical set-up could lead to weeks of racing and it was therefore abandoned in favour of a four-day version more than 100 years ago. Otherwise, it is only [[Oxford University|Oxford]] and [[Cambridge University|Cambridge]] that continue to have bumps. Shrewsbury and Eton both race bumps in fours whilst Oxford and Cambridge race in eights.\n\n=== Running ===\nThe Royal Shrewsbury School Hunt (RSSH or \"the Hunt\") is the oldest cross-country club in the world, with written records (the Hound Books) going back to 1831 and evidence that it was established by 1819.<ref name=\"Robinson\">{{cite journal|last=Robinson|first=Roger|date=December 1998|title=On the Scent of History|journal=Running Times|page=28}}</ref> The sport of \"the Hunt\" or \"the Hounds\", now known as a [[Paper Chase (game)|Paper Chase]], was formalised at the school around 1800. Two runners (the \"foxes\") made a trail with paper shreds and after a set time they would be pursued by the other runners (the \"hounds\"). The club officers are the Huntsman and Senior and Junior Whips. The hounds start most races paired into \"couples\" as in real [[fox hunting]]; the winner of a race is said to \"kill\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/history-tucks|title=History of The Tucks|year=2011|publisher=Shrewsbury School}}</ref> In his 1903 semi-autobiographical novel ''[[The Way of All Flesh]]'', Old Salopian [[Samuel Butler (novelist)|Samuel Butler]] describes a school based on Shrewsbury where the main protagonist's favourite recreation is running with \"the Hounds\" so \"a run of six or seven miles across country was no more than he was used to\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Butler|first=Samuel|title=The Way of All Flesh|title-link=The Way of All Flesh|publisher=Project Gutenberg|year=1903|chapter=39|authorlink=Samuel Butler (novelist)|chapter-url=http://www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/2084}}</ref> The first definite record of the Annual Steeplechase is in 1834, making it the oldest cross-country race of the modern era.<ref name=\"Robinson\" /> The main inter-house cross-country races are still called the Junior and Senior Paperchase, although no paper is dropped and urban development means the historical course can no longer be followed. Every October the whole school participates in a 3.5-mile run called \"The Tucks\", originally intended to prevent pupils attending a local horse race.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/tucks|title=The Tucks|year=2011|publisher=Shrewsbury School}}</ref> The school also lays claim to the oldest [[track and field]] meeting still in existence, which originated in the Second Spring Meeting first documented in 1840. This featured a series of mock horse races including the Derby Stakes, the Hurdle Race, the Trial Stakes and a programme of throwing and jumping events, with runners being entered by \"owners\" and named as though they were horses.<ref name=\"Robinson\" />\n\n=== Cricket ===\nCricket was being played at Shrewsbury at least as long ago as the 1860s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/news/nostalgia/2018/09/15/did-photographer-call-out-cricketer-with-dirty-pads/|title=Did photographer call out Shrewsbury School cricketer with dirty pads?|last=Neal|first=Toby|website=www.shropshirestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> A reference was made to an effort to set up a game with Westminster School in 1866 (declined by Westminster) in a House of Commons debate by [[Jim Prior]] in 1961.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/commons/1961/jun/16/public-schools-entry|title=PUBLIC SCHOOLS (ENTRY) (Hansard, 16 June 1961)|website=api.parliament.uk|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\n=== Eton Fives ===\n[[Eton Fives]] is major sport within the school and it has 14 Fives courts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/fives|title=Fives|date=2011-03-28|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> \n\n=== Minor Sports ===\nMinor sports include: shooting, fencing, basketball, golf, equestrian, badminton, swimming and squash.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/other-participation-sports|title=Other (Participation) Sports|date=2013-11-08|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==Houses==\nThe School, as of Michaelmas Term 2020, has 807 pupils: 544 boys and 263 girls. There are eight boys' boarding houses, four girls' boarding houses and two for day pupils, each with its own housemaster or housemistress, tutor team and matron. Each house also has its own colours. \n\nA single house will hold around 60 pupils, although School House and each of the dayboy houses hold slightly more. Having about 90 pupils, School House used to be divided into Doctors (black and white) and Headroom (magenta and white) for most sporting purposes, whilst being one house in other respects, but this distinction was abolished in around 2000.\n\nThere are many inter-house competitions: in football, for instance, each house competes in four different leagues (two senior, two junior) and three knock-out competitions (two senior, one junior). \n\nThe houses and their colours are:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!House!!Colours!!&nbsp;!!Notes\n|-\n|Churchill's Hall|| Dark Blue & Light Blue|| Richard Hudson||{{small|Opened in 1882, listed building}}\n|-\n|The Grove|| Cornflower Blue and White ||Clare Wilson||{{small|Converted to girls' house in summer 2014}}\n|-\n|Ingram's Hall ||Green & White||Sam Griffiths||\n|-\n|Moser's Hall|| Deep Red & Black|| Jane Pattenden ||{{small|Opened in 1884, listed building}}\n|-\n|Oldham's Hall|| Chocolate Brown & White ||Henry Exham||{{small|Opened in 1911, listed building}}\n|-\n|Port Hill || Gold & Red|| Andy Barnard|| rowspan=\"2\" |{{small|Formerly merged as Dayboys Hall}}\n|-\n|Radbrook ||Violet & White|| Richard Case\n|-\n|Ridgemount ||Royal Blue & Old Gold|| William Hughes ||{{small|Opened in 1926, listed building}}\n|-\n|Rigg's Hall|| Chocolate & Gold|| Matthew Barrett||{{small|Opened in 1882, listed building}}\n|-\n|School House|| Black, Magenta & White|| Morgan Bird||\n|-\n|Severn Hill || Maroon & French Grey ||Adam Duncan||{{small|Formerly known as Chances}}\n|-\n|Mary Sidney Hall|| Dark Blue & Pink ||Anita Wyatt ||{{small|Opened in September 2008}}\n|-\n|Emma Darwin Hall ||Wedgwood Blue & Green ||William Reynolds||{{small|Opened in September 2011}}\n|}\n\n==Royal Visits ==\nThe following royal visits have been made to Shrewsbury School:\n\n*[[Princess Louise, Duchess of Argyll|Princess Louise]], visited the school for coffee on 19 January 1898. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newspapers.library.wales/view/3273211/3273215/79/lorne|title=PRINCESS- LOUISE AT SHREWSBURY. '-{{!}}1898-01-20{{!}}Evening Express - Welsh Newspapers|website=newspapers.library.wales|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n* The future [[Edward VIII]], then [[Prince of Wales]], visited in 1932 the  to celebrate the Jubilee of the school's move to the Kingsland site.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://volunteeringshropshiresheritage.wordpress.com/2013/11/15/20th-century-royal-visitors-to-shrewsbury/|title=20th Century Royal Visitors to Shrewsbury|date=2013-11-15|website=volunteeringshropshiresheritage|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n*[[George V]] visited the town of Shrewsbury, and he laid a foundation at the school for a new library by electrical switch from the town's square. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://player.bfi.org.uk/free/film/watch-the-kings-visit-to-the-royal-agricultural-show-shrewsbury-1914-online|title=Watch The King's Visit to the Royal Agricultural Show, Shrewsbury|website=BFI Player|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n*[[Elizabeth II|HM The Queen]] and [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|HRH The Duke of Edinburgh]] visited the school to celebrate its 400 year anniversary of foundation in 1952.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zV4JtRuek8U|title=Video of the Visit of HM The Queen in 1952|last=|first=|date=|website=British Movietone|url-status=live|archive-url=|archivedate=|accessdate=}}</ref>\n*[[Princess Royal|The Princess Royal]] opened the new Shrewsbury School Club, called the Shewsy, in Everton in1974.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/queens-visit-shrewsbury-1952|title=The Queen's visit to Shrewsbury in 1952|date=2012-05-09|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\u00a0\n*[[Princess Margaret, Countess of Snowdon|Princess Margaret]], in 1984, while officially visiting a new library in the town, lunched at the school and had a look at the new Art school.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n*[[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother|The Queen Mother]] came to Kingsland Hall during the headmastership of Donald Wright in the 1990s.<ref name=\":0\" />\u00a0\n*[[Charles, Prince of Wales|The Prince of Wales]] opened the new music school in 2001.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/news/2018/11/14/charles-at-70-we-remember-princes-visits-to-shropshire/|title=Charles at 70: We remember prince's visits to Shropshire and Mid Wales|last=Andrews|first=Mark|website=www.shropshirestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n==Coat of arms and flag==\nThe Arms of the school are those of [[King Edward VI]] being The Arms of England (three lions passant) quartered with those of France (fleur-de-lys).<ref>[http://www.victorianweb.org/victorian/history/education/shrewsburyseal.html \"Shrewsbury School coat of arms\"], The Victorian Web.</ref>\n\nAs a [[banner of arms]], this is also used as the school's flag. \n\n== Grants and prizes ==\nThe school awards a number of prizes, some of which have been running for many years, among these are:\n\n*'''The Sidney Gold Medal''', established 1838, The top award Shrewsbury offers, it originally came with a purse of 50 sovereigns as was awarded to the top classicist going on to [[Oxbridge]]. The Trustees commissioned Sir Edward Thomason to cut the original die and the image was based on a miniature painted by [[George Perfect Harding]] and owned by Dr Kennedy, now in the School collection.\u00a0 The medal was discontinued in 1855 when the stocks were exhausted, but was revived again in 1899.\u00a0 In 1980 the Salopian Club decided that the Medal should be open to all disciplines and not purely the Classics.\u00a0 Since that time the majority of recipients have excelled in the sciences.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/news/sidney-gold-medal-shrewsburys-top-academic-prize|title=The Sidney Gold Medal - Shrewsbury's top academic prize|date=2012-10-15|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n*'''The Arand Haggar Prize''', established 1890, original known as \u201cThe Mathematics Prize\u201d, an almost unbroken run of the annual competition paper stretches back in our archives to 1890. This makes it, possibly, one of the longest continually run mathematics competitions in the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/news/arnold-hagger-mathematics-prize-0|title=The Arnold Hagger Mathematics Prize|date=2019-03-29|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n*'''The Bentley Elocution Prize''', established 1867, candidates are required recite well a poem of at least [[sonnet]] length, introduced by Thomas Bentley, whose career at the School spanned more than 50 years. Past winners include Michael Palin<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/news/bentley-elocution-prizes|title=Bentley Elocution Prizes|date=2013-04-18|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n*'''[[Richard Hillary]] Essay Prize''', established 2013, modled on the single word essay formula used for admission for [[All Souls College, Oxford|All Souls, Oxford]]<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n*'''The Miles Clark Travel Award''', established 1994, recipients of this award have, for instance, cycled around the world for over four years; cycled back to the UK from Siberia, cycled by tandem from the north coast of [[Canada]] to [[Tierra del Fuego]] - anumber of accounts of these travels have been published=.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/miles-clark-travel-scholarship|title=The Miles Clark Travel Scholarship Fund|date=2012-04-24|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n== Societies and speakers  ==\nThere are dozens of organisations known as 'societies', in many of which pupils come together to discuss a particular topic or to [[File:Footpath through Shrewsbury School grounds - geograph.org.uk - 1470032.jpg|thumb|right|The school's site is intersected by shaded paths]]listen to a lecture, presided over by a senior pupil, and often including a guest speaker, they are largely run by the students.\n\nThose in existence at present include: \n\n* Archery\n* Art & Photography \n* Bastille Society (history)\n* Beekeeping\n* Canoe and Kayak Club\n* Chinese \n* Christian Forum\n* Coding \n* Comedy \n* Cooking\n* Craft and Textiles Club\n* Darwin Society (Science)\n* Debating Society\n* Drama\n* French\n* Junior History Society\n* Maths Club\n* Mindfulness \n* Model Railway Society\n* Paired Reading Society (students visit a local primary school, where they work with younger children on a one-to-one basis in order to help develop their reading skills).\n* Pilates\n* Quizzing \n* Reading\n* Royal Shrewsbury School Shooting Club\n* Sidney Society (literature)\n* Spanish Society\n* STEM \n* Technical Theatre\n\nThere is also a [[Combined Cadet Force]]. \n\nAmong past guest speakers include \n\n* [[William Hague|Lord Hague]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/news/lord-hague-reasons-be-optimistic|title=Lord Hague's 'Reasons to be Optimistic'|date=2020-02-14|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n* [[Michael Heseltine|Lord Heseltine]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/e-newsletter/180202|title=eNewsletter: Friday 2nd February 2018|date=2018-02-01|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n* [[Peter Hennessy|Lord Hennessy]], \n* [[Brian Hutton, Baron Hutton|Lord Hutton]], \n* [[Douglas Hurd|Lord Hurd]], \n* [[Oleg Gordievsky]],\n* [[Colin McColl|Sir Colin McColl]], \n* [[Aidan Hartley]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/news/bastille-society-lectures-0|title=Bastille Society Lectures|date=2020-03-11|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> \n\n== Music and Drama  ==\n\n=== Orchestras, ensembles and Choirs ===\nThe school has the following orchestras ensembles and choirs<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/ensembles-and-choirs|title=Ensembles and Choirs|date=2011-05-09|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>: \n\n* The Symphony Orchestra;\n* The Wind Orchestra;\n* Big Ban;\n* The Pepys Brass Quintet (one of two brass quintets run for the best senior brass players in the school);\n* The Senior Brass Ensemble\n* The Senior String Ensemble \n* The Chamber Choir\n* The Chapel Choir\n* The Community Choir (includes local members who are not part of the school)\n* Jazz Band\n* String quartets\n* Junior and Senior string ensembles\n* Clarinet and sax groups\n* Year-based brass groups\n* Flute Ensemble\n* Tuba and horn quartets\n\n=== Musicals ===\nEvery other year (and sometimes more often), Shrewsbury puts on its own homegrown School Musical which is taken to the[[Edinburgh Festival Fringe]], these have included<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/event/edinburgh-festival-2010-school-musical-what-you-will-15th-20th-august|title=Edinburgh Festival: The 2010 School Musical 'What You Will' 15th-20th August|date=2011-04-28|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>:\n\n* ''Rebecca The Drowned Bride''\n* ''What You Will''\n* ''Bubble''\n* ''Jekyll!''\n\nHigh profile musicians and performers also visit the school with such visitors including: \n\n* [[Jacques Loussier|Jacques Lussier]] , \n* [[The Swingle Singers|The Swingles]],\n* [[Cristina Ortiz]], \n* [[Tenebrae (choir)|Tenebrae Choir]],\n* [[Joe Stilgoe|Joe Stilgoe,]]  \n* [[Jenny Agutter]], \n* [[Voces8]], \n* [[Peter Donohoe (pianist)|Peter Donohoe]] .<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/music-arts-events|title=Music & Arts Events|date=2017-08-09|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n== Praepostors ==\nThe schools' [[Prefect|prefects]] are known as pr\u00e6postors. The word originally referred to a monastic [[prior]] and is late [[Latin]] of the [[Middle Ages]], derived from classical Latin ''praepositus'', \"placed before\".The use of ''praepostor'' in the context of a school is derived from the practice of using older boys to lead or control the younger boys. Privillages associated with the office are a particular tie showing the school's arms and the right to cycle a bike to lessons.\n\n== Awards ==\nHouse and school ties and scarfs are awarded achievements in co-curricular activities. \n\n== Scholarships, exhibitions and bursary support  ==\nVarious measures of financial assistance are available to students associated with need and with ability.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/scholarships-and-bursaries|title=Scholarships and Bursaries|date=2011-03-29|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n== School Song ==\nThe school has its own song, Carmen Salopiense, written in 1916 by the [[Cyril Alington]] who was Headmaster at the time.\n\n\u201cRex Edwarde, te canamus \nPium Fundatorem, \nNec, sodales, sileamus \nRegiam Sororem. \nMente prosequamur grata \nRegem et reginam, \nFautricemque amoena prata \nResonent Sabrinam. Floreat Salopia.\n\n\nNon tacendumst hic priorum \nNobilem Cohortem, \nPlenam vitam huic honorum, \nPleniorem mortem; \nIllius nec nomen turpis \nObruat robigo, \nQui humanae docet stirpis \nUnde sit origo. Floreat Salopia. \n\n\nCeteri dum magistrorum \nLugent breve fatum, \nFas iactare Informatorum \nHic triumviratum: \nNostra tum iubente nympha \n(Rudis forte si sis) \nExardebat Cami lympha, \nExardebat Isis. Floreat Salopia. \n\n\nNimiis stipata turbis \nAnnis plus trecenis, \nSedem schola liquit urbis \nImparem Camenis: \nNescit studium mutari, \nQuique alumnos pridem \nNominis amor praeclari \nNos exercet idem. Floreat Salopia. \n\n\nEditique caro colle \nMatri quam amamus \nArte, libro, remo, folle \nGloriam petamus: \nSic futuros hic per annos \nLaus accumuletur \nEt per ultimos Britannos \nNomen celebretur. Floreat Salopia.\u201d\n\n{{NoteTag|\"... Rex Edwarde, te canamus\n<br>\nPium Fundatorem,\n<br>\nNec, sodales, sileamus\n<br>\nRegiam Sororem.\n<br>\nMente prosequamur grata\n<br>\nRegem et reginam,\n<br>\nFautricemque amoena prata\n<br>\nResonent Sabrinam. Floreat Salopia.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\nNon tacendumst hic priorum\n<br>\nNobilem Cohortem,\n<br>\nPlenam vitam huic honorum,\n<br>\nPleniorem mortem;\n<br>\nIllius nec nomen turpis\n<br>\nObruat robigo,\n<br>\nQui humanae docet stirpis\n<br>\nUnde sit origo. Floreat Salopia.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\nCeteri dum magistrorum\n<br>\nLugent breve fatum,\n<br>\nFas iactare Informatorum\n<br>\nHic triumviratum:\n<br>\nNostra tum iubente nympha\n<br>\n(Rudis forte si sis)\n<br>\nExardebat Cami lympha,\n<br>\nExardebat Isis. Floreat Salopia.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\nNimiis stipata turbis\n<br>\nAnnis plus trecenis,\n<br>\nSedem schola liquit urbis\n<br>\nImparem Camenis:\n<br>\nNescit studium mutari,\n<br>\nQuique alumnos pridem\n<br>\nNominis amor praeclari\n<br>\nNos exercet idem. Floreat Salopia.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\nEditique caro colle\n<br>\nMatri quam amamus\n<br>\nArte, libro, remo, folle\n<br>\nGloriam petamus:\n<br>\nSic futuros hic per annos\n<br>\nLaus accumuletur\n<br>\nEt per ultimos Britannos\n<br>\nNomen celebretur. Floreat Salopia.\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\n(Translated):\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\nTo King Edward from the loyal\n<br>\nsons of his foundation\n<br>\nhymns are due, and to his royal\n<br>\nsister salutation.\n<br>\nLet us, friends, acknowledge proudly\n<br>\nking and queen as founders,\n<br>\nand with Hail Sabrina! loudly\n<br>\nfill the fields around us.  Floreat Salopia!\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\nNext be praise to those accorded\n<br>\nwho were here before us,\n<br>\none who crowned a life much lauded\n<br>\nwith a death more glorious,\n<br>\nand another (ever splendid\n<br>\nhis renown) who teaches\n<br>\nhumankind from whence descended\n<br>\ntheirs and every species.  Floreat Salopia!\n<br>\nOthers mourn headmasters plundered\n<br>\nalmost ere they've seen them:\n<br>\nwe boast three who spanned a hundred\n<br>\nyears and more between them.\n<br>\nIn their day Salopian learning\n<br>\n(all must know the story)\n<br>\nset both Cam and Isis burning\n<br>\nwith Sabrina's glory.  Floreat Salopia!\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\nScholars long by cramps vexatious\n<br>\ncabin'd and frustrated\n<br>\nfrom their town to fields more spacious\n<br>\nfinally migrated.\n<br>\nSites may change, but not ambition:\n<br>\nours has never faltered;\n<br>\nand our forebears' high tradition\n<br>\nwe remain unaltered.  Floreat Salopia!\n<br>\n<br>\n<br>\nOn our hill to serve our Mother\n<br>\nfame through art we'll give her,\n<br>\nfame in learning, as we love her,\n<br>\nfame on field and river.\n<br>\nPraise on praise be hers, and never\n<br>\nmay we fail to seek it,\n<br>\npraise that shall be heard wherever\n<br>\nBritish tongues can speak it.  Floreat Salopia!.\"<ref>{{cite book |first=Basil |last=Oldham |authorlink= |title=Boy |title-link=Boy (book) |year=1952 |publisher=B. Blackwell}}</ref>}} <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/features/school-song|title=School song|date=2011-03-28|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}} {{refn}}</ref>\n\n== Ancient Library ==\nThe school has an ancient library, containing various significant antiquarian books and other items.  Particular highlights of the collection include:\n\n* Charles Darwin's school atlas, along with books, manuscripts and letters ;\n* [[Isaac Newton|Newton]]'s 'Principia', acquired on publication in 1687;\n* some forty medieval manuscripts, including a fine twelfth-century Gradual from [[Haughmond Abbey]] and the Lichfield Processional with its unique liturgical English plays of circa 1430 and [[Polyphonic Music|polyphonic music]]\n* the [[death mask]] of [[Oliver Cromwell]]<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n== Art Collection ==\nThe Moser Gallery, within the library buildings, contains part of the school's collection of paintings.  This includes work by [[J. M. W. Turner|J. M. W Turner]], important nineteenth century water colours, and work by [[Kyffin Williams]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.watercolourworld.org/collection/moser-gallery-shrewsbury-school|title=The Moser Gallery at Shrewsbury School|date=2019-04-04|website=Watercolour World|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> \n\n==Headmasters==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=22em|\n*2018\u2013 : Leo Winkley\n*2010\u201318: Mark Turner\n*2001\u201310: Jeremy W. R. Goulding\n*1988\u20132001: Ted Maidment\n*1981\u201388: Simon J. B. Langdale\n*1975\u201380: [[Sir Eric Anderson]]\n*1963\u201375: [[Donald Wright (schoolmaster)|A. R. D. Wright]]\n*1950\u201363: John \"Jock\" Magnus Peterson\n*1944\u201350: [[John Wolfenden, Baron Wolfenden]]\n*1932\u201344: Henry Harrison Hardy (father of the actor [[Robert Hardy]])\n*1917\u201332: Harold A. P. Sawyer\n*1908\u201317: [[Cyril Alington|Cyril Argentine Alington]]\n*1866\u20131908: [[Henry Whitehead Moss]]\n*1836\u201365: [[Benjamin Hall Kennedy]]\n*1798\u20131836: [[Samuel Butler (schoolmaster)|Dr Samuel Butler]] (afterwards [[Bishop of Lichfield]])\n*1771\u201398: Revd. J. Atcherley\n*1754\u201370: Charles Newling\n*1735\u201354: Leonard Hotchkiss\n*1727\u201335: Robert Phillips\n*1723\u201327: Revd. H. Owen\n*1687\u20131723: Revd. R. Lloyd\n*?1646\u201387: Revd. A. Taylor\n*1645{{ndash}}62: Thomas Pigott (deprived under [[Act of Uniformity 1662|Act of Uniformity]])\n*1637\u201345: Revd. Thomas Chaloner (expelled by Parliamentarians, died 1664)\n*1583\u20131635: John Meighen\n*1571\u201383: T. Lawrence\n*1561\u201371: [[Thomas Ashton (schoolmaster)|Thomas Ashton]]\n}}\n\n==Notable masters==\n*[[Nick Bevan]], housemaster, rowing coach, later headmaster of [[Shiplake College]]\n*[[Anthony Chenevix-Trench]], housemaster of School House, later headmaster of [[Bradfield College]], [[Eton College]] and [[Fettes College]]\n*[[Frank McEachran]]<ref>'Frank McEachran', obituary in ''Books and Bookmen'', vol. 20 (Hanson Books, 1975), pp. 58\u201359.</ref>\n*[[Ronald Knox|The Reverend Monsignor Ronald Knox]], English Catholic priest, theologian, author and broadcaster\n*[[David Profumo]], 6th Baron Profumo, teacher and novelist\n*[[Sir William Gladstone, 7th Baronet]], teacher and officer\n\n== Affiliate Schools ==\nShrewsbury has the following affiliate schools:\n\n* [[Shrewsbury International School, Bangkok]]. located on the banks of the [[Chao Phraya River]], opened 2003;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://whichschooladvisor.com/thailand/school-review/shrewsbury-international-school-bangkok-riverside|title=Shrewsbury International School Bangkok (Riverside) Review|website=whichschooladvisor.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n* Shrewsbury International School, [[Hong Kong]], opened 2018;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/shrewsbury-hong-kong|title=Shrewsbury Hong Kong|date=2017-08-01|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.edu.hk/|title=British Primary School {{!}} Shrewsbury International School Hong Kong|website=www.shrewsbury.edu.hk|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n* [[Packwood Haugh School]], is a Shropshire Preparatory School which united with Shrewsbury School in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/news/education/2019/05/15/merger-will-see-shropshire-school-family-grow/|title=Merger will see Shropshire school family grow|last=Robertson|first=Dominic|website=www.shropshirestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n==Fess and Admission ==\nPupils are admitted at the age of 13 by selective examination,<ref name=\"isi report\" /> and for approximately ten per cent of the pupils, English is a second or additional language.<ref name=\"ofsted\" /> The fees at Shrewsbury are up to \u00a312,980 a term for UK students and up to \u00a313,500 a term for international students, with three terms per academic year in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/fees|title=Fees|date=29 March 2011|website=Shrewsbury School}}</ref> \n\n==Old Salopians==\n{{See also|List of Old Salopians}}\nFormer pupils are referred to as [[:Category:People educated at Shrewsbury School|Old Salopians]] (from the old name for [[Shropshire]]).\n[[File:Charles darwin.gif|alt=Charles Darwin, Old Salopian, naturalist|thumb|Charles Darwin, naturalist]]\n[[File:AndrewIrvine.jpg|alt=Andrew Ivine, Old Salopian, part of the 1924 Everest Expedition|thumb|Andrew Ivine, part of the 1924 Everest Expedition. ]]\n[[File:Michael Palin (2).jpg|alt=Michael Palin, Old Salopian, member of Monty Plyton|thumb|Michael Palin, member of Monty Plyton]]\n[[File:Lord Heseltine (6969083278).jpg|alt=Michael Heseltine, former Deputy Prime Minister|thumb|Michael Heseltine, Old Salopian, former Deputy Prime Minister  ]]\n[[File:NSRW Phillip Sidney.jpg|alt=Sir Phillip Sidney, Old Slaopian, solidier, courtier and poet|thumb|Sir Phillip Sidney, solidier, courtier and poet ]]\n\n=== Contemporary Old Salopians  ===\n\n'''1930s'''\n\n* [[James Adams (diplomat)|Sir William Adams]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|KCMG}} (born 1932), ambassador to [[Tunisia]] 1984{{ndash}}87 and [[Egypt]] 1987{{ndash}}92\n* [[Peter Brown (historian)|Peter Brown]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FBA}} (born 1935), historian of [[Late Antiquity]] and Fellow of [[All Souls College, Oxford]]\n* [[Christopher Booker]] (born 1937), journalist, founder of ''[[Private Eye]]''\n* [[Michael Heseltine]], Baron Heseltine {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CH|PC}} (born 1933), politician and [[Deputy Prime Minister]]\n* [[Brian Hutton, Baron Hutton]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|PC|QC}} (born 1931), Law Lord, [[Lord Chief Justice of Northern Ireland]] and Chairman of Hutton Inquiry\n* [[Christopher Gill]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|RD}} (born 1936), politician\n* [[Richard Ingrams]] (born 1937), journalist, founder of ''[[Private Eye]]''\n* [[Colin McColl|Sir Colin Hugh Verel McColl]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|KCMG}} (born 1932), head of the [[Secret Intelligence Service]] (MI6)\n* [[Michael Simmons (RAF officer)|Air Marshall Sir Michael Simmons]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|KCB|AFC}} (born 1937), Royal Air Force Officer, Assistant Chief of the Air Staff\n\n'''1940s'''\n\n* [[Richard Barber]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRSL|FSA|FRHistS}} (born 1941), historian\n* [[Richard Best, Baron Best]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE|DL|FAcSS}} (born 1945), politician\n* [[Piers Brendon]] (born 1940), writer\n* [[Robert Corbett (British Army officer)|Major General Sir Robert John Swan Corbett]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|KCVO|CB}} (born 1940), [[List of Commandants of Berlin Sectors|Commandant of the British Sector in Berlin]] 1987-90\n* [[Peter Davis (businessman)|Sir Peter Davis]] (born 1941), businessman and chairman of [[Sainsbury's]]\n* [[Edward Foljambe, 5th Earl of Liverpool]] (born 1944), Conservative politician and peer\n* [[Martin Ferguson Smith]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE|FSA}} (born 1941), scholar, writer and Classics and Ancient History professor at [[Durham University|Durham]]\n* [[Robin Hodgson, Baron Hodgson of Astley Abbotts]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE}} (born 1942), politician and [[life peer]]\n* [[Stephen Jessel]] (born 1942), BBC correspondent\n* [[David Lovell Burbidge]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE|DL}} (born 1943), [[High sheriff]] of the West Midlands County 1990\u201391\n* [[Baron Rochester|David Lamb, 3rd Baron Rochester]] (born 1944), noble\n* [[Christopher MacLehose]] (born 1940), publisher\n* [[Terry Milewski]] (born 1949), journalist\n* [[Nick Owen]] (born 1947), TV presenter\n* [[Sir Mark Moody-Stuart]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|KCMG}} (born 1940), ex-chairman of [[Royal Dutch Shell]] and Chairman of the UN Global Compact committee\n* [[Michael Palin|Sir Michael Palin]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CBE|FRGS}} (born 1943), actor and TV presenter\n* [[Richard Passingham]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRS}} (born 1943), neurologist\n* [[Nicholas Penny|Sir Nicholas Penny]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FBA|FSA}} (born 1949), art historian, Director of the National Gallery\n* [[Martin Rees, Baron Rees of Ludlow]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OM|FRS|FREng|FMedSci|FRAS}} (born 1942), Astronomer Royal, erstwhile Master of [[Trinity College, Cambridge]], ex-President of [[Royal Society]]\n* [[Sykes Baronets|Sir Francis John Badcock Sykes, 10th Baronet]] (born 1942), businessman\n* [[Tom Macan|Thomas Townley Macan]] (born 1946), Governor and Commander-in-Chief of the [[British Virgin Islands]]\n* [[Roddy Llewellyn|Sir Roderic Victor Llewellyn, 5th Baronet]] (born 1947), author and partner of [[Princess Margaret, Countess of Snowdon]]\n* [[Selby Whittingham]] (born 1941), art expert\n* [[Vernon baronets|Sir James William Vernon, 5th Baronet]] (born 1949), landowner and accountant\n* [[Christopher Wallace (British Army officer)|Sir Christopher Wallace]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|KBE|DL}} (born 1943), Lieutenant General and Royal Green Jackets\n* [[Stephen Wright (diplomat)|Sir Stephen Wright]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|KCMG}} (born 1946), diplomat, [[Under-Secretary]] at the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]], Ambassador to Spain\n\n'''1950s'''\n\n* [[Bruce Clark (journalist)|Bruce Clark]] (born 1958), author and International Security Editor of [[The Times]]\n* [[Stephen Glover (columnist)|Stephen Glover]] (born 1952), journalist & columnist\n* [[Tim Lamb|Timothy Edward Lamb]] (born 1959), cricketer and sports administrator\n* [[Sir John Auld Mactaggart, 4th Baronet]] (born 1951), entrepreneur and philanthropist\n* [[Jonathan Marland, Baron Marland|Jonathan Peter Marland, Baron Marland]] (born 1956), Treasurer of the Conservative Party\n* [[Andrew McFarlane (judge)|Sir Andrew McFarlane]] (born 1954), [[Lord Justice of Appeal]] in England and [[Wales]]\n* [[Philip Campbell (scientist)|Sir Philip Montgomery Campbell]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRAS|FInstP}}  (born 1951), astrophysicist and editor-in-chief of [[Nature (journal)|Nature]]\n* [[Michael Proctor (academic)|Michael Proctor]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRS|FIMA|FRAS}} (born 1950), academic and [[Provost (education)|Provost]] of [[King's College, Cambridge]]\n* [[Nicholas Rankin]] (born 1950), writer and broadcaster\n* [[John Ryle (writer)|Johnathan Ryle]] (born 1952), writer, anthropologist and professor at [[Bard College]]\n* [[Desmond Shawe-Taylor]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|LVO}} (born 1955), art historian, Surveyor of the Queen's Pictures\n* [[John Shawe-Taylor|Jonathon Shawe-Taylor]] (born 1953), Director of the Centre for Computational Statistics and Machine Learning at [[University College, London|University College]], London\n* [[John Stuttard|Sir John Stuttard]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|JP|FCA}} (born 1945), Alderman and [[Lord Mayor of the City of London]] 2006\u201307\n\n'''1960s''' \n\n* [[Andrew Berry]] (born 1963), biologist and lecturer of Organismic and Evolutionary Biology at [[Harvard University|Harvard]]\n* [[Simon Baynes]] (born 1960), politician \n* [[Tim Booth]] (born 1960), musician\n* [[Nick Hancock]] (born 1962), actor and TV presenter\n* [[Clive Johnstone|Clive Carruthers Johnstone]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CB|CBE}} (born 1961), Royal Navy officer and Commander of the [[Allied Maritime Command]]\n* [[Baron Hampton|John Humphrey Arnott Pakington, 7th Baron Hampton]] (born 1964), landowner and photographer\n* [[Nicholas Jarrold]] (born 1959), Ambassador to [[Croatia]] 2000\u20132004 and to [[Latvia]] 1996\u20131999\n* [[Jonathan Legard]] (born 1961), journalist and broadcaster\n* [[Jonathan Lord]] (born 1962), politician\n* [[Twm Morys]] (born 1961), poet and musician.\n* [[Mark Oakley]] (born 1968), Canon Chancellor of [[St. Paul's Cathedral]] and Dean of [[St John\u2019s College, Cambridge]]\n* [[Angus Pollock]] (born 1962), cricketer for [[Cambridge University Cricket Club]]\n* [[Simon Shackleton]] (born 1968), DJ, musician\n* [[Martin Wainwright]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|MBE}} (born 1960), journalist and author\n\n'''1970s'''\n\n* [[Charles Robertson-Adams]] (born 1976), athlete\n* [[Jonty Heaversedge]] (born 1971), TV doctor\n* [[Christopher Hope]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRSL}} (born 1972), journalist, political editor of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''\n* [[Alastair Humphreys]] (born 1976), adventurer and author\n\n'''1980s'''\n\n* [[Line of succession to the Bruneian throne|Omar \u2018Ali Bolkiah]] (born 1986), [[Crown Prince]] of the [[Sultanate of Brunei]]\n* [[Anthony Mangnall|Anthony Magnall]] (born 1989), MP for [[Totnes (UK Parliament constituency)|Totnes]]\n* [[Richard Bridgeman, 7th Earl of Bradford|Alexander Orlando Bridgeman, Viscount Newport]] (born 1980), businessman and landowner\n* [[Big Brother (British series 10)|Freddie Fisher]] (born 1985), actor \n* [[Richard Goulding]] (born 1980) actor\n* [[Ian Massey]] (born 1985), cricketer, [[Cambridge University Cricket Club|Cambridge MCCU]] and [[Herefordshire County Cricket Club|Herefordshire]]\n* [[Joshua Sasse]] (born 1987), actor\n*[[Will Tudor]] (born 1987), actor\n\n'''1990s'''\n\n*[[James Taylor (cricketer, born 1990)|James Taylor]] (born 1990), Nottinghamshire and England cricketer\n*[[Claas Mertens]] (born 1992), German rower\n<!-- Please add deceased alumni to the separate List Of Old Salopians -->\n<!-- Proof of attendance is required -Please do not add Old Salopians who do not have a Wiki page, unless references are added.-->\n\n===Victoria Cross holders===\nTwo Old Salopians received the [[Victoria Cross]], both in the [[First World War]], 1914\u201318.\n*[[Thomas Tannatt Pryce]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|VC|MC}}\n*[[Harold Ackroyd]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|VC|MC}}\n\n=== Old Salopain Activities ===\nThe \"Old Salopian Club\", now known as the Salopian Club, was founded in 1886.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iwm.org.uk/collections/item/object/1500040698|title=Old Salopian Club, founded 1886 year-book, thirty-third issue; April 1921|website=Imperial War Museums|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>  A number of reunions, clubs and activities are arranged by the club.  The post nominals OS are used to denote Old Saloplians. .<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/salopian-club-has-been-furloughed-until-further-notice|title=The Salopian Club has been furloughed until further notice.|date=2011-03-14|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> \n\n==== Sports ====\nFormer members of the school have various sporting clubs:\n\n* Rowing is arranged by the \"Sabrina Club\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/os-rowing-sabrina|title=OS Rowing - Sabrina|date=2011-03-28|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>, which fields crews, including for Henley Royal Regatta<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hrr.co.uk/henley-royal-regatta-list-of-2019-entries|title=Henley Royal Regatta List of 2019 entries {{!}} Henley Royal Regatta|website=www.hrr.co.uk|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> as well as supporting the school crews at various events\n* Cricket is arranged by the \"Saracens\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/os-cricket-saracens|title=OS Cricket - Saracens|date=2011-05-20|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n* Old Salopian golf, yachting, fives cross country, tennis, football, squash and basket ball are also provided for.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/os-sport|title=OS Sport|date=2011-05-18|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\n==== Careers, arts and activities ====\nArrangements for cultural engagement of former members if the school, for instance concerts and plays and art exhibitions are also put on, and there is a programme around around careers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/os-arts-and-activities|title=OS Arts and Activities|date=2011-05-18|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/os-careers|title=OS Careers|date=2012-10-02|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\n== Social Action  ==\n\n=== Shrewsbury House - 'The Shewsy' ===\nShrewsbury House is a youth and community centre attached to St Peter's Church in [[Everton, Liverpool|Everton]], [[Liverpool]].  It was founded in 1903 by masters from Shrewsbury School, it employs two full-time trained youth workers and a team of part-time staff and offers young people in the local area an excellent range of facilities and sporting and recreational opportunities. 'The Shewsy' runs Junior Clubs for children aged 5 - 11 and Senior Clubs for those aged 12 - 20 throughout the week, as well as a variety of weekend activities, including residential trips and exchange visits.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/page/the-shewsy|title=Shrewsbury House - 'The Shewsy'|date=2011-03-28|website=Shrewsbury School|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.shrewsburyhouse.org.uk/|title=Shrewsbury House {{!}} Youth Club|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\n=== Other Outreach ===\nDuring the [[coronavirus]] [[pandemic]] of 2020 the school donated over 1,600 items of [[personal protective equipment]] to the [[National Health Service|NHS]], including face shields it had 3D printed in its technology labs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/news/local-hubs/shrewsbury/2020/04/13/shrewsbury-school-donates-ppe-in-covid-19-fight/|title=Shrewsbury School donates PPE in Covid-19 fight|last=Humphreys|first=Nick|website=www.shropshirestar.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>  It also opened up rooms in its boarding houses for use for NHS staff.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boarding.org.uk/media/news/article/13563/2-500-boarding-beds-offered-in-the-fight-against-coronavirus|title=2,500+ boarding beds offered in the fight against coronavirus|website=www.boarding.org.uk|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n== Talargerwyn ==\nThe School owns Talargerwyn, a farm house situated in the Forest above Betws-y-Coed in central Snowdonia. It can accommodate up to twenty boys and staff and is used at week-ends in term-time throughout the year as a base for field work and expeditions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://files.api.beta.ofsted.gov.uk/v1/file/1585723|title=Inspection Report, Boarding School, Shrewsbury School|last=Commission of Socail Care Inspection|first=|date=2004|website=Ostead|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Controversy ==\nIn September 2005, the school was one of fifty independent schools operating [[Independent school fee fixing scandal|independent school fee-fixing]], in breach of the [[Competition Act 1998|Competition Act, 1998]]. All of the schools involved were ordered to abandon this practice, pay a nominal penalty of \u00a310,000 each and to make ex-gratia payments totalling three million pounds into a trust designed to benefit pupils who attended the schools during the period in respect of which fee information had been shared.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Halpin|first=Halpin|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/independent-schools-face-huge-fines-over-cartel-to-fix-fees-rcwcznjnvnt|title=Independent schools face huge fines over cartel to fix fees|access-date=2020-02-29|issn=0140-0460}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20100402135855tf_/http://www.oft.gov.uk/news/press/2006/182-06|title=Office of Fair Trading Press Release|last=|first=|date=21 December 2006|website=National Ara chive|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=29 Feb 2020}}</ref> \n\n==See also==\n*[[Listed buildings in Shrewsbury (outer areas)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n* Alan Stewart, \"Philip Sidney: A Double Life\", Chatto and Windus, 2000. {{ISBN|0-7011-6859-5}}\n* \"Shrewsbury Library: Its History and Restoration\" \u2013 A.M Carr Shropshire Libraries 1983\n\n==Further reading==\n*[[Parliament of the United Kingdom|UK Parliament]] ''Clarendon Report'' (London: HM Stationery Office 1864) \n*[[iarchive:annalsshrewsbur01hillgoog|Annals of Shrewsbury School]], George William Fisher & John Spencer Hill (1899)\n* [https://archive.org/details/historyofshrewsb00blak History of Shrewsbury School, 1551\u20131888], [[John Brickdale Blakeway]] & Alfred Rimmer (1889)\n*Draisey, M., ''Thirty Years On! A Private View of Public Schools'' (Halsgrove,  2014 {{ISBN|978-0857042118}})\n*Gee, D., ''City on a Hill - A Portrait of Shrewsbury School'' (Somerset, Greenbank Press, 2015, {{ISBN|9780952369981}})\n*Bloomfield, R., ''History of Rowing at Shrewsbury School'' (2005)\n*Oldham, J.B., The History of Shrewsbury School (1952)\n*Fanning, P., ''The Divided Self'' (Somerset, Greenbank Press, 2015, {{ISBN|0952369990}})\n*McEachran, F., ''A Cauldron of Spells''  Jan. 1992 (Somerset, Greenbank Press, 1991, {{ISBN|0955398606}})\n*Charlesworth, M.L.,. ''Behind the Headlines'' (Somerset: Greenbank Press, 1994. {{ISBN|0952369915}})\n\n== Notes ==\n{{NoteFoot}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscatinline}}\n* {{Official|https://www.shrewsbury.org.uk/}}\n\n{{Schools in Shropshire}}\n{{Shrewsbury architecture}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n\n[[Category:Boarding schools in Shropshire]]\n[[Category:Independent schools in Shropshire]]\n[[Category:Member schools of the Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in the 1550s]]\n[[Category:1552 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Schools in Shrewsbury]]\n[[Category:Schools with a Royal Charter]]\n", "name_user": "Taniasled", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eFootball:details added)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shrewsbury_School"}
{"title_page": "Leeds and Selby Railway", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2013}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = Leeds and Selby Railway\n| logo             = \n| caption          = \n| type             = \n| genre            = \n| fate             = Track owned by [[Network Rail]], services by various operators\n| predecessor      = Leeds&nbsp;and&nbsp;Hull&nbsp;Railroad&nbsp;Company&nbsp;(1824) ''unbuilt''\n| successor        = ''Leased and acquired by''<br>[[York and North Midland Railway]] 1844<br>''merged into''<br>[[North Eastern Railway (UK)|North Eastern Railway]] 1854<br>[[London and North Eastern Railway]] 1923<br>[[British Rail]] 1948\n| foundation       = 1830 (Act of Parliament)<br>1834 (Opening)\n| founder          = \n| defunct          = \n| location_city    = \n| location_country = \n| location         = \n| locations        = \n| area_served      = \n| key_people       = \n| industry         = \n| products         = \n| services         = \n| revenue          = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income       = \n| aum              = \n| assets           = \n| equity           = \n| owner            = \n| num_employees    = \n| parent           = \n| divisions        = \n| subsid           = \n| homepage         = \n| footnotes        = \n| intl             = \n}}\nThe '''Leeds and Selby Railway''' was an early British railway company and first mainline railway within Yorkshire. It was opened in 1834.\n\nAs built, the line ran west/east between two termini, [[Leeds Marsh Lane railway station|Marsh Lane station, Leeds]] and [[Selby railway station]]. The company was leased and then acquired by the [[York and North Midland Railway]] in 1840 and 1844; the line remained in use through the subsequent [[North Eastern Railway (UK)|NER]], [[London and North Eastern Railway|LNER]], [[British Rail|BR]] and [[History of rail transport in Great Britain 1995 to date|post-privatisation]] periods.\n\nUse of the line was expanded through junction connections to new railways, most built in the late 19th century; a junction with the [[York and North Midland Railway]] in 1839; an end on junction at Selby to Hull ([[Hull and Selby Railway]], 1840); a through route into Leeds and westward (Leeds viaduct extension, 1869); a shortened route to York (Micklefield to Church Fenton, 1869); a line to [[Wetherby]] ([[Cross Gates to Wetherby Line]], 1876, closed 1964); a line to [[Castleford]] ([[Garforth to Castleford Line]], 1878, closed 1969) and a line avoiding Selby for Goole ([[Selby to Goole Line]], 1910, closed 1964) as well as a number of minor and industrial lines and sidings. The [[Selby Diversion]] of the [[East Coast Main Line]] (1983) also made junctions with the Leeds and Selby.\n\nAs of 2014, the line is still in mainline use and use for services operated by [[TransPennine Express]] and [[Northern (train operating company)|Northern]] for services from Leeds to Selby, Hull, York and beyond.\n\n== The Leeds and Selby Railway Company (1830\u20131844) ==\n\n=== Background ===\n{{See also|History of Leeds}}\nBy 1830 Leeds had long been an important town, having become prosperous initially through the manufacture of woollen cloth. The [[Leeds and Liverpool Canal]] was complete and the [[Aire and Calder Navigation]] connected Leeds to the Ouse, and thus to the North Sea and beyond.<ref>{{cite web| url =http://www.leeds.gov.uk/page.aspx?pageidentifier=B08840B63BB604C480256E1B00307E07| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090101103059/http://www.leeds.gov.uk/page.aspx?pageidentifier=B08840B63BB604C480256E1B00307E07|archivedate=1 January 2009 |title = History of the city of Leeds|publisher= Leeds City Council|}}</ref> [[Selby]] had grown in importance as a port since the construction of the [[Selby Canal]] and had become an important inland east coast port for coastal and foreign trade.\n\nAs early as 1814{{#tag:ref|One source ('The Tourist's companion..') gives a date of 16 January 1823 {{harv|Parsons|1835|p=86}}, In 'Annals and History of Leeds' records a proposal as early as 1802.<ref>{{citation|title = The annals and history of Leeds|first= John|last = Mayhall|year= 1860|page = 203|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=mAQWAAAAYAAJ}}</ref>|group=\"note\"}} the ''[[Leeds Mercury]]'' had printed letters promoting the idea of a railway from Leeds to Selby.<ref name=\"early\">[[#LNER|The London & North Eastern Railway (LNER) Encyclopedia]]: [http://www.lner.info/co/NER/selby/selby.shtml The Leeds and Selby Railway], \"Early History\"</ref>\n\n==== The Leeds and Hull Railway ====\nThe Leeds and Hull Railroad Company was formed in 1824 in Leeds. [[George Stephenson]] was appointed as engineer, and he directed [[Joseph Locke]] to survey the line.<ref name=\"t98\">{{harvnb|Tomlinson|1915|pp=98\u201399}}</ref>\n\nStephenson recommended a double track railway, operated by locomotives at a speed of {{convert|8|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|Tomlinson|1915|pp=98\u201399}} The hills on the route out of Leeds were to have three inclined planes to be worked by three stationary engines. The remainder of the line was to be very nearly level.<ref name=\"gg\">{{harvnb|MacTurk|1879|p=17}}</ref>\n\nThe company was one of a number of contemporary projects aimed at linking the east and west sides of northern England, such as the [[Newcastle and Carlisle Railway]] (act of Parliament 1829) and the [[Liverpool and Manchester Railway]] (act of Parliament 1826). The Manchester and Leeds Railroad Company was formed in 1825, and would have completed the Lancashire to Yorkshire link.<ref name=\"t98\"/> Representatives of the company were present at the opening of the [[Stockton and Darlington Railway]] in 1825.{{sfn|Tomlinson|1915|p=114}} Of these schemes the Leeds and Hull, and the Manchester and Leeds were not immediately acted upon, in part due to the [[Panic of 1825|stock market crash of 1825]].<ref name=\"t202\">{{harvnb|Tomlinson|1915|p=202}}</ref><ref group=\"note\">It may have also been that the shareholders were unwilling to commit to building the line until the success or failure of the [[Liverpool and Manchester Railway]] was known.  {{harv|Allen|1974|p=50}}, {{harv|Tomlinson|1915|p=99}}</ref> The Leeds and Hull scheme stagnated, and in the meantime the Knottingley and Goole Canal (an extension of the Aire and Calder Navigation) opened in 1826 bringing the village of [[Goole]] from obscurity, and turning it into a viable transhipment port for Europe.\n\nThe growth of Goole as a port to rival Hull was sufficient to spur the Hull-based shareholders of the Leeds and Hull railway into action; at the end of 1828 they motioned that the railway should be built as far as Selby, with the remainder of the journey to Hull being made by [[Steam Packet|steam packet]], most importantly, bypassing Goole. The shareholders passed the proposal at a general meeting in Leeds on 20 March 1829, and the '''Leeds and Selby Railway Company''' was formed.<ref name=\"t202\"/>\n\n=== Formation of the Leeds and Selby Railway Company ===\n{{Leeds and Selby Railway, 1834}}\nThe Leeds and Hull railway scheme of 1824 was revived as a shortened line from Leeds to Selby and was resurveyed by [[James Walker (engineer)|James Walker]] in 1829;{{sfn|Hoole|1986|p=29}} [[Benjamin Gott]], one of the line's promoters and a wool and cloth magnate thought the inclined planes would be a disadvantage.<ref name=\"gg\"/>\n\nJames Walker reported that the stationary engines could be abandoned, and tunnels and cuttings built in their place. He expected that the additional cost of their construction would be offset by use of the stone elsewhere on the railway and by its sale. The railway would also be of use for the transportation of coal and stone from quarries and mines near the line, such as the Huddlestone quarry. Additionally he suggested that the route of the railway could also be used for the piping of clean water to Leeds. As to the route of the railway, he suggested resiting the Leeds terminus at cheaper and less-developed land around Marsh Lane instead of at Far Bank. The resurveyed line was also deviated to the north away from the river bank, to avoid the objections of the Aire and Calder Undertakers; the more northern path would require passing Richmond Hill requiring either stationary engines or a tunnel; Walker recommended the latter. Outside Leeds, minor deviations were made in order for the line to cross the north\u2013south [[turnpike trust|turnpikes]] using bridges. At Selby, the new plan sited the station further south than the original, which had been sited next to the road bridge, with the intention of crossing the [[River Ouse, Yorkshire|River Ouse]] by widening this bridge; with the line no longer going to Hull but terminating at Selby a site with more space for wharves and jetties was required. He recommended a double track line, with sufficient land acquired for a four track line.<ref>James Walker's report: \"To the Committee of the proposed Leeds and Selby Railway Company\", 18 July 1829, reprinted in full in {{harvnb|MacTurk|1879|pp=18\u201332}}</ref>\n\nMuch of the line was to be built on land belonging to the shareholders, including [[Edward Robert Petre]] who owned land in Selby, and Richard Oliver Gascoigne (who later had built the Aberford Railway). Walker's alterations to Stephenson's original plan were accepted unaltered and put before Parliament.{{sfn|MacTurk|1879|pp=33\u201335, 21(note)}}\n\nDespite strong opposition from the Aire and Calder Navigation, which had a practical monopoly on transportation in the area, a bill was passed in Parliament on 29 May 1830 allowing construction of the line. The company was allowed to raise a total of \u00a3300,000 in shares and loans.<ref name=\"t203\">{{harvnb|Tomlinson|1915|pp=203\u20134}}</ref>{{sfn|Whishaw|1842|p=173}}<ref group=\"note\">An extract from the act on the rates of carriage, as well as a list of subscribers can be found reprinted in \"The Tourist's Companion\".{{harv|Parsons|1835|pp=56\u201360}}</ref> The company's directors were James Audus, [[Edward Baines (1800\u20131890)|Edward Baines]], [[Bland baronets|Thomas Davison Bland]], John Broadley, [[Gascoigne baronets|Richard Oliver Gascoigne]], [[Benjamin Gott]], Robert Harrison, [[John Marshall (disambiguation)|John Marshall]], John Cowham Parker, the Hon. Edward Robert Petrie, John Scholefield and John Wilson. Samuel Wilks Waud was the first company chairman.<ref name=\"t204\">{{harvnb|Tomlinson|1915|pp=204\u2013205}}</ref>\n\n=== Construction, infrastructure and rolling stock ===\nTwo contractors, Messrs. Nowell & Sons and Messrs. Hamer & Pratt, were chosen to carry out the construction of the line. Nowell began construction of the {{convert|2|mi|km}} out of Leeds on 1 October 1830,<ref group=\"note\">The work in Leeds was postponed until February 1831, since there was a possibility that a proposed Leeds & Bradford Railway might be built, giving the possibility of a through link taking a different path. {{harv|Tomlinson|1915|p=205}}</ref> and Hamer & Pratt began work in February 1831 on the remaining {{convert|18|mi|km}} to Selby.<ref name=\"t204\"/>\n\nThe primary engineering feature of the line was the tunnel through [[Richmond Hill, West Yorkshire|Richmond Hill]] in Leeds. It was {{convert|700|yd|m}} long, with its western entrance at {{convert|8|chain|m}} from the Leeds terminus. The tunnel's cross section was that of a [[horseshoe arch]], {{convert|22|ft|m|abbr=on}} at its widest, and {{convert|17|ft|abbr=on}} high from the level of the rails. The construction of the tunnel required the sinking of three shafts, subsequently retained for ventilation.<ref name=\"w176\">{{harvnb|Whishaw|1842|p=176}}</ref><ref name=\"instun\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Walker | first1 = J. | last2 = Smith | first2 = G. | doi = 10.1680/itrcs.1836.24482 | title = On Ventilating and Lighting Tunnels, Particularly in Reference to the One on the Leeds and Selby Railway | journal = ICE Transactions | volume = 1 | issue = 1836 | pages = 95 | year = 1836 | pmid =  | pmc = | url = https://archive.org/stream/transactions01goog#page/n131/mode/1up}}</ref> Excavation of the tunnel yielded mostly shale and coal, with the remaining third being stone which was used as foundations for other parts of the line. The arch was lined with two courses of brickwork, lengthways to a thickness of 20 inches. In some places three courses were used, depending on the strength of the surrounding ground. Volcanic matter was used in the mortar, to obtain a quick-setting and strong cement.{{sfn|Parsons|1835|pp=61\u201363}} The entrances of the tunnel were faced with stone.<ref>{{harvnb|Brees||loc=Series 1, Plate 61}}</ref> There were once reflectors at the base of the shafts, designed to reflect light onto the whitewashed walls of the tunnel.{{sfn|Tomlinson|1915|p=253}} The shafts were found to be useful for ventilation, but the experiment with illuminating the interior with reflect light was of limited utility to passengers; lamps were provided to light the carriages.<ref name=\"instun\"/> Despite the efforts, an early passenger reported that on entering the tunnel:\n\n{{quote|We were immediately enveloped in total darkness, and every one of the carriages filled with smoke and steam to a most annoying degree|Mechanic's magazine (1835)|<ref>{{citation| url =https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=JggAAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA277| journal = The Mechanics' magazine, museum, register, journal, and gazette| volume = 23| date = 4 April \u2013 25 September 1835|publisher  =J. Cunningham|title = Of the Smoke, Noise, &c. in Tunnels|page=277|first=John|last=Herepath}}</ref>{{sfn|Tomlinson|1915|p=259}}}}\n\n[[File:Diagram of section of Leeds and Selby Railway Chair showing rail and key.JPG|thumb|Cross section diagram of Leeds and Selby railway chair, key and rail]]\nAs built, the line had 43 bridges and around 16 level crossings.<ref name=\"wh174\"/> Ballast was of stone chips; the rails were held in place by keys lodged into iron [[Chair (railway)|chairs]] which rested on and were fixed to stone blocks or larch sleepers. On some parts of the line, a [[ladder track]] arrangement of sleepers was used, with longitudinal stone sleepers of {{convert|3|ft|m|abbr=on}} held in gauge by transverse cast-iron rods. T or bar-shaped malleable iron rails of {{convert|35|lb/yd|kg/m|1|abbr=on}} were initially used, within a few years {{convert|42|lb/yd|kg/m|1|abbr=on}} rails were being introduced.<ref name=\"wh174\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Tomlinson|1915|p=255}}, diagrams of rail and track transverse cross section.</ref>\n\nCuttings and embankments were built to keep the gradient of the line to a minimum. The deepest cutting was {{convert|43|ft|m|abbr=on}}, the highest embankment {{convert|54|ft|m|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"t253\">{{harvnb|Tomlinson|1915|pp=253\u2013255}}</ref> Both embankments and cuttings had stone retaining walls at the base, at an angle of 67.5\u00b0 to the horizontal, which reduced the overall width of the earthworks. The line was built as a double-track railway.<ref name=\"wh174\">{{harvnb|Whishaw||loc= First Series|pp=174\u2013178}}</ref>\n\n==== Route and stations ====\nAfter {{convert|8|chain|m}} of level track outside the Leeds terminus, the line generally ascended for a distance of {{miles-chains|4|mi|32|chain|km}} at a maximum slope of 1 in 160; it was then level for {{miles-chains|2|mi|61|chain|km}} after which it generally descended eastwards towards Selby for {{miles-chains|6|mi|6|chain|km}} with a maximum rate of descent of 1 in 137. The final {{miles-chains|6|mi|41|chain|km}} to Selby was practically level with a rate of descent of only 1 in 3785. The highest point was {{convert|132|ft|m|abbr=on}} above the Leeds terminus, with the whole line having a net descent of {{convert|100|ft|m|1|abbr=on}} towards Selby.<ref name=\"wh174\"/>\n\nThe [[Leeds Marsh Lane railway station|Marsh Lane terminus]] in Leeds, and the station at Selby, were early examples of what would become 'railway architecture': both were long rectangular sheds, with wooden trussed roofs, supported internally on cast iron columns.{{sfn|Brees||loc= First series, plates 62 and 63|pp=133\u2013134}} The stations served for both passenger and freight, with additional tracks external to the sheds for coal; there was no platform for passengers. Both stations had coal depots, the Leeds station contained the facilities for maintenance of engines and wagons.<ref>{{harvnb|Tomlinson|1915| pp=253\u2013260|loc=Plates, p.258}}, Station plans reproduced from Brees' Railway Practice, Fourth series, 1847</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Brees||loc= Fourth series, Plate 48 and legend pages cii\u2013ciii}}</ref> The rear of the Selby station backed onto the Ouse, across a road (Ousegate) from jetties that would allow a continuation of the journey to Hull.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.selby.gov.uk/upload/091015_Selby_Old_Station.pdf |title = A brief guide to Selby Railway Station, Yorkshire\u2019s Oldest: Built 1834 |publisher = Selby District Council |accessdate = 15 January 2013 |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120302075154/http://www.selby.gov.uk/upload/091015_Selby_Old_Station.pdf |archivedate = 2 March 2012 |df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAfter the station at Marsh Lane in Leeds were stations at Cross Gates, Garforth, Roman Road, Micklefield, Milford, and Hambleton.{{sfn|Parsons|1835|pp=241\u2013243}}\n\n==== Locomotives ====\nThe original engines were of the lightweight four-wheeled [[Bury Bar Frame locomotive|\"Bury\" type]]<ref>*Whishaw. F., (1842), London: Weale</ref> from [[Edward Bury]] of Liverpool. They were shown to lack traction sufficient for the line, and were sold. Replacements were obtained from [[Fenton, Murray and Jackson]] of ([[Leeds]]) and from [[Thomas Kirtley and Co|Kirtley & Co.]] of [[Warrington]].{{sfn|Tomlinson|1915|pp=391\u20132}}\n\n;Locomotive list\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Wheels !! Builder !! Date introduced !! YNMR no. !! NER no. !! Comments\n|-\n|   ''St Vincent'' || [[2-2-0]] || [[Edward Bury and Company]] || 1834 || \u2013 || \u2013 || To [[Newcastle & North Shields Railway]], 1838<ref name=\"steamindex.com\">http://www.steamindex.com/locotype/nerloco.htm</ref>\n|-\n|   ''Lord Hood'' ||  [[2-2-0]] || [[Edward Bury and Company]] || 1834 || \u2013 || \u2013 || To [[West Hartlepool Harbour & Railway]], 1840<ref name=\"steamindex.com\"/>\n|-\n|   ''Rodney'' || [[2-2-0]] || [[Edward Bury and Company]] || 1834 || \u2013 || \u2013 || To [[West Hartlepool Harbour & Railway]], 1840<ref name=\"steamindex.com\"/>\n|-\n|   ''Nelson'' ||  [[2-2-0]] || [[Fenton, Murray & Jackson]] || 1834 || \u2013 || \u2013 ||  To [[York & North Midland Railway]], 1849<ref name=\"steamindex.com\"/>\n|-\n| ''Exmouth'' ||  [[2-2-0]] || [[Fenton, Murray & Jackson]] || 1836 || \u2013 || \u2013 || To [[West Hartlepool Harbour & Railway]], 1840<ref name=\"steamindex.com\"/>\n|-\n|   ? ||  [[0-2-2]] || [[Robert Stephenson and Company]] || 1830 || \u2013 || \u2013 || Ex-[[List of Liverpool and Manchester Railway locomotives|Liverpool & Manchester Railway]] ''North Star'' (acquired December 1833).<br>\nSold, January 1836<ref name=\"steamindex.com\"/>\n|-\n|   ''Gambier'' or ''Hawke'' ||  [[2-2-2]] || [[Fenton, Murray & Jackson]] || 1836 || 14 || \u2013 ||  <ref name=\"steamindex.com\"/>\n|-\n|   ''Eagle'' or ''Anson'' ||  [[2-2-2]] || [[Fenton, Murray & Jackson]] || 1837 || 15 || \u2013 ||  <ref name=\"steamindex.com\"/>\n|-\n|   ''Dart'' ||  [[2-2-2]] || [[Fenton, Murray & Jackson]] || 1839 || 16 || \u2013 ||  <ref name=\"steamindex.com\"/>\n|-\n| ?  ||  [[2-2-0]] || [[Thomas Kirtley]] || 1839 || 17 || \u2013 ||  <ref name=\"steamindex.com\"/>\n|-\n|   ''Express'' ||  [[2-2-2]] || [[Fenton, Murray & Jackson]] || 1839 || 18 || \u2013 ||  Rebuilt as a tank engine by the YNMR<ref name=\"steamindex.com\"/>\n|-\n| ''Prince''  ||  [[2-2-0]] || [[Thomas Kirtley]] || 1839 || 19 || \u2013 ||  <ref name=\"steamindex.com\"/>\n|-\n| ''Swift''  ||  [[2-2-0]] || [[Thomas Kirtley]] || 1839 || 20 || \u2013 ||  <ref name=\"steamindex.com\"/>\n|-\n| ''Swallow''  ||  [[2-2-0]] || [[Thomas Kirtley]] || 1839 || 21 || \u2013 ||  <ref name=\"steamindex.com\"/>\n|-\n| ''Queen''  ||  [[2-2-0]] || [[Thomas Kirtley]] || 1839 || 22 || \u2013 ||  <ref name=\"steamindex.com\"/>\n|}\n;Notes\n# YNMR = [[York and North Midland Railway]]\n# NER = [[North Eastern Railway (United Kingdom)|North Eastern Railway]]\n# The names and numbers of the Kirtley locomotives may have been transposed\n\n==== Rolling stock ====\nThere were first and second-class [[Passenger car (rail)|carriages]], [[Horse trailer#Railway horse boxes|boxeshorse boxes]] and [[Goods wagon|wagons]], including privately owned wagons.{{sfn|Whishaw|1842|pp=179\u2013180}}\n\n=== Opening and operation ===\nBy 22 September 1834, a single complete line of track had been built, and the railway was officially opened. A train of ten carriages, hauled by the locomotive \"Nelson\", set out from [[Leeds Marsh Lane railway station|Marsh Lane station]] in Leeds at 6.30&nbsp;am. To the embarrassment or amusement of those present, the locomotive got into difficulty on the incline at the tunnel. The wheels began to slip on wet rails, and despite the application of ash on the rails, initial progress was no better than walking pace. Once the high point of the line was reached, better progress was made: at Garforth, on a stretch of track falling 1 in 180 a speed of {{convert|20|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} was attained. Selby was reached before 9&nbsp;am. The return journey took 1 hour and sixteen minutes. On the 23rd, two trains were run each way, with a better timing of 1 hour and five minutes from Leeds to Selby.{{sfn|Tomlinson|1915|pp=256\u20137}}{{sfn|Parsons|1835|pp=77\u201379}}\n\nBoth lines of track were complete by 15 December, when the railway began to take goods traffic.{{sfn|Tomlinson|1915|pp=259\u2013260}}\n\nIn ''The Railways of Britain and Ireland practically described and illustrated'', [[Francis Whishaw]] ascribed the poor financial performance of the railway to the management of the line; after six years of existence, the railway was returning a profit, but the average dividend on a \u00a3100 share over 1837 to 1840 was a meagre one pound, sixteen shillings and nine pence.{{sfn|Whishaw|1842|pp=173, 182\u2013184}}\n\nAs a result of the opening of the line, the Aire and Calder Navigation had to make considerable reductions in their charges.<ref>{{harvnb|Brees|1839|pp=208\u20139}}</ref> Previously, that company's monopoly had resulted in a dividend on shares of over 200%.{{sfn|Tomlinson|1915|p=205}}\n\n=== Connections with other railway lines ===\n{{anchor|York junction}}\n\n==== York and North Midland Railway ====\n{{York Junction, Leeds and Selby Railway, 1840}}\n{{See also|York and North Midland Railway}}\nOn 29 May 1839 the first section of [[George Hudson]]'s York and North Midland Railway opened. It ran from York to a point just to the east of Milford station where a short chord connected it to the Leeds and Selby Railway. The line was extended southwards to Burton Salmon by 11 May 1840; and that line connected by another short chord to the junction with the Leeds and Selby on 9 November 1840.<ref name=\"rh30\">{{harvnb|Hoole|1986|pp=30\u201333}}</ref>\n\nEast of the junction was a station called York Junction.<ref name=\"rh30\"/><ref group=\"note\" name=\"oldj\">After 1850 ''York Junction'' was called ''Old Junction'', in 1867 in became ''Milford Old Junction'', from 1897 it was called ''Gascoigne Wood''. {{harv|Hoole|1986|pp=32\u201333}}</ref>\n\n==== Hull and Selby Railway ====\n{{See also|Hull and Selby Railway}}\nThe original Leeds to Hull plan was completed in 1840 with the construction of a line running almost directly east from Selby to Hull. A bascule bridge was constructed across the Ouse at Selby, just north of the jetties at the rear of the original Selby station. A new station to the west was constructed, and the old station became a goods shed.{{sfn|Hoole|1986|pp=29\u201330}}<ref>Ordnance Survey. Town plans 1:1056, 1849</ref>\n\n==== Aberford Railway ====\n{{Main|Aberford Railway}}\nThe Aberford railway was a private railway built during the same period as the Leeds and Selby Railway by the [[Gascoigne family]]. It  ran from [[Aberford]] and connected at Garforth. It was built primarily to carry coal from the Gascoigne's coal mines but also carried passengers. It closed in 1924.\n\n== History, 1840\u2013present ==\n\n=== Lease and acquisition by the York and North Midland (1840\u20131854) ===\nThe Leeds and Selby Railway offered a direct route into Leeds from the east. [[George Hudson]] had his own route into Leeds (through Castleford via the Whitford and Methey Junctions)  accessed via a working arrangement with the [[North Midland Railway]]. The Leeds and Selby had the potential to offer opportunities to rival companies, as well as a competing route to Hudson's. On 9 November 1840 George Hudson arranged a lease of the Leeds and Selby  for \u00a317,000 per annum.<ref name=\"rh30\"/>{{sfn|Tomlinson|1915|pp=341\u2013342}}\n\nHudson's first act was to close the line to passengers west of Milford; despite his line being 4 miles longer passengers now had no choice but to use it. In 1848 the line west of Milford was closed to freight as well; Marsh Lane station was at that time still a terminus, and so useless for through traffic to Manchester and beyond. Passenger services were reinstated in 1850, but freight continued to run to Leeds via Castleford and not Marsh Lane.<ref name=\"rh30\"/>\n\nIn 1844 an act of Parliament was passed allowing the York and North Midland to absorb the Leeds and Selby Railway entirely, and so the Leeds and Selby Railway as an independent entity ceased to exist.{{sfn|Tomlinson|1915|pp=453, 778}} A decade later, the York and North Midland Railway would become the [[North Eastern Railway (UK)|North Eastern Railway]] after its amalgamation with other railway companies.\n\n=== NER period (1854\u20131923) ===\n\nIn the 1860s the [[North Eastern Railway (UK)|North Eastern Railway (NER)]] sought to extend the line from its Marsh Lane terminus into the centre of Leeds. Concurrently the NER and the [[London and North Western Railway]] planned to construct a joint station in Leeds.{{sfn|Hoole|1986|p=37}} An initial (1863) plan for the line into Leeds met with significant local opposition and was withdrawn, and a revised route was made.{{sfn|Tomlinson|1915|pp=612, 616}} (See also {{harvnb|Leather|1864}}) The plan was submitted to parliament in 1864 and received assent in 1865.{{sfn|Hoole|1986|p=37}}{{#tag:ref|\"The North-eastern Railway (Leeds Extension) Act, 1865\" (Cap. 251, 5 July 1865).<ref>{{citation | url =https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=X6FUAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA310#v=onepage&q&f=false |title = The Statutes of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland |volume =28 Pt.I|year = 1865|page = 310}}</ref>|group=\"note\"}} The new joint station received assent in the same session.{{sfn|Hoole|1986|p=37}}{{#tag:ref|\"The Leeds New Railway Station Act, 1865\" (Cap. 267, 5 July 1865).<ref>{{citation| url =https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=X6FUAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA315#v=onepage&q&f=false |title = The Statutes of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland |volume =28 Pt.I|year = 1865|page = 315}}</ref>|group=\"note\"}}\n\nIn 1869 the Leeds extension was completed; a 1-mile length of line which connected Marsh Lane through central Leeds to [[Holbeck]]; the line was elevated, running over the streets on bridges and viaducts and embankments.{{sfn|Tomlinson|1915|pp=612, 616\u20137, 634\u20135}} A new station, called [[Leeds New railway station]] was constructed for this connecting line, adjacent to and south of [[Leeds Wellington railway station|Wellington Street station]].<ref>{{citation| title=Yorkshire Railways, A comprehensive survey including Cleveland and Humberside|first= A.|last= Haigh |first2=David|last2= Joy|publisher=Dalesmans Books|year = 1979|at= \"Leeds Terminals\", pp.53.55}}</ref> The line representing a saving of around 35 miles journey for trains travelling from west of Leeds to Hull or York.{{sfn|Railway Times|13 February 1869|loc = pp.165, col.1}} A new goods station was built at the [[Leeds Marsh Lane railway station|Marsh Lane station site]], and in 1893 this was enlarged, and the extra lines added between Marsh Lane and Neville Hill,{{sfn|Tomlinson|1915|pp=651, 703}} the Richmond Hill tunnel was opened out at the same time, and made into a cutting, so that the extra tracks could be accommodated.<ref name=\"lner\">[[#LNER|The London and North Eastern Railway (LNER) Encyclopedia]], [http://www.lner.info/co/NER/selby/selby.shtml The Leeds and Selby Railway]</ref>\n\nIn 1869 a connecting line running northeast from [[Micklefield railway station|Micklefield station]] on the Leeds and Selby to [[Church Fenton railway station|Church Fenton station]] on the former York and North Midland line was opened, shortening the route between Leeds and York and avoiding a reversal at York Junction;{{sfn|Hoole|1986|p=34}} the line came into use on the opening of the Leeds extension.{{sfn|Railway Times|13 February 1869|loc=p.165, col.2}}\n\nIn 1876 the [[Cross Gates\u2013Wetherby line]] was opened; this ran from a junction just east of Cross Gates on the Leeds and Selby Line northward to [[Wetherby]].<ref name=\"leedswethe\">{{citation| url = http://www.lostrailwayswestyorkshire.co.uk/Leeds%20Wetherby.htm|title= Leeds to Wetherby, 1876 \u2013 1966 North Eastern Railway| work = www.lostrailwayswestyorkshire.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{citation| url = http://www.barwickinelmethistoricalsociety.com/8508.html| title = The Leeds \u2013 Cross Gates \u2013 Wetherby Railway| journal=The Barwicker| number =85}}, via ''www.barwickinelmethistoricalsociety.com''</ref>\n\nAn act for the construction of the [[Garforth to Castleford Line]] was passed in 1873 and the line opened in 1878, it left the Leeds and Selby Line east of [[Garforth railway station|Garforth station]]. The NER owned over three quarters of the shares in the line.{{sfn|Tomlinson|1915|pp=665, 682}}\n\nIn 1898 the [[Cawood, Wistow and Selby Light Railway]] was opened. This connected to the Leeds and Selby Line about 1 mile west of Selby at Brayton Gates junction.\n\nIn 1902 Gascoigne Wood station (formerly York Junction station<ref group=\"note\" name=\"oldj\"/>) closed.<ref name=\"kh\">{{citation| title = North Eastern Branch Lines since 1925| first =K.|last = Hoole|authorlink= Ken Hoole| year= 1978|pages=11\u201312}}</ref>\n\nIn 1910 the [[Selby to Goole Line]] was opened, which had a junction with the Leeds and Selby Line at Thorpe Gates junction, west of Selby.\n\nA halt station ''Ridge Bridge'' opened {{circa|1912}} near to the crossing of the  Roman Ridge road (now the [[A656 road|A656]].); the station closed to general passengers on 1 April 1914,<ref>Private and Untimetabled Railway Stations by G.Croughton page 118</ref> but remained in use as a workmans halt for the ''Ridge Bridge Colliery'' into the 1920s.<ref>{{citation| journal=The Railway Magazine| year = 1922 |page = 303|quote= ..Mr. J. W. Armstrong points out that there is a halt, built apparently to serve the workers at the Ridge Bridge Collieries, on the North Eastern Railway, between Garforth and Micklefield stations. Certain workmen's trains only call there. Mr. G. W. G. Cass, of Scarborough, in giving the same information, mentions that the station is located at the point where the Roman road between Castleford and Wetherby crosses the line. Mr. G. A. Bamlet mentions that this station was opened either in 1912 or 1913, and was closed to ordinary passenger traffic on March 31, 1914, quoting \"Bradshaw\" as his authority. The station remained open, and is apparently still used, for workmen's traffic. Mr. J. M. Adams states that the road which here crosses the line is marked on some maps as \"Roman Ridge.''| title = Ridge Bridge Station}}</ref>\n\n=== LNER period (1923\u20131948) ===\nIn 1930 a station at Osmondthorpe opened.<ref name=\"lner\"/>\n\n=== BR and post-privatisation period (1948\u2013present) ===\n[[File:East Garforth station 4.jpg|East Garforth station in 2006|thumb]]\nMany of the connecting lines closed in the 1950s and 60s: passenger services on the [[Castleford\u2013Garforth line]] from the junction at [[Garforth railway station|Garforth station]] closed in 1951, and freight ended in 1969,<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.lostrailwayswestyorkshire.co.uk/Castleford%20Garforth.htm | title = Castleford to Garforth 1878 \u2013 1951| work= www.lostrailwayswestyorkshire.co.uk|accessdate=18 January 2013}}</ref> the [[Cawood, Wistow and Selby Light Railway]] in 1960, the [[Selby to Goole Line]] in 1964, and [[Cross Gates\u2013Wetherby line]] from Cross Gates station also in 1964.<ref name=\"leedswethe\"/>\n\nHambleton station closed in 1959 and Osmondthorpe station in 1960.<ref name=\"lner\"/> [[East Garforth railway station]] opened in 1987.\n\nThe land north of Gascoigne Wood station was used as a marshalling yard until 1959.<ref name=\"kh\"/> The site was later used in the 1970s<ref>{{cite news| url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/october/29/newsid_2467000/2467783.stm| title= 1976: Duchess opens massive Selby coalfield| work = On This Day| publisher = BBC|accessdate=12 August 2010}}</ref> as the point at which coal from the collieries of the [[Selby Coalfield]] was brought to the surface.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://pamelaross.co.uk/gascoigne_wood_mine.htm | title = Gascoigne Wood Mine | work = pamelaross.co.uk | accessdate = 18 January 2013 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120310114421/http://pamelaross.co.uk/gascoigne_wood_mine.htm | archive-date = 10 March 2012 | url-status = dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.abandoned-britain.com/PP/gascoignewood/1.htm | title = Gascoigne Wood Mine| work = www.abandoned-britain.com|accessdate=18 January 2013}}</ref> {{#tag:ref|The last mine in the coalfield closed in 2004.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.selbytimes.co.uk/selby-news/END-OF-AN-ERA.877649.jp | archive-url = https://archive.today/20120912143939/http://www.selbytimes.co.uk/selby-news/END-OF-AN-ERA.877649.jp | url-status = dead | archive-date = 12 September 2012 | title = End of an era | date = 27 October 2004 | work = Selby Times | accessdate = 12 August 2010 }}</ref> The site is now a business park and in 2008 was used to store [[gypsum]] produced at coal burning power stations as part of the [[flue gas desulphurisation|desulphurisation process]].<ref>{{cite news| url = http://www.selbytimes.co.uk/district-news/Gascoigne-Wood-mine-building-gets.4757200.jp| archive-url = https://archive.today/20120912165152/http://www.selbytimes.co.uk/district-news/Gascoigne-Wood-mine-building-gets.4757200.jp| url-status = dead| archive-date = 12 September 2012| title = Gascoigne Wood mine building gets new lease of life| date = 3 December 2008| work = Selby Times| accessdate = 12 August 2010}}</ref>|group=\"note\"}}\n\nThe [[Selby Diversion]] of the [[East Coast Main Line]] opened in 1983, passing under the Leeds-Selby Line between South Milford and Selby; junctions were made between the two lines allowing running from York onto the Leeds-Selby eastwards, and from the south onto the line travelling westwards to Leeds.\n\n== Electrification ==\nThe line from Leeds Central station to Neville Hill depot was electrified in the early 1990s as a corollary to the [[East Coast Main Line]] electrification project.<ref>{{cite web| title = Electrification of the East Coast Main Line: Project Completion Certificate| url = http://www.railwaysarchive.co.uk/docsummary.php?docID=853| at = ''section'' 1.b.ii, p.3; Appendix A, sheet 3, A.2.1.vi| date= 1 March 1992| publisher = British Rail|}}</ref> The electrification was energised in March 1993.<ref>{{citation| title = Electric Railway Society Journal| volume = 38\u201339| page = 97}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, as part of its franchise offer, the train operating [[Great North Eastern Railway|Great North Eastern Railway (GNER)]] proposed to electrify the section of the line between Leeds and Hambleton junction in association with [[Network Rail]], at an estimated cost of \u00a370 million.<ref>{{cite web| title = GNER wins second franchise term| date = 1 May 2005 | url = http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/single-view/view/gner-wins-second-franchise-term.html| work = www.railwaygazette.com|}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050323090129/http://www.sra.gov.uk/news/2005/3/ICEC| url=http://www.sra.gov.uk/news/2005/3/ICEC| archivedate = 23 March 2005| date = 22 March 2005| publisher = Strategic Rail Authority| title = Biggest Deal in European Rail History Marks East Coast Franchise Announcement|}}</ref> GNER lost the franchise in December 2006 before undertaking the electrification work.<ref group=\"note\">The [[Department for Transport]] ended GNER's franchise due to financial problems, including the insolvency of its parent company Sea Containers; see [[Great North Eastern Railway|GNER]], and [[Sea Containers]]</ref>\n\nIn 2009 the Network Rail route utilisation strategy electrification paper identified the North Cross-Pennine route including the Leeds-Selby-Hull Line as a high ranking option for future electrification, in terms of benefits to passenger services.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.networkrail.co.uk/networkrus_electrification.pdf| title = Network RUS Electrification| date = October 2009| publisher = Network Rail| at = Fig. 5.1 'Gaps', p.44; Table 6.5, p.66| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141012195531/http://www.networkrail.co.uk/networkrus_electrification.pdf| archivedate = 12 October 2014| df = dmy-all}}</ref> In 2011 funding for the electrification in CP5 (see [[Network Rail Control Periods]]) of the section from Leeds to Micklefield was announced.<ref>{{cite web| url  =http://www.railnews.co.uk/news/general/2011/12/16-electrification-york-is-in-and.html| title = Electrification: Leeds-York is in, and more could follow| date = 16 November 2011| work = www.railnews.co.uk| quote = ''From the other side of Leeds, the wires would be installed from Neville West Junction to Colton Junction, which is south of York on the already-electrified East Coast Main Line''|}}</ref>{{#tag:ref|The scheme also included the section of line from Mickefield to Church Fenton on the former [[York and North Midland Railway|York and North Midland]] track, and the line from Church Fenton to the ECML at Colton junction.<ref name=\"cp5elec1\">{{cite web| url  =https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/high-level-output-specification-2012| title = The High Level Output Specification 2012| date = 16 July 2012|at=[https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/3645/map-schemes-already-committed.pdf Map featuring HLOS schemes already committed]}}</ref>|group=\"note\"}} Funding for the section of the line from Micklefield to Selby was added to the electrification schedule in 2013.<ref name=\"cp5elec3\">{{cite web| url  =https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/high-level-output-specification-2012| title = The High Level Output Specification 2012| date = 16 July 2012|at=[https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/3641/railways-act-2005.pdf The High Level Output Specification (HLOS) 2012: Railways Act 2005 statement. ''Section'' 42; also 4, 33]}}</ref>\n\n== Popular culture ==\nIn the song \"Poor Paddy\" by [[The Pogues]], this railway is mentioned in the verse for 1843:<blockquote>''In eighteen hundred and forty three,<br>I broke my shovel across me knee;<br>I went to work for the company,<br> on the Leeds and Selby Railway.''</blockquote>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Neville Hill depot]], rolling stock and locomotive depot on the line near Osmondthorpe, Leeds\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=\"note\"}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n* {{citation|title=The North Eastern Railway|first= Cecil J. |last = Allen|year= 1974}}\n* {{citation| title = Railway practice: A collection of working plans and practical details of construction in the public works of the most celebrated engineers ...| authorlink=Samuel Charles Brees|first= Samuel Charles|last= Brees}}\n** {{citation| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=5KghAAAAMAAJ |title=First Series|edition =3| publisher= J. Williams and Co.|year= 1847}}, including illustrative plates\n** {{citation| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=nstanKmFJIUC |title = First, Second, Third and Fourth Series| publisher= E.& F.N. Spon, R. Griffin & Co.|year= 1859}}, without the illustrative plates\n* {{citation| title = Appendix to Railway Practice, containing a copious abstract of the whole of the evidence given upon the London and Birmingham and Great Western Railway Bills...|year = 1839| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=caohAAAAMAAJ | authorlink=Samuel Charles Brees |first=Samuel Charles|last = Brees}}\n* {{citation|title = A Regional History of the Railways of Great Britain, Volume 4: The North East| authorlink=Ken Hoole| first = Ken |last = Hoole|year = 1986}}\n* {{citation|title = A History of the Hull Railways| first = G.G.|last= MacTurk| year = 1879 | at= Chapter II \"The Leeds and Selby Railway\"}}, reprinted 1970 with preface by Ken Hoole\n* {{citation| title = The Tourist's Companion; Or, the History of the Scenes and Places on the Route by the Railroad and Steam-Packet from Leeds and Selby to Hull|first= Edward|last= Parsons| url =https://archive.org/details/touristscompani01parsgoog| year=1835}}\n* {{citation|url=http://www.lner.info|title= The London and North Eastern Railway (LNER) Encyclopedia|work = www.lner.info|ref=LNER}}\n* {{citation| title = The North Eastern Railway; its rise and development| authorlink=William Weaver Tomlinson| first = William Weaver|last = Tomlinson| year=1915| url = https://archive.org/details/northeasternrail00tomlrich }}\n*{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/railwaysgreatbr00whisgoog|title=The Railways of Great Britain and Ireland Practically Described and Illustrated|first=Francis|last=Whishaw|authorlink=Francis Whishaw|edition=2nd|location=London|publisher=John Weale|year=1842|oclc=833076248|ref=harv}}\n* {{citation| url = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=NIMqAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA165 | title = The North Eastern New Station and Line \u2013 The New Route to York and Hull| date = 13 February 1869| page = 165| journal = Railway News|volume=11| number = 268|ref = {{harvid|Railway Times|13 February 1869}} }}\n\n=== Further reading ===\n* {{citation| title = A few general observations on the principal railways executed, in progress, & projected in the midland counties & north of England, with the author's opinion upon them as investments| year= 1838| at= p.14, \"The York and North Midland Railway\"; p.16, \"The Leeds and Selby Railway\"|url = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=e2YEAAAAQAAJ}}, contemporary analysis of the competitive threat from the York and North Midland Railway, and the prospects of the Leeds and Selby Railway\n* {{citation| first  =John W.| last = Leather| year = 1864| title = Letter to Mr. Alderman Kitson: On the Proposed New Central Railway Station, and the Lines Projected by the North Eastern Railway Company for Connecting the Lines on the Western and Eastern Sides of Leeds| url = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-LoMAQAAIAAJ }}\n* {{citation| title = Yorkshire's First Main Line| publisher = West Yorkshire Transport Museum |year =1984|first = John|last = Bushell}}\n* {{citation| url =http://www.selby.gov.uk/upload/091021_Yorkshires_First_Main_Line.pdf| title =Yorkshire\u2019s First Railway Station, a commemorative booklet. Marking the 175th anniversary of the opening of Selby station. 22nd September 1834| publisher =Selby District Council| url-status =dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20110614105156/http://www.selby.gov.uk/upload/091021_Yorkshires_First_Main_Line.pdf| archivedate =14 June 2011| df =dmy-all}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Selby Line}}\n\n{{Railway lines in Yorkshire and the Humber}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leeds And Selby Railway}}\n[[Category:Early British railway companies]]\n[[Category:Railway companies established in 1830]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 1834]]\n[[Category:Railway companies disestablished in 1844]]\n[[Category:Rail transport in North Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Rail transport in West Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Leeds and Selby Railway]]\n[[Category:1830 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:British companies established in 1830]]\n[[Category:1844 disestablishments in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2013}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = Leeds and Selby Railway\n| logo             = \n| caption          = \n| type             = \n| genre            = \n| fate             = Track owned by [[Network Rail]], services by various operators\n| predecessor      = Leeds&nbsp;and&nbsp;Hull&nbsp;Railroad&nbsp;Company&nbsp;(1824) ''unbuilt''\n| successor        = ''Leased and acquired by''<br>[[York and North Midland Railway]] 1844<br>''merged into''<br>[[North Eastern Railway (UK)|North Eastern Railway]] 1854<br>[[London and North Eastern Railway]] 1923<br>[[British Rail]] 1948\n| foundation       = 1830 (Act of Parliament)<br>1834 (Opening)\n| founder          = \n| defunct          = \n| location_city    = \n| location_country = \n| location         = \n| locations        = \n| area_served      = \n| key_people       = \n| industry         = \n| products         = \n| services         = \n| revenue          = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income       = \n| aum              = \n| assets           = \n| equity           = \n| owner            = \n| num_employees    = \n| parent           = \n| divisions        = \n| subsid           = \n| homepage         = \n| footnotes        = \n| intl             = \n}}\nThe '''Leeds and Selby Railway''' was an early British railway company and first mainline railway within Yorkshire. It was opened in 1834.\n\nAs built, the line ran west/east between two termini, [[Leeds Marsh Lane railway station|Marsh Lane station, Leeds]] and [[Selby railway station]]. The company was leased and then acquired by the [[York and North Midland Railway]] in 1840 and 1844; the line remained in use through the subsequent [[North Eastern Railway (UK)|NER]], [[London and North Eastern Railway|LNER]], [[British Rail|BR]] and [[History of rail transport in Great Britain 1995 to date|post-privatisation]] periods.\n\nUse of the line was expanded through junction connections to new railways, most built in the late 19th century; a junction with the [[York and North Midland Railway]] in 1839; an end on junction at Selby to Hull ([[Hull and Selby Railway]], 1840); a through route into Leeds and westward (Leeds viaduct extension, 1869); a shortened route to York (Micklefield to Church Fenton, 1869); a line to [[Wetherby]] ([[Cross Gates to Wetherby Line]], 1876, closed 1964); a line to [[Castleford]] ([[Garforth to Castleford Line]], 1878, closed 1969) and a line avoiding Selby for Goole ([[Selby to Goole Line]], 1910, closed 1964) as well as a number of minor and industrial lines and sidings. The [[Selby Diversion]] of the [[East Coast Main Line]] (1983) also made junctions with the Leeds and Selby.\n\nAs of 2014, the line is still in mainline use and use for services operated by [[TransPennine Express]] and [[Northern (train operating company)|Northern]] for services from Leeds to Selby, Hull, York and beyond.\n\n== The Leeds and Selby Railway Company (1830\u20131844) ==\n\n=== Background ===\n{{See also|History of Leeds}}\nBy 1830 Leeds had long been an important town, having become prosperous initially through the manufacture of woollen cloth. The [[Leeds and Liverpool Canal]] was complete and the [[Aire and Calder Navigation]] connected Leeds to the Ouse, and thus to the North Sea and beyond.<ref>{{cite web| url =http://www.leeds.gov.uk/page.aspx?pageidentifier=B08840B63BB604C480256E1B00307E07| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090101103059/http://www.leeds.gov.uk/page.aspx?pageidentifier=B08840B63BB604C480256E1B00307E07|archivedate=1 January 2009 |title = History of the city of Leeds|publisher= Leeds City Council|}}</ref> [[Selby]] had grown in importance as a port since the construction of the [[Selby Canal]] and had become an important inland east coast port for coastal and foreign trade.\n\nAs early as 1814{{#tag:ref|One source ('The Tourist's companion..') gives a date of 16 January 1823 {{harv|Parsons|1835|p=86}}, In 'Annals and History of Leeds' records a proposal as early as 1802.<ref>{{citation|title = The annals and history of Leeds|first= John|last = Mayhall|year= 1860|page = 203|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=mAQWAAAAYAAJ}}</ref>|group=\"note\"}} the ''[[Leeds Mercury]]'' had printed letters promoting the idea of a railway from Leeds to Selby.<ref name=\"early\">[[#LNER|The London & North Eastern Railway (LNER) Encyclopedia]]: [http://www.lner.info/co/NER/selby/selby.shtml The Leeds and Selby Railway], \"Early History\"</ref>\n\n==== The Leeds and Hull Railway ====\nThe Leeds and Hull Railroad Company was formed in 1824 in Leeds. [[George Stephenson]] was appointed as engineer, and he directed [[Joseph Locke]] to survey the line.<ref name=\"t98\">{{harvnb|Tomlinson|1915|pp=98\u201399}}</ref>\n\nStephenson recommended a double track railway, operated by locomotives at a speed of {{convert|8|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|Tomlinson|1915|pp=98\u201399}} The hills on the route out of Leeds were to have three inclined planes to be worked by three stationary engines. The remainder of the line was to be very nearly level.<ref name=\"gg\">{{harvnb|MacTurk|1879|p=17}}</ref>\n\nThe company was one of a number of contemporary projects aimed at linking the east and west sides of northern England, such as the [[Newcastle and Carlisle Railway]] (act of Parliament 1829) and the [[Liverpool and Manchester Railway]] (act of Parliament 1826). The Manchester and Leeds Railroad Company was formed in 1825, and would have completed the Lancashire to Yorkshire link.<ref name=\"t98\"/> Representatives of the company were present at the opening of the [[Stockton and Darlington Railway]] in 1825.{{sfn|Tomlinson|1915|p=114}} Of these schemes the Leeds and Hull, and the Manchester and Leeds were not immediately acted upon, in part due to the [[Panic of 1825|stock market crash of 1825]].<ref name=\"t202\">{{harvnb|Tomlinson|1915|p=202}}</ref><ref group=\"note\">It may have also been that the shareholders were unwilling to commit to building the line until the success or failure of the [[Liverpool and Manchester Railway]] was known.  {{harv|Allen|1974|p=50}}, {{harv|Tomlinson|1915|p=99}}</ref> The Leeds and Hull scheme stagnated, and in the meantime the Knottingley and Goole Canal (an extension of the Aire and Calder Navigation) opened in 1826 bringing the village of [[Goole]] from obscurity, and turning it into a viable transhipment port for Europe.\n\nThe growth of Goole as a port to rival Hull was sufficient to spur the Hull-based shareholders of the Leeds and Hull railway into action; at the end of 1828 they motioned that the railway should be built as far as Selby, with the remainder of the journey to Hull being made by [[Steam Packet|steam packet]], most importantly, bypassing Goole. The shareholders passed the proposal at a general meeting in Leeds on 20 March 1829, and the '''Leeds and Selby Railway Company''' was formed.<ref name=\"t202\"/>\n\n=== Formation of the Leeds and Selby Railway Company ===\n{{Leeds and Selby Railway, 1834}}\nThe Leeds and Hull railway scheme of 1824 was revived as a shortened line from Leeds to Selby and was resurveyed by [[James Walker (engineer)|James Walker]] in 1829;{{sfn|Hoole|1986|p=29}} [[Benjamin Gott]], one of the line's promoters and a wool and cloth magnate thought the inclined planes would be a disadvantage.<ref name=\"gg\"/>\n\nJames Walker reported that the stationary engines could be abandoned, and tunnels and cuttings built in their place. He expected that the additional cost of their construction would be offset by use of the stone elsewhere on the railway and by its sale. The railway would also be of use for the transportation of coal and stone from quarries and mines near the line, such as the Huddlestone quarry. Additionally he suggested that the route of the railway could also be used for the piping of clean water to Leeds. As to the route of the railway, he suggested resiting the Leeds terminus at cheaper and less-developed land around Marsh Lane instead of at Far Bank. The resurveyed line was also deviated to the north away from the river bank, to avoid the objections of the Aire and Calder Undertakers; the more northern path would require passing Richmond Hill requiring either stationary engines or a tunnel; Walker recommended the latter. Outside Leeds, minor deviations were made in order for the line to cross the north\u2013south [[turnpike trust|turnpikes]] using bridges. At Selby, the new plan sited the station further south than the original, which had been sited next to the road bridge, with the intention of crossing the [[River Ouse, Yorkshire|River Ouse]] by widening this bridge; with the line no longer going to Hull but terminating at Selby a site with more space for wharves and jetties was required. He recommended a double track line, with sufficient land acquired for a four track line.<ref>James Walker's report: \"To the Committee of the proposed Leeds and Selby Railway Company\", 18 July 1829, reprinted in full in {{harvnb|MacTurk|1879|pp=18\u201332}}</ref>\n\nMuch of the line was to be built on land belonging to the shareholders, including [[Edward Robert Petre]] who owned land in Selby, and Richard Oliver Gascoigne (who later had built the Aberford Railway). Walker's alterations to Stephenson's original plan were accepted unaltered and put before Parliament.{{sfn|MacTurk|1879|pp=33\u201335, 21(note)}}\n\nDespite strong opposition from the Aire and Calder Navigation, which had a practical monopoly on transportation in the area, a bill was passed in Parliament on 29 May 1830 allowing construction of the line. The company was allowed to raise a total of \u00a3300,000 in shares and loans.<ref name=\"t203\">{{harvnb|Tomlinson|1915|pp=203\u20134}}</ref>{{sfn|Whishaw|1842|p=173}}<ref group=\"note\">An extract from the act on the rates of carriage, as well as a list of subscribers can be found reprinted in \"The Tourist's Companion\".{{harv|Parsons|1835|pp=56\u201360}}</ref> The company's directors were James Audus, [[Edward Baines (1800\u20131890)|Edward Baines]], [[Bland baronets|Thomas Davison Bland]], John Broadley, [[Gascoigne baronets|Richard Oliver Gascoigne]], [[Benjamin Gott]], Robert Harrison, [[John Marshall (disambiguation)|John Marshall]], John Cowham Parker, the Hon. Edward Robert Petrie, John Scholefield and John Wilson. Samuel Wilks Waud was the first company chairman.<ref name=\"t204\">{{harvnb|Tomlinson|1915|pp=204\u2013205}}</ref>\n\n=== Construction, infrastructure and rolling stock ===\nTwo contractors, Messrs. Nowell & Sons and Messrs. Hamer & Pratt, were chosen to carry out the construction of the line. Nowell began construction of the {{convert|2|mi|km}} out of Leeds on 1 October 1830,<ref group=\"note\">The work in Leeds was postponed until February 1831, since there was a possibility that a proposed Leeds & Bradford Railway might be built, giving the possibility of a through link taking a different path. {{harv|Tomlinson|1915|p=205}}</ref> and Hamer & Pratt began work in February 1831 on the remaining {{convert|18|mi|km}} to Selby.<ref name=\"t204\"/>\n\nThe primary engineering feature of the line was the tunnel through [[Richmond Hill, West Yorkshire|Richmond Hill]] in Leeds. It was {{convert|700|yd|m}} long, with its western entrance at {{convert|8|chain|m}} from the Leeds terminus. The tunnel's cross section was that of a [[horseshoe arch]], {{convert|22|ft|m|abbr=on}} at its widest, and {{convert|17|ft|abbr=on}} high from the level of the rails. The construction of the tunnel required the sinking of three shafts, subsequently retained for ventilation.<ref name=\"w176\">{{harvnb|Whishaw|1842|p=176}}</ref><ref name=\"instun\">{{Cite journal | last1 = Walker | first1 = J. | last2 = Smith | first2 = G. | doi = 10.1680/itrcs.1836.24482 | title = On Ventilating and Lighting Tunnels, Particularly in Reference to the One on the Leeds and Selby Railway | journal = ICE Transactions | volume = 1 | issue = 1836 | pages = 95 | year = 1836 | pmid =  | pmc = | url = https://archive.org/stream/transactions01goog#page/n131/mode/1up}}</ref> Excavation of the tunnel yielded mostly shale and coal, with the remaining third being stone which was used as foundations for other parts of the line. The arch was lined with two courses of brickwork, lengthways to a thickness of 20 inches. In some places three courses were used, depending on the strength of the surrounding ground. Volcanic matter was used in the mortar, to obtain a quick-setting and strong cement.{{sfn|Parsons|1835|pp=61\u201363}} The entrances of the tunnel were faced with stone.<ref>{{harvnb|Brees||loc=Series 1, Plate 61}}</ref> There were once reflectors at the base of the shafts, designed to reflect light onto the whitewashed walls of the tunnel.{{sfn|Tomlinson|1915|p=253}} The shafts were found to be useful for ventilation, but the experiment with illuminating the interior with reflect light was of limited utility to passengers; lamps were provided to light the carriages.<ref name=\"instun\"/> Despite the efforts, an early passenger reported that on entering the tunnel:\n\n{{quote|We were immediately enveloped in total darkness, and every one of the carriages filled with smoke and steam to a most annoying degree|Mechanic's magazine (1835)|<ref>{{citation| url =https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=JggAAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA277| journal = The Mechanics' magazine, museum, register, journal, and gazette| volume = 23| date = 4 April \u2013 25 September 1835|publisher  =J. Cunningham|title = Of the Smoke, Noise, &c. in Tunnels|page=277|first=John|last=Herepath}}</ref>{{sfn|Tomlinson|1915|p=259}}}}\n\n[[File:Diagram of section of Leeds and Selby Railway Chair showing rail and key.JPG|thumb|Cross section diagram of Leeds and Selby railway chair, key and rail]]\nAs built, the line had 43 bridges and around 16 level crossings.<ref name=\"wh174\"/> Ballast was of stone chips; the rails were held in place by keys lodged into iron [[Chair (railway)|chairs]] which rested on and were fixed to stone blocks or larch sleepers. On some parts of the line, a [[ladder track]] arrangement of sleepers was used, with longitudinal stone sleepers of {{convert|3|ft|m|abbr=on}} held in gauge by transverse cast-iron rods. T or bar-shaped malleable iron rails of {{convert|35|lb/yd|kg/m|1|abbr=on}} were initially used, within a few years {{convert|42|lb/yd|kg/m|1|abbr=on}} rails were being introduced.<ref name=\"wh174\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Tomlinson|1915|p=255}}, diagrams of rail and track transverse cross section.</ref>\n\nCuttings and embankments were built to keep the gradient of the line to a minimum. The deepest cutting was {{convert|43|ft|m|abbr=on}}, the highest embankment {{convert|54|ft|m|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"t253\">{{harvnb|Tomlinson|1915|pp=253\u2013255}}</ref> Both embankments and cuttings had stone retaining walls at the base, at an angle of 67.5\u00b0 to the horizontal, which reduced the overall width of the earthworks. The line was built as a double-track railway.<ref name=\"wh174\">{{harvnb|Whishaw||loc= First Series|pp=174\u2013178}}</ref>\n\n==== Route and stations ====\nAfter {{convert|8|chain|m}} of level track outside the Leeds terminus, the line generally ascended for a distance of {{miles-chains|4|mi|32|chain|km}} at a maximum slope of 1 in 160; it was then level for {{miles-chains|2|mi|61|chain|km}} after which it generally descended eastwards towards Selby for {{miles-chains|6|mi|6|chain|km}} with a maximum rate of descent of 1 in 137. The final {{miles-chains|6|mi|41|chain|km}} to Selby was practically level with a rate of descent of only 1 in 3785. The highest point was {{convert|132|ft|m|abbr=on}} above the Leeds terminus, with the whole line having a net descent of {{convert|100|ft|m|1|abbr=on}} towards Selby.<ref name=\"wh174\"/>\n\nThe [[Leeds Marsh Lane railway station|Marsh Lane terminus]] in Leeds, and the station at Selby, were early examples of what would become 'railway architecture': both were long rectangular sheds, with wooden trussed roofs, supported internally on cast iron columns.{{sfn|Brees||loc= First series, plates 62 and 63|pp=133\u2013134}} The stations served for both passenger and freight, with additional tracks external to the sheds for coal; there was no platform for passengers. Both stations had coal depots, the Leeds station contained the facilities for maintenance of engines and wagons.<ref>{{harvnb|Tomlinson|1915| pp=253\u2013260|loc=Plates, p.258}}, Station plans reproduced from Brees' Railway Practice, Fourth series, 1847</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Brees||loc= Fourth series, Plate 48 and legend pages cii\u2013ciii}}</ref> The rear of the Selby station backed onto the Ouse, across a road (Ousegate) from jetties that would allow a continuation of the journey to Hull.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.selby.gov.uk/upload/091015_Selby_Old_Station.pdf |title = A brief guide to Selby Railway Station, Yorkshire\u2019s Oldest: Built 1834 |publisher = Selby District Council |accessdate = 15 January 2013 |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120302075154/http://www.selby.gov.uk/upload/091015_Selby_Old_Station.pdf |archivedate = 2 March 2012 |df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAfter the station at Marsh Lane in Leeds were stations at Cross Gates, Garforth, Roman Road, Micklefield, Milford, and Hambleton.{{sfn|Parsons|1835|pp=241\u2013243}}\n\n==== Locomotives ====\nThe original engines were of the lightweight four-wheeled [[Bury Bar Frame locomotive|\"Bury\" type]]<ref>*Whishaw. F., (1842), London: Weale</ref> from [[Edward Bury]] of Liverpool. They were shown to lack traction sufficient for the line, and were sold. Replacements were obtained from [[Fenton, Murray and Jackson]] of ([[Leeds]]) and from [[Thomas Kirtley and Co|Kirtley & Co.]] of [[Warrington]].{{sfn|Tomlinson|1915|pp=391\u20132}}\n\n;Locomotive list\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Wheels !! Builder !! Date introduced !! YNMR no. !! NER no. !! Comments\n|-\n|   ''St Vincent'' || [[2-2-0]] || [[Edward Bury and Company]] || 1834 || \u2013 || \u2013 || To [[Newcastle & North Shields Railway]], 1838<ref name=\"steamindex.com\">http://www.steamindex.com/locotype/nerloco.htm</ref>\n|-\n|   ''Lord Hood'' ||  [[2-2-0]] || [[Edward Bury and Company]] || 1834 || \u2013 || \u2013 || To [[West Hartlepool Harbour & Railway]], 1840<ref name=\"steamindex.com\"/>\n|-\n|   ''Rodney'' || [[2-2-0]] || [[Edward Bury and Company]] || 1834 || \u2013 || \u2013 || To [[West Hartlepool Harbour & Railway]], 1840<ref name=\"steamindex.com\"/>\n|-\n|   ''Nelson'' ||  [[2-2-0]] || [[Fenton, Murray & Jackson]] || 1834 || \u2013 || \u2013 ||  To [[York & North Midland Railway]], 1849<ref name=\"steamindex.com\"/>\n|-\n| ''Exmouth'' ||  [[2-2-0]] || [[Fenton, Murray & Jackson]] || 1836 || \u2013 || \u2013 || To [[West Hartlepool Harbour & Railway]], 1840<ref name=\"steamindex.com\"/>\n|-\n|   ? ||  [[0-2-2]] || [[Robert Stephenson and Company]] || 1830 || \u2013 || \u2013 || Ex-[[List of Liverpool and Manchester Railway locomotives|Liverpool & Manchester Railway]] ''North Star'' (acquired December 1833).<br>\nSold, January 1836<ref name=\"steamindex.com\"/>\n|-\n|   ''Gambier'' or ''Hawke'' ||  [[2-2-2]] || [[Fenton, Murray & Jackson]] || 1836 || 14 || \u2013 ||  <ref name=\"steamindex.com\"/>\n|-\n|   ''Eagle'' or ''Anson'' ||  [[2-2-2]] || [[Fenton, Murray & Jackson]] || 1837 || 15 || \u2013 ||  <ref name=\"steamindex.com\"/>\n|-\n|   ''Dart'' ||  [[2-2-2]] || [[Fenton, Murray & Jackson]] || 1839 || 16 || \u2013 ||  <ref name=\"steamindex.com\"/>\n|-\n| ?  ||  [[2-2-0]] || [[Thomas Kirtley]] || 1839 || 17 || \u2013 ||  <ref name=\"steamindex.com\"/>\n|-\n|   ''Express'' ||  [[2-2-2]] || [[Fenton, Murray & Jackson]] || 1839 || 18 || \u2013 ||  Rebuilt as a tank engine by the YNMR<ref name=\"steamindex.com\"/>\n|-\n| ''Prince''  ||  [[2-2-0]] || [[Thomas Kirtley]] || 1839 || 19 || \u2013 ||  <ref name=\"steamindex.com\"/>\n|-\n| ''Swift''  ||  [[2-2-0]] || [[Thomas Kirtley]] || 1839 || 20 || \u2013 ||  <ref name=\"steamindex.com\"/>\n|-\n| ''Swallow''  ||  [[2-2-0]] || [[Thomas Kirtley]] || 1839 || 21 || \u2013 ||  <ref name=\"steamindex.com\"/>\n|-\n| ''Queen''  ||  [[2-2-0]] || [[Thomas Kirtley]] || 1839 || 22 || \u2013 ||  <ref name=\"steamindex.com\"/>\n|}\n;Notes\n# YNMR = [[York and North Midland Railway]]\n# NER = [[North Eastern Railway (United Kingdom)|North Eastern Railway]]\n# The names and numbers of the Kirtley locomotives may have been transposed\n\n==== Rolling stock ====\nThere were first and second-class [[Passenger car (rail)|carriages]], [[Horse trailer#Railway horse boxes|boxeshorse boxes]] and [[Goods wagon|wagons]], including privately owned wagons.{{sfn|Whishaw|1842|pp=179\u2013180}}\n\n=== Opening and operation ===\nBy 22 September 1834, a single complete line of track had been built, and the railway was officially opened. A train of ten carriages, hauled by the locomotive \"Nelson\", set out from [[Leeds Marsh Lane railway station|Marsh Lane station]] in Leeds at 6.30&nbsp;am. To the embarrassment or amusement of those present, the locomotive got into difficulty on the incline at the tunnel. The wheels began to slip on wet rails, and despite the application of ash on the rails, initial progress was no better than walking pace. Once the high point of the line was reached, better progress was made: at Garforth, on a stretch of track falling 1 in 180 a speed of {{convert|20|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} was attained. Selby was reached before 9&nbsp;am. The return journey took 1 hour and sixteen minutes. On the 23rd, two trains were run each way, with a better timing of 1 hour and five minutes from Leeds to Selby.{{sfn|Tomlinson|1915|pp=256\u20137}}{{sfn|Parsons|1835|pp=77\u201379}}\n\nBoth lines of track were complete by 15 December, when the railway began to take goods traffic.{{sfn|Tomlinson|1915|pp=259\u2013260}}\n\nIn ''The Railways of Britain and Ireland practically described and illustrated'', [[Francis Whishaw]] ascribed the poor financial performance of the railway to the management of the line; after six years of existence, the railway was returning a profit, but the average dividend on a \u00a3100 share over 1837 to 1840 was a meagre one pound, sixteen shillings and nine pence.{{sfn|Whishaw|1842|pp=173, 182\u2013184}}\n\nAs a result of the opening of the line, the Aire and Calder Navigation had to make considerable reductions in their charges.<ref>{{harvnb|Brees|1839|pp=208\u20139}}</ref> Previously, that company's monopoly had resulted in a dividend on shares of over 200%.{{sfn|Tomlinson|1915|p=205}}\n\n=== Connections with other railway lines ===\n{{anchor|York junction}}\n\n==== York and North Midland Railway ====\n{{York Junction, Leeds and Selby Railway, 1840}}\n{{See also|York and North Midland Railway}}\nOn 29 May 1839 the first section of [[George Hudson]]'s York and North Midland Railway opened. It ran from York to a point just to the east of Milford station where a short chord connected it to the Leeds and Selby Railway. The line was extended southwards to Burton Salmon by 11 May 1840; and that line connected by another short chord to the junction with the Leeds and Selby on 9 November 1840.<ref name=\"rh30\">{{harvnb|Hoole|1986|pp=30\u201333}}</ref>\n\nEast of the junction was a station called York Junction.<ref name=\"rh30\"/><ref group=\"note\" name=\"oldj\">After 1850 ''York Junction'' was called ''Old Junction'', in 1867 in became ''Milford Old Junction'', from 1897 it was called ''Gascoigne Wood''. {{harv|Hoole|1986|pp=32\u201333}}</ref>\n\n==== Hull and Selby Railway ====\n{{See also|Hull and Selby Railway}}\nThe original Leeds to Hull plan was completed in 1840 with the construction of a line running almost directly east from Selby to Hull. A bascule bridge was constructed across the Ouse at Selby, just north of the jetties at the rear of the original Selby station. A new station to the west was constructed, and the old station became a goods shed.{{sfn|Hoole|1986|pp=29\u201330}}<ref>Ordnance Survey. Town plans 1:1056, 1849</ref>\n\n==== Aberford Railway ====\n{{Main|Aberford Railway}}\nThe Aberford railway was a private railway built during the same period as the Leeds and Selby Railway by the [[Gascoigne family]]. It  ran from [[Aberford]] and connected at Garforth. It was built primarily to carry coal from the Gascoigne's coal mines but also carried passengers. It closed in 1924.\n\n== History, 1840\u2013present ==\n\n=== Lease and acquisition by the York and North Midland (1840\u20131854) ===\nThe Leeds and Selby Railway offered a direct route into Leeds from the east. [[George Hudson]] had his own route into Leeds (through Castleford via the Whitford and Methey Junctions)  accessed via a working arrangement with the [[North Midland Railway]]. The Leeds and Selby had the potential to offer opportunities to rival companies, as well as a competing route to Hudson's. On 9 November 1840 George Hudson arranged a lease of the Leeds and Selby  for \u00a317,000 per annum.<ref name=\"rh30\"/>{{sfn|Tomlinson|1915|pp=341\u2013342}}\n\nHudson's first act was to close the line to passengers west of Milford; despite his line being 4 miles longer passengers now had no choice but to use it. In 1848 the line west of Milford was closed to freight as well; Marsh Lane station was at that time still a terminus, and so useless for through traffic to Manchester and beyond. Passenger services were reinstated in 1850, but freight continued to run to Leeds via Castleford and not Marsh Lane.<ref name=\"rh30\"/>\n\nIn 1844 an act of Parliament was passed allowing the York and North Midland to absorb the Leeds and Selby Railway entirely, and so the Leeds and Selby Railway as an independent entity ceased to exist.{{sfn|Tomlinson|1915|pp=453, 778}} A decade later, the York and North Midland Railway would become the [[North Eastern Railway (UK)|North Eastern Railway]] after its amalgamation with other railway companies.\n\n=== NER period (1854\u20131923) ===\n\nIn the 1860s the [[North Eastern Railway (UK)|North Eastern Railway (NER)]] sought to extend the line from its Marsh Lane terminus into the centre of Leeds. Concurrently the NER and the [[London and North Western Railway]] planned to construct a joint station in Leeds.{{sfn|Hoole|1986|p=37}} An initial (1863) plan for the line into Leeds met with significant local opposition and was withdrawn, and a revised route was made.{{sfn|Tomlinson|1915|pp=612, 616}} (See also {{harvnb|Leather|1864}}) The plan was submitted to parliament in 1864 and received assent in 1865.{{sfn|Hoole|1986|p=37}}{{#tag:ref|\"The North-eastern Railway (Leeds Extension) Act, 1865\" (Cap. 251, 5 July 1865).<ref>{{citation | url =https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=X6FUAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA310#v=onepage&q&f=false |title = The Statutes of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland |volume =28 Pt.I|year = 1865|page = 310}}</ref>|group=\"note\"}} The new joint station received assent in the same session.{{sfn|Hoole|1986|p=37}}{{#tag:ref|\"The Leeds New Railway Station Act, 1865\" (Cap. 267, 5 July 1865).<ref>{{citation| url =https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=X6FUAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA315#v=onepage&q&f=false |title = The Statutes of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland |volume =28 Pt.I|year = 1865|page = 315}}</ref>|group=\"note\"}}\n\nIn 1869 the Leeds extension was completed; a 1-mile length of line which connected Marsh Lane through central Leeds to [[Holbeck]]; the line was elevated, running over the streets on bridges and viaducts and embankments.{{sfn|Tomlinson|1915|pp=612, 616\u20137, 634\u20135}} A new station, called [[Leeds New railway station]] was constructed for this connecting line, adjacent to and south of [[Leeds Wellington railway station|Wellington Street station]].<ref>{{citation| title=Yorkshire Railways, A comprehensive survey including Cleveland and Humberside|first= A.|last= Haigh |first2=David|last2= Joy|publisher=Dalesmans Books|year = 1979|at= \"Leeds Terminals\", pp.53.55}}</ref> The line representing a saving of around 35 miles journey for trains travelling from west of Leeds to Hull or York.{{sfn|Railway Times|13 February 1869|loc = pp.165, col.1}} A new goods station was built at the [[Leeds Marsh Lane railway station|Marsh Lane station site]], and in 1893 this was enlarged, and the extra lines added between Marsh Lane and Neville Hill,{{sfn|Tomlinson|1915|pp=651, 703}} the Richmond Hill tunnel was opened out at the same time, and made into a cutting, so that the extra tracks could be accommodated.<ref name=\"lner\">[[#LNER|The London and North Eastern Railway (LNER) Encyclopedia]], [http://www.lner.info/co/NER/selby/selby.shtml The Leeds and Selby Railway]</ref>\n\nIn 1869 a connecting line running northeast from [[Micklefield railway station|Micklefield station]] on the Leeds and Selby to [[Church Fenton railway station|Church Fenton station]] on the former York and North Midland line was opened, shortening the route between Leeds and York and avoiding a reversal at York Junction;{{sfn|Hoole|1986|p=34}} the line came into use on the opening of the Leeds extension.{{sfn|Railway Times|13 February 1869|loc=p.165, col.2}}\n\nIn 1876 the [[Cross Gates\u2013Wetherby line]] was opened; this ran from a junction just east of Cross Gates on the Leeds and Selby Line northward to [[Wetherby]].<ref name=\"leedswethe\">{{citation| url = http://www.lostrailwayswestyorkshire.co.uk/Leeds%20Wetherby.htm|title= Leeds to Wetherby, 1876 \u2013 1966 North Eastern Railway| work = www.lostrailwayswestyorkshire.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{citation| url = http://www.barwickinelmethistoricalsociety.com/8508.html| title = The Leeds \u2013 Cross Gates \u2013 Wetherby Railway| journal=The Barwicker| number =85}}, via ''www.barwickinelmethistoricalsociety.com''</ref>\n\nAn act for the construction of the [[Garforth to Castleford Line]] was passed in 1873 and the line opened in 1878, it left the Leeds and Selby Line east of [[Garforth railway station|Garforth station]]. The NER owned over three quarters of the shares in the line.{{sfn|Tomlinson|1915|pp=665, 682}}\n\nIn 1898 the [[Cawood, Wistow and Selby Light Railway]] was opened. This connected to the Leeds and Selby Line about 1 mile west of Selby at Brayton Gates junction.\n\nIn 1902 Gascoigne Wood station (formerly York Junction station<ref group=\"note\" name=\"oldj\"/>) closed.<ref name=\"kh\">{{citation| title = North Eastern Branch Lines since 1925| first =K.|last = Hoole|authorlink= Ken Hoole| year= 1978|pages=11\u201312}}</ref>\n\nIn 1910 the [[Selby to Goole Line]] was opened, which had a junction with the Leeds and Selby Line at Thorpe Gates junction, west of Selby.\n\nA halt station ''Ridge Bridge'' opened {{circa|1912}} near to the crossing of the  Roman Ridge road (now the [[A656 road|A656]].); the station closed to general passengers on 1 April 1914,<ref>Private and Untimetabled Railway Stations by G.Croughton page 118</ref> but remained in use as a workmans halt for the ''Ridge Bridge Colliery'' into the 1920s.<ref>{{citation| journal=The Railway Magazine| year = 1922 |page = 303|quote= ..Mr. J. W. Armstrong points out that there is a halt, built apparently to serve the workers at the Ridge Bridge Collieries, on the North Eastern Railway, between Garforth and Micklefield stations. Certain workmen's trains only call there. Mr. G. W. G. Cass, of Scarborough, in giving the same information, mentions that the station is located at the point where the Roman road between Castleford and Wetherby crosses the line. Mr. G. A. Bamlet mentions that this station was opened either in 1912 or 1913, and was closed to ordinary passenger traffic on March 31, 1914, quoting \"Bradshaw\" as his authority. The station remained open, and is apparently still used, for workmen's traffic. Mr. J. M. Adams states that the road which here crosses the line is marked on some maps as \"Roman Ridge.''| title = Ridge Bridge Station}}</ref>\n\n=== LNER period (1923\u20131948) ===\nIn 1930 a station at Osmondthorpe opened.<ref name=\"lner\"/>\n\n=== BR and post-privatisation period (1948\u2013present) ===\n[[File:East Garforth station 4.jpg|East Garforth station in 2006|thumb]]\nMany of the connecting lines closed in the 1950s and 60s: passenger services on the [[Castleford\u2013Garforth line]] from the junction at [[Garforth railway station|Garforth station]] closed in 1951, and freight ended in 1969,<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.lostrailwayswestyorkshire.co.uk/Castleford%20Garforth.htm | title = Castleford to Garforth 1878 \u2013 1951| work= www.lostrailwayswestyorkshire.co.uk|accessdate=18 January 2013}}</ref> the [[Cawood, Wistow and Selby Light Railway]] in 1960, the [[Selby to Goole Line]] in 1964, and [[Leeds to Wetherby Line]] from Cross Gates station also in 1964.<ref name=\"leedswethe\"/>\n\nHambleton station closed in 1959 and Osmondthorpe station in 1960.<ref name=\"lner\"/> [[East Garforth railway station]] opened in 1987.\n\nThe land north of Gascoigne Wood station was used as a marshalling yard until 1959.<ref name=\"kh\"/> The site was later used in the 1970s<ref>{{cite news| url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/october/29/newsid_2467000/2467783.stm| title= 1976: Duchess opens massive Selby coalfield| work = On This Day| publisher = BBC|accessdate=12 August 2010}}</ref> as the point at which coal from the collieries of the [[Selby Coalfield]] was brought to the surface.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://pamelaross.co.uk/gascoigne_wood_mine.htm | title = Gascoigne Wood Mine | work = pamelaross.co.uk | accessdate = 18 January 2013 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120310114421/http://pamelaross.co.uk/gascoigne_wood_mine.htm | archive-date = 10 March 2012 | url-status = dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.abandoned-britain.com/PP/gascoignewood/1.htm | title = Gascoigne Wood Mine| work = www.abandoned-britain.com|accessdate=18 January 2013}}</ref> {{#tag:ref|The last mine in the coalfield closed in 2004.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.selbytimes.co.uk/selby-news/END-OF-AN-ERA.877649.jp | archive-url = https://archive.today/20120912143939/http://www.selbytimes.co.uk/selby-news/END-OF-AN-ERA.877649.jp | url-status = dead | archive-date = 12 September 2012 | title = End of an era | date = 27 October 2004 | work = Selby Times | accessdate = 12 August 2010 }}</ref> The site is now a business park and in 2008 was used to store [[gypsum]] produced at coal burning power stations as part of the [[flue gas desulphurisation|desulphurisation process]].<ref>{{cite news| url = http://www.selbytimes.co.uk/district-news/Gascoigne-Wood-mine-building-gets.4757200.jp| archive-url = https://archive.today/20120912165152/http://www.selbytimes.co.uk/district-news/Gascoigne-Wood-mine-building-gets.4757200.jp| url-status = dead| archive-date = 12 September 2012| title = Gascoigne Wood mine building gets new lease of life| date = 3 December 2008| work = Selby Times| accessdate = 12 August 2010}}</ref>|group=\"note\"}}\n\nThe [[Selby Diversion]] of the [[East Coast Main Line]] opened in 1983, passing under the Leeds-Selby Line between South Milford and Selby; junctions were made between the two lines allowing running from York onto the Leeds-Selby eastwards, and from the south onto the line travelling westwards to Leeds.\n\n== Electrification ==\nThe line from Leeds Central station to Neville Hill depot was electrified in the early 1990s as a corollary to the [[East Coast Main Line]] electrification project.<ref>{{cite web| title = Electrification of the East Coast Main Line: Project Completion Certificate| url = http://www.railwaysarchive.co.uk/docsummary.php?docID=853| at = ''section'' 1.b.ii, p.3; Appendix A, sheet 3, A.2.1.vi| date= 1 March 1992| publisher = British Rail|}}</ref> The electrification was energised in March 1993.<ref>{{citation| title = Electric Railway Society Journal| volume = 38\u201339| page = 97}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, as part of its franchise offer, the train operating [[Great North Eastern Railway|Great North Eastern Railway (GNER)]] proposed to electrify the section of the line between Leeds and Hambleton junction in association with [[Network Rail]], at an estimated cost of \u00a370 million.<ref>{{cite web| title = GNER wins second franchise term| date = 1 May 2005 | url = http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/single-view/view/gner-wins-second-franchise-term.html| work = www.railwaygazette.com|}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050323090129/http://www.sra.gov.uk/news/2005/3/ICEC| url=http://www.sra.gov.uk/news/2005/3/ICEC| archivedate = 23 March 2005| date = 22 March 2005| publisher = Strategic Rail Authority| title = Biggest Deal in European Rail History Marks East Coast Franchise Announcement|}}</ref> GNER lost the franchise in December 2006 before undertaking the electrification work.<ref group=\"note\">The [[Department for Transport]] ended GNER's franchise due to financial problems, including the insolvency of its parent company Sea Containers; see [[Great North Eastern Railway|GNER]], and [[Sea Containers]]</ref>\n\nIn 2009 the Network Rail route utilisation strategy electrification paper identified the North Cross-Pennine route including the Leeds-Selby-Hull Line as a high ranking option for future electrification, in terms of benefits to passenger services.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.networkrail.co.uk/networkrus_electrification.pdf| title = Network RUS Electrification| date = October 2009| publisher = Network Rail| at = Fig. 5.1 'Gaps', p.44; Table 6.5, p.66| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141012195531/http://www.networkrail.co.uk/networkrus_electrification.pdf| archivedate = 12 October 2014| df = dmy-all}}</ref> In 2011 funding for the electrification in CP5 (see [[Network Rail Control Periods]]) of the section from Leeds to Micklefield was announced.<ref>{{cite web| url  =http://www.railnews.co.uk/news/general/2011/12/16-electrification-york-is-in-and.html| title = Electrification: Leeds-York is in, and more could follow| date = 16 November 2011| work = www.railnews.co.uk| quote = ''From the other side of Leeds, the wires would be installed from Neville West Junction to Colton Junction, which is south of York on the already-electrified East Coast Main Line''|}}</ref>{{#tag:ref|The scheme also included the section of line from Mickefield to Church Fenton on the former [[York and North Midland Railway|York and North Midland]] track, and the line from Church Fenton to the ECML at Colton junction.<ref name=\"cp5elec1\">{{cite web| url  =https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/high-level-output-specification-2012| title = The High Level Output Specification 2012| date = 16 July 2012|at=[https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/3645/map-schemes-already-committed.pdf Map featuring HLOS schemes already committed]}}</ref>|group=\"note\"}} Funding for the section of the line from Micklefield to Selby was added to the electrification schedule in 2013.<ref name=\"cp5elec3\">{{cite web| url  =https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/high-level-output-specification-2012| title = The High Level Output Specification 2012| date = 16 July 2012|at=[https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/3641/railways-act-2005.pdf The High Level Output Specification (HLOS) 2012: Railways Act 2005 statement. ''Section'' 42; also 4, 33]}}</ref>\n\n== Popular culture ==\nIn the song \"Poor Paddy\" by [[The Pogues]], this railway is mentioned in the verse for 1843:<blockquote>''In eighteen hundred and forty three,<br>I broke my shovel across me knee;<br>I went to work for the company,<br> on the Leeds and Selby Railway.''</blockquote>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Neville Hill depot]], rolling stock and locomotive depot on the line near Osmondthorpe, Leeds\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=\"note\"}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n* {{citation|title=The North Eastern Railway|first= Cecil J. |last = Allen|year= 1974}}\n* {{citation| title = Railway practice: A collection of working plans and practical details of construction in the public works of the most celebrated engineers ...| authorlink=Samuel Charles Brees|first= Samuel Charles|last= Brees}}\n** {{citation| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=5KghAAAAMAAJ |title=First Series|edition =3| publisher= J. Williams and Co.|year= 1847}}, including illustrative plates\n** {{citation| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=nstanKmFJIUC |title = First, Second, Third and Fourth Series| publisher= E.& F.N. Spon, R. Griffin & Co.|year= 1859}}, without the illustrative plates\n* {{citation| title = Appendix to Railway Practice, containing a copious abstract of the whole of the evidence given upon the London and Birmingham and Great Western Railway Bills...|year = 1839| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=caohAAAAMAAJ | authorlink=Samuel Charles Brees |first=Samuel Charles|last = Brees}}\n* {{citation|title = A Regional History of the Railways of Great Britain, Volume 4: The North East| authorlink=Ken Hoole| first = Ken |last = Hoole|year = 1986}}\n* {{citation|