Isa Guha]]\n|}\n{| style=\"text-align: center; width: 60%;\" class=wikitable\n|+ [[New Zealand women's national cricket team|New Zealand]] bowling\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Bowling (cricket)|Bowler]]\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Over (cricket)|Overs]]\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Over (cricket)|Maidens]]\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Run (cricket)|Runs]]\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Wicket]]s\n! scope=\"col\" | [[Economy rate (cricket)|Economy]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Sophie Devine]] \n| 9 || 0 || 30 || 0 || 3.33\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Kate Pulford]] \n| 3 || 0 || 17 || 0 || 5.66\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Nicola Browne]] \n| 7 || 1 || 24 || 0 || 3.42\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Suzie Bates]] \n| 4.1 || 0 || 21 || 0 || 5.04\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Lucy Doolan]] \n| 10 || 4 || 23 || 3 || 2.30\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Sarah Tsukigawa]] \n| 4 || 1 || 23 || 0 || 5.75\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal; text-align: left;\" | [[Aimee Watkins|Aimee Mason]] \n| 9 || 0 || 28 || 2 || 3.11\n|}\n\n'''Match officials'''\n* On-field [[umpire (cricket)|umpires]]: [[Steve Davis (umpire)|Steve Davis]] and [[Brian Jerling]]\n* [[Third umpire]]: [[Tyron Wijewardene]]\n* [[Match referee]]: [[Brian Aldridge (cricketer)|Brian Aldridge]]\n* [[Fourth umpire|Reserve umpire]]: [[Jeff Brookes]]\n\n'''Key'''\n* {{asterisk}} \u2013 [[Captain (cricket)|Captain]]\n* {{dagger}} \u2013 [[Wicket-keeper]]\n* c ''Fielder'' \u2013 Indicates that the batter was dismissed by a catch by the named [[Fielding (cricket)|fielder]]\n* b ''Bowler'' \u2013 Indicates which [[Bowling (cricket)|bowler]] gains credit for the dismissal\n* lbw \u2013 Indicates the batter was dismissed [[leg before wicket]]\n* st \u2013 Indicates the batter was [[stumped]]\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe ICC awarded England US$45,000 for their cup win, while New Zealand received $25,000.<ref name=\"tears\"/> Shaw, who had not expected to play, said after the match; \"I started the day crying, I finished it crying, but we won a World Cup in between\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2009/mar/23/women-england-cricket-world-cup |title=England win the World Cup |last=Booth |first=Lawrence |author-link=Lawrence Booth (cricket writer) |work=The Guardian |date=23 March 2009 |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> New Zealand's captain, Tiffen, reflected after the match, \"Maybe there were some nerves in amongst the camp. We didn't hype it up to be anything more than another day at the office, unfortunately it was a bad day at the office.\"<ref name=\"tears\"/> The team of the tournament included seven finalists: England's Edwards was selected as captain, and was joined by teammates Brunt, Marsh, Claire Taylor and Sarah Taylor. Bates and Pulford represented New Zealand in the team, while Devine was named as the team's twelfth woman. Claire Taylor, who finished the tournament as the leading run-scorer, was named as the player of the tournament.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wwc2009/content/story/396488.html |title=Five England players in World Cup XI |website=ESPNcricinfo |date=23 March 2009 |accessdate=9 April 2012}}</ref> The month after the final, Taylor became the first woman to be selected as one of [[Wisden Cricketers of the Year|''Wisden's'' Cricketers of the Year]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/international/england/5096209/Claire-Taylor-the-first-woman-to-be-named-among-the-Wisden-Cricketers-of-the-Year.html |title=Claire Taylor the first woman to be named among the Wisden Cricketers of the Year |last=Berry |first=Scyld |authorlink=Scyld Berry |work=The Daily Telegraph |publisher=Telegraph Media Group |location=London |date=3 April 2009 |accessdate=9 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe England team flew back to the United Kingdom in [[economy class]]; Mitchell highlighted the contrast with the [[England cricket team|England men's team]], who \"fly business as standard\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/tms/2009/03/world_champions.shtml |title=World champions return home |last=Mitchell |first=Alison |author-link=Alison Mitchell |work=BBC Sport |date=24 March 2009 |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> They held a reception at Lord's in London upon their return, but the former [[Minister for Sport and Civil Society|sports minister]], [[Richard Caborn]], lamented the low-key celebrations, saying that \"I would have a Number 10 reception, a reception at the House of Commons, and, at the appropriate time, in the Lords.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2009/mar/25/england-womens-world-cup-winners |title=England women's cricket team bring back the cup \u2013 and the pride |last=Gibson |first=Owen |work=The Guardian |date=25 March 2009 |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe two sides met again three months later to contest the final of the [[2009 ICC Women's World Twenty20|2009 Women's World Twenty20]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wwt202009/engine/match/355990.html |title=Final: England Women v New Zealand Women at Lord's, Jun 21, 2009 |website=ESPNcricinfo |date=9 April 2012}}</ref> England once again won the contest, and in doing so became the first team of either gender to be champions in all three cricketing formats: [[Women's Test cricket|Test]], [[Women's One Day International|One Day International]] and [[Women's Twenty20 International|Twenty20]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wwt202009/content/story/409994.html |title=All-conquering England take title |last=Narayanan |first=Nishi |website=ESPNcricinfo |date=21 June 2009 |accessdate=9 April 2012}}</ref> Each of the top four in the 2009 tournament automatically qualified for the [[2013 Women's Cricket World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.rediff.com/cricket/report/kiwi-bates-does-a-sehwag-world-cup/20090319.htm |title=Kiwi Bates does a Sehwag in World Cup |work=[[Rediff.com]] |date=19 March 2009 |accessdate=9 February 2015}}</ref> Neither England nor New Zealand reached the final of that tournament, but instead met in the third-place playoff, which England won by four wickets.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sports.ndtv.com/icc-womens-world-cup/news/203626-charlotte-edwards-guides-england-to-third-spot-in-womens-world-cup |title=Charlotte Edwards guides England to third spot in Women's World Cup |agency=Press Trust of India |publisher=[[NDTV]] |date=15 February 2013 |accessdate=9 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Women's Cricket World Cup}}\n{{2009 Women's Cricket World Cup}}\n{{England women's cricket team}}\n{{New Zealand women's national cricket team}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n[[Category:2008\u201309 Australian women's cricket season|World Cup]]\n[[Category:2009 in English women's cricket|World Cup]]\n[[Category:2009 in New Zealand cricket|World Cup]]\n[[Category:2009 in New Zealand women's sport|cricket]]\n[[Category:2009 Women's Cricket World Cup|!]]\n[[Category:England women's national cricket team matches|World Cup 2009]]\n[[Category:New Zealand women's national cricket team matches|World Cup 2009]]\n[[Category:Women's Cricket World Cup finals]]\n", "name_user": "Harrias", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRoute to the final:rem dup links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2009_Women%27s_Cricket_World_Cup_Final"}
{"title_page": "Beth Rivkah", "text_new": "{{short description|Chabad girls' school}}\n{{About|the Brooklyn girls' school|the Melbourne girls' school|Beth Rivkah Ladies College}}\n{{Chabad sidebar}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name                   = Beth Rivkah\n| image                  =\n| alt                    =\n| caption                =\n| motto                  =\n| location               = [[Brooklyn]], New York\n| country                = United States\n| coordinates            = {{Coord|40.666053|-73.949845|display=inline,title|format=dms|type:edu}}\n| established            = {{Start date|1941|df=y}}\n| opened                 =\n| closed                 =\n| type                   = [[Private school]]\n| district               =\n| grades                 = [[K-12]]\n| superintendent         =\n| principal              =\n| viceprincipal          =\n| enrollment             = 2,000<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bethrivkah.edu/templates/articlecco_cdo/aid/581923/jewish/About-Us.htm|title=About Us|publisher=Associated Beth Rivkah Schools|year=2015|access-date=22 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.collive.com/show_news.rtx?id=10263|title=Bais Rivkah Joins the Race|date=4 August 2010|access-date=22 August 2015|publisher=COLLive}}</ref>\n| faculty                =\n| campus_type            =\n| campus_size            =\n| team_name              =\n| newspaper              =\n| colors                 =\n| communities            =\n| feeders                =\n| website                = {{URL|bethrivkah.edu}}\n| footnotes              =\n}}\n\n'''Beth Rivkah''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05d1\u05d9\u05ea \u05e8\u05d1\u05e7\u05d4}}, ''Bais Rivkah'', lit. \"House of Rebecca\"), formally known as '''Associated Beth Rivkah Schools''', is a [[Private school|private]] [[Single-sex education|girls' school]] system affiliated with the [[Chabad|Chabad Lubavitch]] [[Hasidic Judaism|Hasidic]] movement. It was established in 1941 by Rabbi [[Yosef Yitzchak Schneersohn]], the sixth Lubavitcher [[Rebbe]], and developed by his son-in-law, Rabbi [[Menachem Mendel Schneerson]], the seventh Lubavitcher Rebbe. The flagship school in [[Crown Heights, Brooklyn]], includes an early childhood division, elementary school, high school, and a teacher training seminary. Other branches are located in [[Montreal|Montreal, Quebec]], Canada; [[Yerres]], France; [[Melbourne]], Australia; [[Casablanca]], Morocco; and [[Kfar Chabad]], Israel.\n\nMany Lubavitcher girls attend the Beth Rivkah school system from first through twelfth grades. Students at the one- to two-year, post-high-school teacher training seminary have the option of earning a teaching certificate, which can be used in both Chabad and non-Chabad Jewish schools.{{sfn|Fishkoff|2009|page=244}}{{sfn|Aiken|2009|p=361}}\n\n== Name ==\nThe sixth Lubavitcher Rebbe named Beth Rivkah after his grandmother, [[Rebbetzin]] Rivkah Schneersohn, wife of the fourth Lubavitcher Rebbe, Rabbi [[Shmuel Schneersohn]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://crownheights.info/chabad-news/421557/bais-rivkah-marks-100th-yahrzeit-of-namesake-2/|title= Bais Rivkah Marks 100th Yahrzeit of Namesake|date=17 January 2014|access-date=18 August 2015|work=crownheights.info}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UWTHAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT15 |title=Where Did Bais Rivkah Get Its Name?|first=Miriam|last=Smetana|journal=Nshei Chabad Newsletter|date=January 2014|isbn=9781311826992}}</ref>\n\n== Location ==\nBeth Rivkah of Crown Heights is spread over two campuses. The early childhood center (including a [[Head Start Program]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nycprivateschoolsblog.com/private-schools/focus-on-beth-rivkah-preschool/03/24/2014/|title=Focus On Beth Rivkah Preschool|date=24 March 2014|access-date=18 August 2015|publisher=NYC Private Schools Blog|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304055839/http://nycprivateschoolsblog.com/private-schools/focus-on-beth-rivkah-preschool/03/24/2014/|archive-date=4 March 2016}}</ref>) and elementary school are located at Campus Chomesh at 470 Lefferts Avenue. The high school, teacher training seminary, and administrative offices are located at 310 Crown Street.<ref name=postpone>{{cite web |url=http://www.collive.com/show_news.rtx?id=31833|title=Bais Rivkah Postpones First Day|date=1 September 2014|access-date=18 August 2015|work=COLLive}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe Beth Rivkah elementary school for girls was established by Rabbi Yosef Yitzchok Schneersohn in [[Brooklyn]], New York, in 1941, two years after he founded the first boys' [[yeshiva]] in that city. The initial enrollment of about 30 students met in a rented storefront.{{sfn|Fishkoff|2009|page=242}}{{sfn|Morris|2012|p=39}} The high school was established in 1955, and the teacher training seminary opened in Crown Heights in 1960.{{sfn|Fishkoff|2009|page=242}}{{sfn|Morris|2012|p=40}}\n\nThe elementary and high school divisions experienced significant growth from the late 1950s to the 1970s due to the high birthrate among Lubavitcher families, and the influx of Soviet and Iranian Jewish refugees to New York City.{{sfn|Morris|2012|p=40}} By the early 1980s, enrollment exceeded 600 students.{{sfn|Morris|2012|p=43}}\n\nIn 1988 the seventh Lubavitcher Rebbe presided at a groundbreaking ceremony for Campus Chomesh, which he established as a memorial to his Rebbetzin, [[Chaya Mushka Schneerson]], who had died that year. The four-story, {{convert|125,000|sqft}} campus occupies the site of the former Lefferts General Hospital and two adjacent structures, covering nearly one city block.{{sfn|Morris|2012|p=43}} The campus accommodates over 2,000 students with close to 100 classrooms, as well as science labs, computer centers, libraries, a sports gymnasium, and a rooftop playground.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bethrivkah.edu/templates/articlecco_cdo/aid/581928/jewish/Our-Building.htm|title=Our Building|publisher=Associated Beth Rivkah Schools|year=2015|access-date=18 August 2015}}</ref> Philanthropist [[Ronald Perelman]] provided nearly half of the $15 million funding for the campus, which opened in 1995.{{sfn|Fishkoff|2009|page=249}}<ref name=daily/>\n\n== Curriculum ==\nSchool is in session six days a week, excluding [[Shabbat]] (Saturday), with a half-day scheduled on Fridays to accommodate Shabbat preparations.{{sfn|Morris|2012|p=40}} The school day runs from 9 am to 4 pm, with a half-hour break for lunch.{{sfn|Fishkoff|2009|page=250}} Judaic studies \u2013 including Bible, [[Midrash]], [[Halakha|Jewish law]], Jewish history, [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]], [[Yiddish language|Yiddish]], and the writings of the Chabad Rebbes \u2013 are taught in the mornings. Secular subjects such as English, mathematics, geography, science, and American history are taught in the afternoons.{{sfn|Morris|2012|p=40}}{{sfn|Fishkoff|2009|page=250}} While in previous decades the language of instruction was Yiddish, the school now teaches religious subjects in Hebrew and secular subjects in English. Yiddish is taught as a second language.{{sfn|Fishkoff|2009|page=249}} An optional Yiddish track is offered in first grade.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.shturem.org/index.php?section=news&id=24837|title=Yiddish Still Spoken Here|first=R. C.|last=Berman|date=3 April 2008|publisher=shturem.org|access-date=18 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs a private school certified by the State of New York, Beth Rivkah is required to teach science (biology and chemistry), history (U.S. and world history), English literature, and mathematics (algebra, geometry, and trigonometry), among other subjects.{{sfn|Fishkoff|2009|page=253}} For fifth-grade science and sixth-grade world history, however, Chabad educators eschew state-mandated booklets and textbooks and instead use material that they collect from a variety of sources in order to comply with the Hasidic movement's religious beliefs. In high school, where students are required by the New York Board of Regents to study from specific textbooks, teachers append their own notations to pages describing theories such as the [[Big Bang]] and [[evolution]] to inform students of the [[Torah]] point of view on these topics.{{sfn|Fishkoff|2009|page=254}} Novels read in English literature classes are also vetted for compliance with Chabad philosophy and religious belief.{{sfn|Fishkoff|2009|page=254-255}}\n\nBeth Rivkah teachers employ pedagogical techniques such as \"group work, cooperative learning, and multiple-intelligence methods\", and attend both regional and national workshops sponsored by Chabad to improve their pedagogical methods.{{sfn|Fishkoff|2009|page=251}}\n\n== Summer camp ==\nThe Crown Heights school runs a 7-week day camp on the premises each summer for preschool through seventh grade. The camp is divided into three divisions: Kiddie Camp (Pre-1A), Younger Division (Grades 1 and 2) and Older Division (Grades 3 through 7).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bethrivkah.edu/templates/articlecco_cdo/aid/707682/jewish/Day-Camp.htm|title=Bais Rivkah Day Camp|publisher=Associated Beth Rivkah Schools|year=2015|access-date=18 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150815082849/http://www.bethrivkah.edu/templates/articlecco_cdo/aid/707682/jewish/Day-Camp.htm|archive-date=2015-08-15|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://crownheights.info/camp-news/481003/bais-rivkah-day-camp-announces-head-staff/|title=Bais Rivkah Day Camp Announces Head Staff|date=23 April 2015|access-date=18 August 2015|publisher=crownheights.info}}</ref>\n\n== Student body ==\nBeth Rivkah accepts all students regardless of religious affiliation or educational background.<ref name=sarna/><ref name=quebec/> It also accepts students who cannot afford full [[Tuition payments|tuition]].<ref name=postpone/><ref name=cjn/> The school has weathered financial shortfalls due to its tuition policy.<ref name=postpone/> In September 2014 the Pre-1A, elementary and high school divisions did not open on time for the fall semester due to financial difficulties; the early childhood center, which is government-funded, was not affected.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chabadinfo.com/crown_heights/breaking-news-bais-rivkah-will-not-open/|title=Breaking News: Bais Rivkah Will Not Open|date=2 September 2014|access-date=20 August 2014|publisher=chabadinfo.com}}</ref>\n\nBeth Rivkah has a dress code. In addition to a school uniform, jewelry and grooming guidelines are enforced in accordance with the laws of ''[[tzniut]]'' (modesty).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bethrivkah.edu/media/pdf/840/uaTY8403867.pdf |title=Respect for Torah Values \u2013 Respect Yourself: Dress Code|publisher=Associated Beth Rivkah Schools|access-date=20 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, the Crown Heights school ordered students to delete their [[Facebook]] accounts or face expulsion.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.algemeiner.com/2012/03/23/brooklyn-girls-school-bans-facebook/#|title=Brooklyn Girls School Bans Facebook|date=23 March 2012|access-date=18 August 2015|work=[[Algemeiner Journal]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2012/03/28/report-brooklyn-high-school-students-told-to-delete-facebook-profiles/|title=Beis Rivkah High School Students Told To Delete Facebook Profiles|date=28 March 2012|access-date=18 August 2015|work=CBS New York}}</ref>\n\nSince many girls are named Chaya Mushka after [[Chaya Mushka Schneerson|the Rebbetzin]] of the seventh Lubavitcher Rebbe, teachers call on students by their [[surname]]s.{{sfn|Fishkoff|2009|page=251}}<ref name=daily>{{cite web |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/boroughs/school-hails-schneerson-article-1.679081|title=School Hails a Schneerson|first=Joyce|last=Shelby|date=28 March 1995|access-date=20 August 2015|work=[[New York Daily News]]}}</ref>\n\n== Branches ==\nThe seventh Lubavitcher Rebbe, Rabbi Menachem Mendel Schneerson, founded other branches of Beth Rivkah in [[Yerres]], France; [[Montreal|Montreal, Quebec]], Canada; [[Melbourne]], Australia; [[Casablanca]], [[Meknes]], and [[Sefrou]], Morocco; and [[Kfar Chabad]], Israel in the 1940s and 1950s.{{sfn|Schneersohn|Schneerson|2005|p=A-42}} By 1967, there were 98 Beth Rivkah schools worldwide, with an enrollment of 40,000 students.<ref name=sarna>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=883&dat=19670721&id=p6haAAAAIBAJ&sjid=wUsDAAAAIBAJ&pg=1093,5551185&hl=en|title=Beth Rivkah Academy Opens Doors in Fall|first=Aaron|last=Sarna|date=14 July 1967 |newspaper=[[Canadian Jewish Review|Canadian Jewish Chronicle Review]]|page=12}}</ref>\n\n=== Yerres, France ===\nThe Beth Rivkah school in the [[Paris]] neighborhood of [[Yerres]] opened in 1947.<ref name=yerres>{{cite web |url=http://www.mobile.collive.com/show_news.rtx?id=23808&hl=beth+rivkah|title=Beth Rikvah Holds Gala Dinner|date=13 January 2013|access-date=21 August 2015|work=COLLive}}</ref> It consists of an early childhood division, elementary school, high school, and seminary for girls. There is also a [[cheder]] for boys. As of 2015, total enrollment is 600 students.<ref name=yerres/>\n\n=== Montreal ===\nBeth Rivkah Academy of [[Montreal]] opened in 1956.<ref name=quebec/><ref name=academy/> In 1967 it opened a facility for 500 students, with dormitory accommodations for 180.<ref name=sarna/> As of 2015, enrollment in the early childhood division, elementary school, and high school is 600 students aged 18 months to 18 years.<ref name=quebec>{{cite web |url=http://crownheights.info/chabad-news/458408/beth-rivkah-ranked-2nd-best-jewish-school-in-quebec/|title=Beth Rivkah Ranked 2nd Best Jewish School in Quebec|date=11 November 2014|access-date=18 August 2015|publisher=crownheights.info}}</ref> Approximately 10 percent of students are immigrants, and there is a significant percentage of special-needs students in the elementary and high school divisions.<ref name=cjn>{{cite web|url=http://www.cjnews.com/node/82131|title=Second study finds Beth Rivkah lowest-ranked|first=Janice|last=Arnold|date=13 November 2008|access-date=22 August 2015|work=[[Canadian Jewish News]]}}</ref> In addition to providing religious and secular studies, the academy is an accredited French-language school.<ref name=quebec/><ref name=academy>{{cite web |url=http://www.bethrivkah.com/templates/articlecco_cdo/aid/1048001/jewish/ABOUT-US.htm|title=About Us|publisher=Beth Rivkah Academy of Montreal|year=2015|access-date=20 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Melbourne ===\n{{Main|Beth Rivkah Ladies College}}\nThe [[Beth Rivkah Ladies College]] in [[Melbourne]], [[Australia]] was established in 1956.{{sfn|Lubin|1983|p=37}}<ref name=insider>{{cite web |url= http://www.businessinsider.com.au/cheat-sheet-10-of-the-best-private-schools-for-girls-in-melbourne-2015-6#4 |title= CHEAT SHEET: 10 of the best private schools for girls in Melbourne|first=Sarah|last=Kimmorley|date=25 June 2015|access-date=22 August 2015|work=[[Business Insider|Business Insider Australia]]}}</ref> Part of the [[Yeshivah Centre, Melbourne|Yeshivah Centre]] educational network, which includes the [[Yeshivah College, Australia|Yeshivah College]] for boys founded in 1954,{{sfn|Lubin|1983|p=37}} the Beth Rikvah Ladies College consists of a preschool, elementary school, and high school for girls. A sister school, [[Ohel Chana]], is a teacher training seminary. Both Beth Rivkah and Yeshivah College enroll students from non-Chabad families.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dro.deakin.edu.au/eserv/DU:30060273/benmoshe-barbatmitzvah-2013.pdf|title=Bar/Bat Mitzvah Programs and Jewish Identities: An Australian Case Study|first=Danny|last=Ben-Moshe|year=2013|publisher=Sociological Institute for Community Studies, [[Bar Ilan University]]|volume=17}}</ref> In 2014 the educational network made headlines by capping tuition fees at 8% of family income for low wage-earners and 18% for high wage-earners, notwithstanding how many children in the family are enrolled in the schools.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jewishnews.net.au/jewish-schools-too-expensive-not-any-more/37672|title=Jewish Schools Too Expensive? Not Any More|date=18 September 2014|access-date=22 August 2015|first=Zeddy|last=Lawrence|work=[[Australian Jewish News]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mobile.collive.com/show_news.rtx?id=32075|title=Melbourne School Caps Tuition Fee|date=19 September 2014|access-date=22 August 2015|work=COLLive}}</ref>\n\n=== Morocco ===\nBeth Rivkah schools were established in [[Casablanca]], [[Meknes]], and [[Sefrou]], Morocco, in the mid-1950s. According to a 1956 survey, these schools had a combined enrollment of 374 students that year.{{sfn|Laskier|2012|p=250}} With the [[migration of Moroccan Jews to Israel]] and France in the 1950s, the Lubavitch yeshiva for boys, Oholei Yosef Yitzchok, and the Beth Rivkah school for girls were centered in Casablanca and dormitory facilities were opened to accommodate students from other locales.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chabadalberta.org/templates/articlecco_cdo/aid/1328703/jewish/-Moroccan-Government-sends-Condolences-to-the-Matusof-Family.htm|title=Moroccan Government sends Condolences to the Matusof Family|year=2010|access-date=22 August 2015|publisher=Chabad Lubavitch of Alberta}}</ref> By 1980, the Beth Rivkah school had some 300 students.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.toviapreschel.com/casablanca/|title=Casablanca|first=Tovia|last=Preschel|date=11 April 1980|work=[[The Jewish Press]]|access-date=22 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Israel ===\nThe Beit Rivkah College in Kfar Chabad, Israel, opened in 1957.<ref name=rivka/> Originally a teacher training institute, it evolved into a two-year seminary and then a teachers college which bestows both B.A. and M.A. degrees. As of 2010, enrollment was 1,000 students in Kfar Chabad and in branches in [[Jerusalem]] and [[Safed]].<ref name=rivka>{{cite web|url=http://www.rivka.org.il/pages/22.aspx|title=About the College|publisher=Beit Rikva|year=2010|access-date=18 August 2015|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150606130512/http://www.rivka.org.il/pages/22.aspx|archive-date=6 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Bais Chana Women International]]\n* [[Bais Yaakov #Hasidic schools]] \n* [[Midrasha]]\n* [[Role of women in Judaism]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* {{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Btma22BvWEoC&pg=PA361|title=The Baal Teshuva Survival Guide|first=Lisa|last=Aiken|year=2009|publisher=Rossi Publications|isbn=978-0977962938|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4R7zbndjTRgC |title=The Rebbe's Army: Inside the World of Chabad-Lubavitch|first=Sue|last=Fishkoff|publisher= Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group|year=2009|isbn= 978-0307566140|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=xxZE3-K3AR4C&pg=PA250 |title=The Alliance Israelite Universelle and the Jewish Communities of Morocco, 1862\u20131962|first= Michael M. |last=Laskier|publisher=SUNY Press|year=2012|isbn= 978-1438410166|page=250|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|title=Jewish Schooling and Jewish Education in Melbourne|first=Chaim|last=Lubin|journal=Journal of Jewish Education|year=1983|volume=51|issue=2|pages=37\u201342|doi=10.1080/0021642830510212|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4vnW76KGHncC&pg=PA40 |title=Lubavitcher Women in America: Identity and Activism in the Postwar Era|first=Bonnie J.|last=Morris|year=2012|publisher=SUNY Press|isbn=978-1438413662|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=T4ARAQAAIAAJ&dq=bais+rivkah+chabad&q=bais+rivkah|title=HaYom Yom...\"From Day to Day\"|publisher=Kehot|year=2005|page=A-42|edition=18th|isbn=978-0826606693|last1=Schneersohn|first1=Yosef Yitzchak|authorlink1=Yosef Yitzchak Schneersohn|last2=Schneerson|first2=Menachem Mendel|authorlink2=Menachem Mendel Schneerson|ref=harv}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.bethrivkah.edu/ Associated Beth Rivkah Schools home page]\n* [http://www.bethrivkah.fr/ Les Institutions Beth Rivkah (France) home page]\n* [http://www.bethrivkah.com/?lang=en Beth Rivkah Academy of Montreal home page]\n* [http://www.ybr.vic.edu.au/ Yeshivah-Beth Rivka Colleges (Australia) home page]\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=W2rYAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA110 \"Simchas Beis Hasho'eva in Crown Heights: Rehearsing for the ultimate simcha among the Lubavitcher chassidim\", pp. 110\u2013122]\n* [http://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/real-life/how-brooklyn-girl-chanie-gorkins-poem-became-a-global-sensation/story-fnq2o7hp-1227457186251 \"How Brooklyn girl Chanie Gorkin's poem became a global sensation\"] news.com.au, July 26, 2015\u201308\u201320\n\n{{Chabad}}\n{{Girls' schools in New York City}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Beth Rivkah}}\n[[Category:Chabad schools]]\n[[Category:Private high schools in Queens, New York]]\n[[Category:Girls' schools in New York City]]\n[[Category:Orthodox Jewish schools for women]]\n[[Category:Jewish schools in the United States]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1941]]\n[[Category:Private middle schools in Queens, New York]]\n[[Category:Private elementary schools in Queens, New York]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Chabad girls' school}}\n{{About|the Brooklyn girls' school|the Melbourne girls' school|Beth Rivkah Ladies College}}\n{{Chabad sidebar}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name                   = Beth Rivkah\n| image                  =\n| alt                    =\n| caption                =\n| motto                  =\n| location               = [[Brooklyn]], New York\n| country                = United States\n| coordinates            = {{Coord|40.666053|-73.949845|display=inline,title|format=dms|type:edu}}\n| established            = {{Start date|1941|df=y}}\n| opened                 =\n| closed                 =\n| type                   = [[Private school]]\n| district               =\n| grades                 = [[K-12]]\n| superintendent         =\n| principal              =\n| viceprincipal          =\n| enrollment             = 2,000<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bethrivkah.edu/templates/articlecco_cdo/aid/581923/jewish/About-Us.htm|title=About Us|publisher=Associated Beth Rivkah Schools|year=2015|access-date=22 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.collive.com/show_news.rtx?id=10263|title=Bais Rivkah Joins the Race|date=4 August 2010|access-date=22 August 2015|publisher=COLLive}}</ref>\n| faculty                =\n| campus_type            =\n| campus_size            =\n| team_name              =\n| newspaper              =\n| colors                 =\n| communities            =\n| feeders                =\n| website                = {{URL|bethrivkah.edu}}\n| footnotes              =\n}}\n\n'''Beth Rivkah''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05d1\u05d9\u05ea \u05e8\u05d1\u05e7\u05d4}}, ''Bais Rivkah'', lit. \"House of Rebecca\"), formally known as '''Associated Beth Rivkah Schools''', is a [[Private school|private]] [[Single-sex education|girls' school]] system affiliated with the [[Chabad|Chabad Lubavitch]] [[Hasidic Judaism|Hasidic]] movement. It was established in 1941 by Rabbi [[Yosef Yitzchak Schneersohn]], the sixth Lubavitcher [[Rebbe]], and developed by his son-in-law, Rabbi [[Menachem Mendel Schneerson]], the seventh Lubavitcher Rebbe. The flagship school in [[Crown Heights, Brooklyn]], includes an early childhood division, elementary school, high school, and a teacher training seminary. Other branches are located in [[Montreal|Montreal, Quebec]], Canada; [[Yerres]], France; [[Melbourne]], Australia; [[Casablanca]], Morocco; and [[Kfar Chabad]], Israel.\n\nMany Lubavitcher girls attend the Beth Rivkah school system from first through twelfth grades. Students at the one- to two-year, post-high-school teacher training seminary have the option of earning a teaching certificate, which can be used in both Chabad and non-Chabad Jewish schools.{{sfn|Fishkoff|2009|page=244}}{{sfn|Aiken|2009|p=361}}\n\n== Name ==\nThe sixth Lubavitcher Rebbe named Beth Rivkah after his grandmother, [[Rebbetzin]] Rivkah Schneersohn, wife of the fourth Lubavitcher Rebbe, Rabbi [[Shmuel Schneersohn]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://crownheights.info/chabad-news/421557/bais-rivkah-marks-100th-yahrzeit-of-namesake-2/|title= Bais Rivkah Marks 100th Yahrzeit of Namesake|date=17 January 2014|access-date=18 August 2015|work=crownheights.info}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UWTHAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT15 |title=Where Did Bais Rivkah Get Its Name?|first=Miriam|last=Smetana|journal=Nshei Chabad Newsletter|date=January 2014|isbn=9781311826992}}</ref>\n\n== Location ==\nBeth Rivkah of Crown Heights is spread over two campuses. The early childhood center (including a [[Head Start Program]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nycprivateschoolsblog.com/private-schools/focus-on-beth-rivkah-preschool/03/24/2014/|title=Focus On Beth Rivkah Preschool|date=24 March 2014|access-date=18 August 2015|publisher=NYC Private Schools Blog|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304055839/http://nycprivateschoolsblog.com/private-schools/focus-on-beth-rivkah-preschool/03/24/2014/|archive-date=4 March 2016}}</ref>) and elementary school are located at Campus Chomesh at 470 Lefferts Avenue. The high school, teacher training seminary, and administrative offices are located at 310 Crown Street.<ref name=postpone>{{cite web |url=http://www.collive.com/show_news.rtx?id=31833|title=Bais Rivkah Postpones First Day|date=1 September 2014|access-date=18 August 2015|work=COLLive}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe Beth Rivkah elementary school for girls was established by Rabbi Yosef Yitzchok Schneersohn in [[Brooklyn]], New York, in 1941, two years after he founded the first boys' [[yeshiva]] in that city. The initial enrollment of about 30 students met in a rented storefront.{{sfn|Fishkoff|2009|page=242}}{{sfn|Morris|2012|p=39}} The high school was established in 1955, and the teacher training seminary opened in Crown Heights in 1960.{{sfn|Fishkoff|2009|page=242}}{{sfn|Morris|2012|p=40}}\n\nThe elementary and high school divisions experienced significant growth from the late 1950s to the 1970s due to the high birthrate among Lubavitcher families, and the influx of Soviet and Iranian Jewish refugees to New York City.{{sfn|Morris|2012|p=40}} By the early 1980s, enrollment exceeded 600 students.{{sfn|Morris|2012|p=43}}\n\nIn 1988 the seventh Lubavitcher Rebbe presided at a groundbreaking ceremony for Campus Chomesh, which he established as a memorial to his Rebbetzin, [[Chaya Mushka Schneerson]], who had died that year. The four-story, {{convert|125,000|sqft}} campus occupies the site of the former Lefferts General Hospital and two adjacent structures, covering nearly one city block.{{sfn|Morris|2012|p=43}} The campus accommodates over 2,000 students with close to 100 classrooms, as well as science labs, computer centers, libraries, a sports gymnasium, and a rooftop playground.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bethrivkah.edu/templates/articlecco_cdo/aid/581928/jewish/Our-Building.htm|title=Our Building|publisher=Associated Beth Rivkah Schools|year=2015|access-date=18 August 2015}}</ref> Philanthropist [[Ronald Perelman]] provided nearly half of the $15 million funding for the campus, which opened in 1995.{{sfn|Fishkoff|2009|page=249}}<ref name=daily/>\n\n== Curriculum ==\nSchool is in session six days a week, excluding [[Shabbat]] (Saturday), with a half-day scheduled on Fridays to accommodate Shabbat preparations.{{sfn|Morris|2012|p=40}} The school day runs from 9 am to 4 pm, with a half-hour break for lunch.{{sfn|Fishkoff|2009|page=250}} Judaic studies \u2013 including Bible, [[Midrash]], [[Halakha|Jewish law]], Jewish history, [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]], [[Yiddish language|Yiddish]], and the writings of the Chabad Rebbes \u2013 are taught in the mornings. Secular subjects such as English, mathematics, geography, science, and American history are taught in the afternoons.{{sfn|Morris|2012|p=40}}{{sfn|Fishkoff|2009|page=250}} While in previous decades the language of instruction was Yiddish, the school now teaches religious subjects in Hebrew and secular subjects in English. Yiddish is taught as a second language.{{sfn|Fishkoff|2009|page=249}} An optional Yiddish track is offered in first grade.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.shturem.org/index.php?section=news&id=24837|title=Yiddish Still Spoken Here|first=R. C.|last=Berman|date=3 April 2008|publisher=shturem.org|access-date=18 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs a private school certified by the State of New York, Beth Rivkah is required to teach science (biology and chemistry), history (U.S. and world history), English literature, and mathematics (algebra, geometry, and trigonometry), among other subjects.{{sfn|Fishkoff|2009|page=253}} For fifth-grade science and sixth-grade world history, however, Chabad educators eschew state-mandated booklets and textbooks and instead use material that they collect from a variety of sources in order to comply with the Hasidic movement's religious beliefs. In high school, where students are required by the New York Board of Regents to study from specific textbooks, teachers append their own notations to pages describing theories such as the [[Big Bang]] and [[evolution]] to inform students of the [[Torah]] point of view on these topics.{{sfn|Fishkoff|2009|page=254}} Novels read in English literature classes are also vetted for compliance with Chabad philosophy and religious belief.{{sfn|Fishkoff|2009|page=254-255}}\n\nBeth Rivkah teachers employ pedagogical techniques such as \"group work, cooperative learning, and multiple-intelligence methods\", and attend both regional and national workshops sponsored by Chabad to improve their pedagogical methods.{{sfn|Fishkoff|2009|page=251}}\n\n== Summer camp ==\nThe Crown Heights school runs a 7-week day camp on the premises each summer for preschool through seventh grade. The camp is divided into three divisions: Kiddie Camp (Pre-1A), Younger Division (Grades 1 and 2) and Older Division (Grades 3 through 7).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bethrivkah.edu/templates/articlecco_cdo/aid/707682/jewish/Day-Camp.htm|title=Bais Rivkah Day Camp|publisher=Associated Beth Rivkah Schools|year=2015|access-date=18 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150815082849/http://www.bethrivkah.edu/templates/articlecco_cdo/aid/707682/jewish/Day-Camp.htm|archive-date=2015-08-15|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://crownheights.info/camp-news/481003/bais-rivkah-day-camp-announces-head-staff/|title=Bais Rivkah Day Camp Announces Head Staff|date=23 April 2015|access-date=18 August 2015|publisher=crownheights.info}}</ref>\n\n== Student body ==\nBeth Rivkah accepts all students regardless of religious affiliation or educational background.<ref name=sarna/><ref name=quebec/> It also accepts students who cannot afford full [[Tuition payments|tuition]].<ref name=postpone/><ref name=cjn/> The school has weathered financial shortfalls due to its tuition policy.<ref name=postpone/> In September 2014 the Pre-1A, elementary and high school divisions did not open on time for the fall semester due to financial difficulties; the early childhood center, which is government-funded, was not affected.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chabadinfo.com/crown_heights/breaking-news-bais-rivkah-will-not-open/|title=Breaking News: Bais Rivkah Will Not Open|date=2 September 2014|access-date=20 August 2014|publisher=chabadinfo.com}}</ref>\n\nBeth Rivkah has a dress code. In addition to a school uniform, jewelry and grooming guidelines are enforced in accordance with the laws of ''[[tzniut]]'' (modesty).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bethrivkah.edu/media/pdf/840/uaTY8403867.pdf |title=Respect for Torah Values \u2013 Respect Yourself: Dress Code|publisher=Associated Beth Rivkah Schools|access-date=20 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, the Crown Heights school ordered students to delete their [[Facebook]] accounts or face expulsion.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.algemeiner.com/2012/03/23/brooklyn-girls-school-bans-facebook/#|title=Brooklyn Girls School Bans Facebook|date=23 March 2012|access-date=18 August 2015|work=[[Algemeiner Journal]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2012/03/28/report-brooklyn-high-school-students-told-to-delete-facebook-profiles/|title=Beis Rivkah High School Students Told To Delete Facebook Profiles|date=28 March 2012|access-date=18 August 2015|work=CBS New York}}</ref>\n\nSince many girls are named Chaya Mushka after [[Chaya Mushka Schneerson|the Rebbetzin]] of the seventh Lubavitcher Rebbe, teachers call on students by their [[surname]]s.{{sfn|Fishkoff|2009|page=251}}<ref name=daily>{{cite web |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/boroughs/school-hails-schneerson-article-1.679081|title=School Hails a Schneerson|first=Joyce|last=Shelby|date=28 March 1995|access-date=20 August 2015|work=[[New York Daily News]]}}</ref>\n\n== Branches ==\nThe seventh Lubavitcher Rebbe, Rabbi Menachem Mendel Schneerson, founded other branches of Beth Rivkah in [[Yerres]], France; [[Montreal|Montreal, Quebec]], Canada; [[Melbourne]], Australia; [[Casablanca]], [[Meknes]], and [[Sefrou]], Morocco; and [[Kfar Chabad]], Israel in the 1940s and 1950s.{{sfn|Schneersohn|Schneerson|2005|p=A-42}} By 1967, there were 98 Beth Rivkah schools worldwide, with an enrollment of 40,000 students.<ref name=sarna>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=883&dat=19670721&id=p6haAAAAIBAJ&sjid=wUsDAAAAIBAJ&pg=1093,5551185&hl=en|title=Beth Rivkah Academy Opens Doors in Fall|first=Aaron|last=Sarna|date=14 July 1967 |newspaper=[[Canadian Jewish Review|Canadian Jewish Chronicle Review]]|page=12}}</ref>\n\n=== Yerres, France ===\nThe Beth Rivkah school in the [[Paris]] neighborhood of [[Yerres]] opened in 1947.<ref name=yerres>{{cite web |url=http://www.mobile.collive.com/show_news.rtx?id=23808&hl=beth+rivkah|title=Beth Rikvah Holds Gala Dinner|date=13 January 2013|access-date=21 August 2015|work=COLLive}}</ref> It consists of an early childhood division, elementary school, high school, and seminary for girls. There is also a [[cheder]] for boys. As of 2015, total enrollment is 600 students.<ref name=yerres/>\n\n=== Montreal ===\nBeth Rivkah Academy of [[Montreal]] opened in 1956.<ref name=quebec/><ref name=academy/> In 1967 it opened a facility for 500 students, with dormitory accommodations for 180.<ref name=sarna/> As of 2015, enrollment in the early childhood division, elementary school, and high school is 600 students aged 18 months to 18 years.<ref name=quebec>{{cite web |url=http://crownheights.info/chabad-news/458408/beth-rivkah-ranked-2nd-best-jewish-school-in-quebec/|title=Beth Rivkah Ranked 2nd Best Jewish School in Quebec|date=11 November 2014|access-date=18 August 2015|publisher=crownheights.info}}</ref> Approximately 10 percent of students are immigrants, and there is a significant percentage of special-needs students in the elementary and high school divisions.<ref name=cjn>{{cite web|url=http://www.cjnews.com/node/82131|title=Second study finds Beth Rivkah lowest-ranked|first=Janice|last=Arnold|date=13 November 2008|access-date=22 August 2015|work=[[Canadian Jewish News]]}}</ref> In addition to providing religious and secular studies, the academy is an accredited French-language school.<ref name=quebec/><ref name=academy>{{cite web |url=http://www.bethrivkah.com/templates/articlecco_cdo/aid/1048001/jewish/ABOUT-US.htm|title=About Us|publisher=Beth Rivkah Academy of Montreal|year=2015|access-date=20 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Melbourne ===\n{{Main|Beth Rivkah Ladies College}}\nThe [[Beth Rivkah Ladies College]] in [[Melbourne]], [[Australia]] was established in 1956.{{sfn|Lubin|1983|p=37}}<ref name=insider>{{cite web |url= http://www.businessinsider.com.au/cheat-sheet-10-of-the-best-private-schools-for-girls-in-melbourne-2015-6#4 |title= CHEAT SHEET: 10 of the best private schools for girls in Melbourne|first=Sarah|last=Kimmorley|date=25 June 2015|access-date=22 August 2015|work=[[Business Insider|Business Insider Australia]]}}</ref> Part of the [[Yeshivah Centre, Melbourne|Yeshivah Centre]] educational network, which includes the [[Yeshivah College, Australia|Yeshivah College]] for boys founded in 1954,{{sfn|Lubin|1983|p=37}} the Beth Rikvah Ladies College consists of a preschool, elementary school, and high school for girls. A sister school, [[Ohel Chana]], is a teacher training seminary. Both Beth Rivkah and Yeshivah College enroll students from non-Chabad families.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dro.deakin.edu.au/eserv/DU:30060273/benmoshe-barbatmitzvah-2013.pdf|title=Bar/Bat Mitzvah Programs and Jewish Identities: An Australian Case Study|first=Danny|last=Ben-Moshe|year=2013|publisher=Sociological Institute for Community Studies, [[Bar Ilan University]]|volume=17}}</ref> In 2014 the educational network made headlines by capping tuition fees at 8% of family income for low wage-earners and 18% for high wage-earners, notwithstanding how many children in the family are enrolled in the schools.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jewishnews.net.au/jewish-schools-too-expensive-not-any-more/37672|title=Jewish Schools Too Expensive? Not Any More|date=18 September 2014|access-date=22 August 2015|first=Zeddy|last=Lawrence|work=[[Australian Jewish News]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mobile.collive.com/show_news.rtx?id=32075|title=Melbourne School Caps Tuition Fee|date=19 September 2014|access-date=22 August 2015|work=COLLive}}</ref>\n\n=== Morocco ===\nBeth Rivkah schools were established in [[Casablanca]], [[Meknes]], and [[Sefrou]], Morocco, in the mid-1950s. According to a 1956 survey, these schools had a combined enrollment of 374 students that year.{{sfn|Laskier|2012|p=250}} With the [[migration of Moroccan Jews to Israel]] and France in the 1950s, the Lubavitch yeshiva for boys, Oholei Yosef Yitzchok, and the Beth Rivkah school for girls were centered in Casablanca and dormitory facilities were opened to accommodate students from other locales.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chabadalberta.org/templates/articlecco_cdo/aid/1328703/jewish/-Moroccan-Government-sends-Condolences-to-the-Matusof-Family.htm|title=Moroccan Government sends Condolences to the Matusof Family|year=2010|access-date=22 August 2015|publisher=Chabad Lubavitch of Alberta}}</ref> By 1980, the Beth Rivkah school had some 300 students.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.toviapreschel.com/casablanca/|title=Casablanca|first=Tovia|last=Preschel|date=11 April 1980|work=[[The Jewish Press]]|access-date=22 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Israel ===\nThe Beit Rivkah College in Kfar Chabad, Israel, opened in 1957.<ref name=rivka/> Originally a teacher training institute, it evolved into a two-year seminary and then a teachers college which bestows both B.A. and M.A. degrees. As of 2010, enrollment was 1,000 students in Kfar Chabad and in branches in [[Jerusalem]] and [[Safed]].<ref name=rivka>{{cite web|url=http://www.rivka.org.il/pages/22.aspx|title=About the College|publisher=Beit Rikva|year=2010|access-date=18 August 2015|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150606130512/http://www.rivka.org.il/pages/22.aspx|archive-date=6 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Role of women in Judaism]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* {{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Btma22BvWEoC&pg=PA361|title=The Baal Teshuva Survival Guide|first=Lisa|last=Aiken|year=2009|publisher=Rossi Publications|isbn=978-0977962938|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4R7zbndjTRgC |title=The Rebbe's Army: Inside the World of Chabad-Lubavitch|first=Sue|last=Fishkoff|publisher= Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group|year=2009|isbn= 978-0307566140|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=xxZE3-K3AR4C&pg=PA250 |title=The Alliance Israelite Universelle and the Jewish Communities of Morocco, 1862\u20131962|first= Michael M. |last=Laskier|publisher=SUNY Press|year=2012|isbn= 978-1438410166|page=250|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|title=Jewish Schooling and Jewish Education in Melbourne|first=Chaim|last=Lubin|journal=Journal of Jewish Education|year=1983|volume=51|issue=2|pages=37\u201342|doi=10.1080/0021642830510212|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4vnW76KGHncC&pg=PA40 |title=Lubavitcher Women in America: Identity and Activism in the Postwar Era|first=Bonnie J.|last=Morris|year=2012|publisher=SUNY Press|isbn=978-1438413662|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=T4ARAQAAIAAJ&dq=bais+rivkah+chabad&q=bais+rivkah|title=HaYom Yom...\"From Day to Day\"|publisher=Kehot|year=2005|page=A-42|edition=18th|isbn=978-0826606693|last1=Schneersohn|first1=Yosef Yitzchak|authorlink1=Yosef Yitzchak Schneersohn|last2=Schneerson|first2=Menachem Mendel|authorlink2=Menachem Mendel Schneerson|ref=harv}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.bethrivkah.edu/ Associated Beth Rivkah Schools home page]\n* [http://www.bethrivkah.fr/ Les Institutions Beth Rivkah (France) home page]\n* [http://www.bethrivkah.com/?lang=en Beth Rivkah Academy of Montreal home page]\n* [http://www.ybr.vic.edu.au/ Yeshivah-Beth Rivka Colleges (Australia) home page]\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=W2rYAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA110 \"Simchas Beis Hasho'eva in Crown Heights: Rehearsing for the ultimate simcha among the Lubavitcher chassidim\", pp. 110\u2013122]\n* [http://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/real-life/how-brooklyn-girl-chanie-gorkins-poem-became-a-global-sensation/story-fnq2o7hp-1227457186251 \"How Brooklyn girl Chanie Gorkin's poem became a global sensation\"] news.com.au, July 26, 2015\u201308\u201320\n\n{{Chabad}}\n{{Girls' schools in New York City}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Beth Rivkah}}\n[[Category:Chabad schools]]\n[[Category:Private high schools in Queens, New York]]\n[[Category:Girls' schools in New York City]]\n[[Category:Orthodox Jewish schools for women]]\n[[Category:Jewish schools in the United States]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1941]]\n[[Category:Private mid